### SNES_KB v3 / source=nintendo_dev_manual_book1+book2 + psyq_sdk + curated_knowledge
### format=snesdb_v2 (extended with prose lines)
###
### PARSING RULES
###   [SECTION:name]      = section header
###   key=value           = structured datum (atomic, single line)
###   > text              = narrative prose line (multiple consecutive > lines = paragraph)
###   # text              = comment, ignored by parsers
###   blank line          = separator
###   |                   = inside a value, separates parallel facts
###
### Hex written as $NN or 0xNN. Ranges use ".." (inclusive). Bit fields are Dn.
### Coverage: complete enough to reverse-engineer SNES hardware behavior without
### needing to consult external docs. Detailed prose attached to every critical
### topic (NMI, IRQ, DMA, HDMA, VRAM, OAM, CGRAM, Mode 7, color math, 65816 ISA,
### SPC700 ISA, cycle timing, SRAM quirks, coprocessors).

[SECTION:meta]
file_version=3
sources=nintendo_official_snes_dev_manual_book1+book2|psyq_sdk_programmers_guide_BDL3005-3|curated_hardware_knowledge_for_completeness
distilled_for=ai_system_prompt_re_hacking_homebrew_fan_translation
format=snesdb_v2_with_prose_lines
section_count=approximately_240
philosophy=detail_over_brevity|each_critical_concept_must_be_self_contained|reader_should_not_need_external_docs
> The SNES is a complex 16-bit system whose architecture combines a 65816 main
> CPU, two PPU chips that cooperate to drive video, an isolated SPC700 audio
> subsystem with its own RAM and DSP, and one of several optional in-cart
> coprocessors (DSP1, SA-1, SuperFX, etc). To understand it, you must hold three
> address spaces in your head simultaneously (CPU bus, ROM file offset, runtime
> RAM), four clock domains (master, fast CPU, slow CPU, SPC700), and the
> hard rule that PPU memory (VRAM, OAM, CGRAM) is only safely writable during
> forced blank or vertical blank. Almost every gotcha in SNES programming
> reduces to violating one of those constraints.

# =============================================================================
# === ADDRESS CONVERSION REFERENCE — READ THIS BEFORE TOUCHING ANY ROM ========
# =============================================================================

[SECTION:address_conversion_terminology]
desc=three_address_spaces_distinct_and_must_not_be_confused
cpu_bus_addr=24bit_address_seen_by_65C816|format=BB:OOOO|BB=bank_$00..$FF|OOOO=offset_$0000..$FFFF
snes_addr=alias_for_cpu_bus_addr|aka_LoROM_addr_or_HiROM_addr_depending_on_mode
pc_addr=byte_offset_into_raw_ROM_file|aka_file_offset|aka_linear_offset|aka_ROM_offset
ram_addr=runtime_address_in_WRAM_or_BWRAM_or_VRAM|distinct_from_pc_addr
copier_header=optional_512_byte_prefix_in_some_dumps|MUST_be_skipped_before_any_conversion
> The CPU bus address is what the 65816 actually emits on its address pins:
> a 24-bit number split into a bank byte and an offset word. The PC (file)
> offset is where bytes physically live in the .smc/.sfc file on disk; these
> two are related by the mapping mode formulas in this section. Runtime RAM
> addresses (WRAM at $7E:0000..$7F:FFFF, VRAM accessed via $2116/$2117, etc)
> are a third space and have no PC offset because they are mutable storage.
> Confusing the three spaces is the #1 source of failed ROM hacks. Whenever
> you see "address $8000" with no further context, ASK which space.

[SECTION:address_conversion_copier_header]
desc=512_byte_SMC_header_present_in_some_dumps
detect=if_(file_size_modulo_1024)==512_then_copier_header_present
action=add_$200_to_every_pc_addr_when_indexing_OR_strip_the_$200_first
strip_command=dd_if=in.smc_of=out.sfc_bs=512_skip=1
hashing=ALWAYS_strip_header_before_computing_md5_or_crc32_for_no_intro_match
extension_smc=.smc_often_has_header|but_NOT_reliable_indicator
extension_sfc=.sfc_usually_does_not_have_header|but_NOT_reliable_indicator
> The 512-byte SMC copier header is metadata added by 1990s backup units like
> the Super Wild Card. Modern emulators auto-skip it but every analysis tool
> needs to know whether it is there. The detection rule is mechanical: take
> file size mod 1024; if it equals 512 the header is present. Strip it
> before doing anything else (hashing, header validation, address math).

[SECTION:address_conversion_lorom_mode20]
desc=LoROM_$20_or_$30_FastROM|32_KiB_per_bank
bank_layout=banks_$00..$7D_and_$80..$FF|each_bank_exposes_only_$8000..$FFFF_to_ROM
lower_half_$0000_$7FFF=WRAM_mirror_or_IO_or_SRAM_depending_on_bank
sram_window=banks_$70..$7D:$0000..$7FFF|or_$F0..$FF:$0000..$7FFF_in_some_carts
fastrom_region=banks_$80..$FF_when_$420D.D0=1
formula_snes_to_pc=pc=((bank&0x7F)<<15)|(addr&0x7FFF)
formula_pc_to_snes=bank=(pc>>15)&0x7F|addr=(pc&0x7FFF)|0x8000
formula_pc_to_snes_fastrom=bank=((pc>>15)&0x7F)|0x80|addr=(pc&0x7FFF)|0x8000
test_case_1=snes_$808000=pc_$000000|verify=((0x80&0x7F)<<15)|0x0000=0
test_case_2=snes_$80FFFF=pc_$007FFF
test_case_3=snes_$818000=pc_$008000
test_case_4=snes_$C0FFFF=pc_$207FFF
test_case_5=pc_$040000=snes_$888000|verify=bank=(0x040000>>15)|0x80=0x88
max_rom_size_lorom=4MiB_(32Mbit)|beyond_this_use_HiROM_or_ExHiROM
games_using=Super_Mario_World|Final_Fantasy_IV|Zelda_LTTP|Super_Metroid|F-Zero|Contra_III|Castlevania_IV
> LoROM is the simpler mapping. Each 64K bank exposes only its upper half
> ($8000..$FFFF) to ROM data; the lower half is reserved for WRAM mirror,
> hardware registers, and (in upper banks) SRAM. The math is therefore
> "mask off the high bank bit, shift left 15, OR in the bottom 15 bits of
> the address". File offset $0 corresponds to SNES bank $80 offset $8000
> (or $00 offset $8000) — the reset vector at $00:FFFC reads from there.

[SECTION:address_conversion_hirom_mode21]
desc=HiROM_$21_or_$31_FastROM|full_64_KiB_per_bank
bank_layout_full=banks_$40..$7D_and_$C0..$FF|expose_full_$0000..$FFFF_to_ROM
bank_layout_mirror=banks_$00..$3F_and_$80..$BF|expose_only_$8000..$FFFF_as_upper_half_mirror
sram_window=$20..$3F:$6000..$7FFF|and|$A0..$BF:$6000..$7FFF
fastrom_region=banks_$80..$FF_when_$420D.D0=1
formula_snes_to_pc=pc=((bank&0x3F)<<16)|addr
formula_pc_to_snes_canonical=bank=(pc>>16)|0xC0|addr=pc&0xFFFF
test_case_1=snes_$C00000=pc_$000000
test_case_2=snes_$C0FFB0=pc_$00FFB0|note=internal_header_location
test_case_3=snes_$00FFB0=pc_$00FFB0|note=$00:FFB0_mirrors_$C0:FFB0_so_same_pc
test_case_4=snes_$C18000=pc_$018000
max_rom_size_hirom=4MiB_(32Mbit)
games_using=Final_Fantasy_VI|Chrono_Trigger|Earthbound|Donkey_Kong_Country|Secret_of_Mana|Tales_of_Phantasia_(no_thats_ExHi)|Super_Mario_RPG_(no_thats_SA1)|Romancing_SaGa
> HiROM gives full 64K banks of ROM data. The mirror in $00..$3F:$8000+ is
> not a separate copy — it is the literal upper half of the corresponding
> $C0+ bank. So $00:FFFC and $C0:FFFC are the same byte, and the formula is
> identical. The reset vector lives at $00:FFFC which resolves to PC offset
> $00FFFC, the same place the internal header lives.

[SECTION:address_conversion_exhirom_mode25]
desc=ExHiROM_$25_or_$35_FastROM|>4MiB_games|two_4MiB_halves
half_low=ROM_file_offsets_$000000..$3FFFFF|maps_to_$C0..$FF:$0000..$FFFF
half_high=ROM_file_offsets_$400000..$7DFFFF|maps_to_$40..$7D:$0000..$FFFF
mirror_low=$80..$BF:$8000..$FFFF_mirrors_$C0..$FF_upper_half
mirror_high=$00..$3F:$8000..$FFFF_mirrors_$40..$7D_upper_half
header_location=$40FFB0_in_ROM_file
formula_pseudo=pc=((bank&0x3F)<<16)|addr|((bank&0x80)?0:0x400000)
decision_rule=if_bank_bit_7_is_0_then_OR_with_$400000_else_low_half
test_case_1=snes_$C00000=pc_$000000
test_case_2=snes_$408000=pc_$408000
test_case_3=snes_$00FFB0=pc_$40FFB0|mirror_of_$40
max_rom_size_exhirom=8MiB_(64Mbit)
games_using=Tales_of_Phantasia|Star_Ocean|Daikaijuu_Monogatari_II|Dai-3-ji_Super_Robot_Taisen
> ExHiROM is HiROM with bank-bit-7 selecting which 4 MiB half. Bit 7 set
> ($80..$FF) means low half; bit 7 clear ($00..$7D) means high half. The
> reset vector at $00:FFFC therefore reads from PC offset $40FFFC, NOT
> $00FFFC like HiROM, because bank $00 mirrors bank $40 in this mode.

[SECTION:address_conversion_sa1_mode23]
desc=SA-1_$23|Super_MMC_4_window_bank_switching
super_mmc_blocks=8Mbit_blocks_(1MiB_each)|max_8_blocks=64Mbit
window_C_$2220_CXB=$C0..$CF_and_mirror_$00..$1F:$8000..$FFFF|init_block=$00
window_D_$2221_DXB=$D0..$DF_and_mirror_$20..$3F:$8000..$FFFF|init_block=$01
window_E_$2222_EXB=$E0..$EF_and_mirror_$80..$9F:$8000..$FFFF|init_block=$02
window_F_$2223_FXB=$F0..$FF_and_mirror_$A0..$BF:$8000..$FFFF|init_block=$03
bank_register_bits=D2..D0=block_index_0..7|D7=CBM_image_projection_enable
formula_direct_C=pc=(CXB.block*$100000)|((bank-$C0)<<16)|addr  # bank in $C0..$CF
formula_direct_D=pc=(DXB.block*$100000)|((bank-$D0)<<16)|addr
formula_direct_E=pc=(EXB.block*$100000)|((bank-$E0)<<16)|addr
formula_direct_F=pc=(FXB.block*$100000)|((bank-$F0)<<16)|addr
formula_mirror_C=pc=(CXB.block*$100000)|((bank&$1F)<<15)|(addr&$7FFF)  # $00..$1F:$8000+
formula_mirror_D=pc=(DXB.block*$100000)|((bank&$1F)<<15)|(addr&$7FFF)
formula_mirror_E=pc=(EXB.block*$100000)|((bank&$1F)<<15)|(addr&$7FFF)
formula_mirror_F=pc=(FXB.block*$100000)|((bank&$1F)<<15)|(addr&$7FFF)
header_location=$007FB0_LoROM_position
games_using=Kirby_Super_Star|Kirby_Dream_Land_3|Super_Mario_RPG|Marvelous|PGA_European_Tour|Mini_4WD|Power_Rangers_Zeo
> SA-1 ROM access is fundamentally bank-switched. Four sliding 1 MiB windows
> at $C0..$CF, $D0..$DF, $E0..$EF, $F0..$FF each select one of up to eight
> 8 Mbit blocks via the CXB/DXB/EXB/FXB registers. Each window is also
> mirrored as a LoROM-style 32 KiB-per-bank arrangement at $00..$1F,
> $20..$3F, $80..$9F, $A0..$BF respectively. To convert an SA-1 SNES address
> to a file offset you must know the current state of the four block
> registers; the reset vector at $00:FFFC must therefore be in a region
> that is reachable with default register values ($00,$01,$02,$03).

