$00..$3F:$2200..$23FF=expansion_chip_regs_(SA1_etc)|else_open_bus
$00..$3F:$3000..$33FF=Super_FX_or_SA-1_IRAM_window
$00..$3F:$3400..$3FFF=expansion_chip_or_open_bus
$00..$3F:$4000..$4015=open_bus
$00..$3F:$4016=JOYSER0_(joypad_serial_legacy)
$00..$3F:$4017=JOYSER1
$00..$3F:$4018..$41FF=open_bus
$00..$3F:$4200..$420D=CPU_internal_registers_$4200_$420D
$00..$3F:$420E..$420F=open_bus
$00..$3F:$4210..$421F=CPU_status_and_joypad_auto_read
$00..$3F:$4220..$42FF=open_bus
$00..$3F:$4300..$437F=DMA_channel_registers_8ch_x_16B
$00..$3F:$4380..$5FFF=open_bus
$00..$3F:$6000..$7FFF=cartridge_expansion_(HiROM_SRAM_window_or_else)
$00..$3F:$8000..$FFFF=cartridge_ROM_(LoROM_data_or_HiROM_mirror)
$40..$7D=cartridge_ROM_(HiROM_full_banks_or_LoROM_continuation)
$7E:$0000..$1FFF=WRAM_first_8KiB_(also_visible_at_low_mirror)
$7E:$2000..$FFFF=WRAM_continued
$7F:$0000..$FFFF=WRAM_second_64KiB
$80..$BF=mirror_of_$00..$3F_but_with_FastROM_eligible_$8000_$FFFF
$C0..$FF=cartridge_ROM_(HiROM_or_continuation_or_FastROM)
> The "common" region $00..$3F (mirrored at $80..$BF) holds the WRAM low
> mirror, all hardware registers, and the bottom half of LoROM data. WRAM
> physical storage is in banks $7E and $7F. ROM occupies different bank
> regions depending on mapping mode. Many in-between addresses are not
> mapped to anything: reading them returns "open bus" (the last byte that
> was on the data bus, which depends on the previous instruction).

[SECTION:open_bus_behavior]
desc=reads_from_unmapped_addresses_return_last_data_bus_value
mechanism=SNES_data_bus_has_no_pull_up_or_pull_down|capacitive_storage_holds_last_value
read_returns=value_of_byte_most_recently_placed_on_bus
typical_source=last_instruction_byte_fetched|or_last_explicit_read
not_zero=NEVER_assume_unmapped_reads_return_$00
games_relying_on_open_bus=several_titles_break_if_open_bus_is_implemented_incorrectly
emulator_quirk=accurate_emulators_must_track_data_bus_state
> Open bus is the SNES's behavior when you read from an address that is not
> connected to anything (e.g., $4220, $4380..$5FFF in most carts). The 65816
> data pins are tristate and the bus has enough capacitance to retain the
> last byte that was on it. So a read returns whatever the last load or
> opcode fetch left on the bus. This is NOT zero. Some games (e.g., Speedy
> Gonzales) accidentally rely on open-bus values to make logic decisions,
> so emulators must implement this faithfully.

# =============================================================================
# === 65816 CPU DETAILED REFERENCE ============================================
# =============================================================================

[SECTION:cpu_65816_overview]
desc=Ricoh_5A22_main_CPU_with_WDC_65C816_core
manufacturer=Ricoh|core_design=Western_Design_Center
register_width_native=16bit_with_selectable_8bit_for_A_X_Y
register_width_emulation=8bit_locked_(6502_compatibility)
address_space=24bit_16MiB_total
data_bus_width=8bit
clock_speeds=1.79_2.68_or_3.58_MHz_per_address_region
> The 5A22 is Ricoh's licensed 65C816 core wrapped with custom peripherals
> (DMA controller, NMI/IRQ logic, joypad reader, multiplier/divider, B-bus
> interface for talking to the PPU). At reset it boots in 6502-emulation
> mode (e=1) with the 8-bit accumulator and 8-bit index registers, just
> like a NES. The first thing every SNES game does is execute "CLC; XCE"
> to switch to native mode where the registers can be widened to 16 bits.

[SECTION:cpu_65816_register_file]
desc=programmer_visible_register_set
A=accumulator|width=8_or_16_per_M_flag|hidden_high_byte_called_B_when_M=1
X=index_register_X|width=8_or_16_per_X_flag
Y=index_register_Y|width=8_or_16_per_X_flag
S=stack_pointer|width=8_in_emulation_(forced_to_$01xx)|width=16_in_native
DP=direct_page_register|width=16_always|specifies_DP_base_in_bank_$00
DB=data_bank_register|width=8|prepended_to_16bit_data_addresses
PB=program_bank_register|width=8|prepended_to_PC_for_instruction_fetch
PC=program_counter|width=16|wraps_within_PB_bank
P=processor_status_register|width=8|see_status_flags_section
e=hidden_emulation_mode_flag|accessible_only_via_XCE_instruction
> The 65816 register file looks small but has subtle width-changing
> behavior. A is "actually" a 16-bit register internally, but when M=1
> only the low 8 bits are operated on and the high 8 bits ("B") are
> preserved untouched. The XBA instruction swaps A and B halves. X and Y
> follow the same rule via the X flag (when X=1 their high bytes are
> CLEARED, not preserved). The direct page register DP is a 16-bit value
> that specifies where in bank $00 the "zero page" lives — typically
> programs leave it at $0000 but can move it to e.g. $0100 to get a
> separate workspace. DB is the bank prepended to most data accesses;
> PB is the bank for instruction fetch (changed by JSL/JML/RTL).

[SECTION:cpu_65816_status_flags]
desc=P_register_bit_layout|order_NVMXDIZC
N_D7=Negative|set_if_high_bit_of_result_is_1
V_D6=Overflow|set_on_signed_overflow
M_D5=Memory_accumulator_width|0=16bit_A|1=8bit_A|set_via_REP_SEP|hidden_in_emulation_mode
X_D4=Index_register_width|0=16bit_X_Y|1=8bit_X_Y|when_set_high_bytes_of_X_Y_are_cleared
D_D3=Decimal_mode|0=binary|1=BCD|affects_ADC_SBC|rarely_used_on_SNES
I_D2=IRQ_disable|1=mask_IRQ|set_by_SEI|cleared_by_CLI
Z_D1=Zero|set_if_result_is_zero
C_D0=Carry|set_on_carry_from_addition_or_no_borrow_from_subtraction
B_in_emulation=BRK_flag|shares_bit_with_X_in_native_mode|distinguishes_BRK_from_IRQ_on_emulation_stack
emulation_e_hidden=accessible_via_XCE|swaps_with_C_flag
> When you execute "CLC; XCE" the carry flag and the e flag are exchanged.
> Since CLC clears C to 0, after XCE the e flag becomes 0 (native mode).
> Going back to emulation is "SEC; XCE". REP and SEP take an immediate
> mask byte and clear or set the corresponding bits in P. So "REP #$30"
> clears the M and X flags simultaneously, putting A, X, and Y all into
> 16-bit mode. "SEP #$30" puts them all back to 8-bit. The decimal mode
> flag D is rarely used on SNES — when set, ADC and SBC perform BCD math
> instead of binary, but most code clears it after reset and leaves it.

[SECTION:cpu_65816_emulation_vs_native]
desc=two_distinct_modes_with_different_capabilities
emulation_mode_e=1
emulation_features=8bit_A_X_Y_locked|stack_locked_to_$01xx|new_instructions_disabled|6502_compatibility
emulation_vectors=$FFF4_COP|$FFF8_ABORT|$FFFA_NMI|$FFFC_RESET|$FFFE_IRQ_BRK
native_mode_e=0
native_features=selectable_8_or_16bit_A_X_Y|stack_can_be_anywhere_in_bank_$00|all_65816_instructions_available
native_vectors=$FFE4_COP|$FFE6_BRK|$FFE8_ABORT|$FFEA_NMI|$FFEC_unused|$FFEE_IRQ
reset_state_summary=e=1|m=1|x=1|D=0|I=1|DP=$0000|DB=$00|PB=$00|S=$01FF
> The 65816 boots emulating a 6502 because that is what backward-compatible
> WDC chips were sold as in the late 80s. SNES carts always switch to
> native mode in the first few instructions of the reset handler. The
> emulation mode is essentially never used past initialization. Note that
> in emulation mode the IRQ vector at $FFFE is shared with BRK, so a BRK
> instruction in emulation mode jumps to the IRQ handler with the B flag
> in P set; in native mode BRK has its own vector at $FFE6.

[SECTION:cpu_65816_mode_switching_procedure]
desc=canonical_sequences_for_changing_CPU_state
switch_to_native=|
  CLC                ; clear carry
  XCE                ; exchange carry with emulation flag (e becomes 0)
switch_to_emulation=|
  SEC                ; set carry
  XCE                ; e becomes 1
set_A_X_Y_all_16bit=|
  REP #$30           ; clear M (bit 5) and X (bit 4) of P
set_A_X_Y_all_8bit=|
  SEP #$30           ; set M and X
set_only_A_16bit=|
  REP #$20           ; clear M only
set_only_X_Y_16bit=|
  REP #$10           ; clear X only
canonical_reset_init=|
  SEI                ; mask IRQ
  CLC : XCE          ; switch to native
  REP #$30           ; A, X, Y all 16-bit
  LDX #$1FFF         ; setup native stack
  TXS
  LDA #$0000
  TCD                ; direct page = 0
  SEP #$20           ; back to 8-bit A for setup writes
  LDA #$00
  PHA
  PLB                ; data bank = 0
gotcha_x_high_byte_clear=|
  When you execute SEP #$10 to switch X and Y to 8-bit, the HIGH bytes of
  X and Y are immediately CLEARED to zero. This is unlike the M flag which
  preserves the hidden B half of A. So if you have meaningful data in
  XH/YH and you switch to 8-bit, that data is gone. To preserve it, store
  X and Y to memory before SEP and reload after.

[SECTION:cpu_65816_addressing_modes]
desc=24_addressing_modes_supported_by_the_65816
> The 65816 has 24 distinct addressing modes — twice as many as the 6502
> it descended from. Most are variations on "direct page" (which is the
> 6502's "zero page" but movable), absolute, indirect, and indexed forms.
> Long forms (24-bit addresses) are new in the 65816 and let any
> instruction reach anywhere in the 16 MiB address space without
> manipulating bank registers.

mode_immediate=#imm|operand_is_literal_8_or_16_bits|width_depends_on_M_or_X_flag
example_imm=LDA #$1234         ; load 16-bit literal into A (when M=0)

mode_absolute=abs|16bit_offset_in_current_DBR_bank
example_abs=LDA $1234          ; loads from DBR:1234

mode_absolute_long=long|24bit_full_address_ignores_DBR
example_long=LDA $7E1234       ; loads from $7E:1234 regardless of DBR

mode_direct_page=dp|8bit_offset_added_to_DP_register|always_in_bank_$00
example_dp=LDA $80             ; loads from $00:DP+80

mode_direct_page_indirect=(dp)|reads_pointer_from_DP_dereferences_via_DBR
example_dp_ind=LDA ($80)       ; reads pointer at DP+80, then loads from DBR:that

mode_direct_page_indirect_long=[dp]|reads_24bit_pointer_from_DP|ignores_DBR
example_dp_ind_long=LDA [$80]  ; reads 3 bytes at DP+80, loads from that

mode_absolute_indexed_X=abs,X|16bit_+_X_in_DBR
example_abs_x=LDA $1234,X      ; load from DBR:1234+X

mode_absolute_indexed_Y=abs,Y|same_with_Y
example_abs_y=LDA $1234,Y

mode_absolute_long_indexed_X=long,X|24bit_+_X
example_long_x=LDA $7E1234,X   ; load from $7E:1234+X

mode_dp_indexed_X=dp,X|8bit_+_X_added_to_DP|stays_in_bank_$00
example_dp_x=LDA $80,X

mode_dp_indexed_Y=dp,Y|same_with_Y_(only_for_some_instructions)
example_dp_y=LDX $80,Y

mode_dp_indexed_indirect_X=(dp,X)|read_pointer_from_DP+X_then_use_DBR
example_dp_x_ind=LDA ($80,X)   ; reads pointer at DP+80+X, loads via DBR

mode_dp_indirect_indexed_Y=(dp),Y|read_pointer_from_DP_then_add_Y
example_dp_ind_y=LDA ($80),Y   ; reads pointer at DP+80, loads from DBR:that+Y

mode_dp_indirect_long_indexed_Y=[dp],Y|read_24bit_pointer_from_DP_then_add_Y
example_dp_ind_long_y=LDA [$80],Y  ; reads 3-byte ptr, adds Y, loads

mode_stack_relative=sr,S|8bit_offset_added_to_S
example_sr=LDA 4,S             ; loads from stack pointer + 4 (useful for params)

mode_stack_relative_indirect_indexed_Y=(sr,S),Y|read_pointer_from_stack_offset_then_index
example_sr_ind_y=LDA (4,S),Y

mode_program_counter_relative=PC_rel_8bit|for_branches
example_pc_rel=BNE label

mode_program_counter_relative_long=PC_rel_16bit|BRL_only
example_pc_rel_long=BRL label

mode_block_move=src_dest|MVN_MVP_only|byte_count_in_A
example_block=MVN $7E,$00      ; move from bank $00 to bank $7E

mode_implied=no_operand
example_implied=INX

mode_accumulator=A|operates_on_A_only
example_accumulator=ASL A

mode_stack=PHA_PLA_etc

mode_indirect_jump_long=(addr)|JMP_only|reads_pointer_from_addr_(no_DBR)
example_jmp_ind=JMP ($1234)    ; reads PC vector at $00:1234

mode_indirect_jump_long_X=(addr,X)|JMP_only
example_jmp_ind_x=JMP ($1234,X)

mode_indirect_jump_24=[addr]|JML_only
example_jml_ind=JML [$1234]    ; reads 24-bit ptr from $00:1234

[SECTION:cpu_65816_instruction_set_load_store]
desc=load_and_store_instructions
LDA=load_accumulator|flags=N_Z|width_per_M
LDX=load_X_register|flags=N_Z|width_per_X
LDY=load_Y_register|flags=N_Z|width_per_X
STA=store_accumulator|no_flag_change
STX=store_X|no_flag_change
STY=store_Y|no_flag_change
STZ=store_zero|65816_addition|writes_zero_to_memory_in_current_M_width
> STZ is a 65816 addition over the 6502 — it stores zero to a memory
> location without going through the accumulator. STZ obeys the M width
> (writes 1 byte if M=1, 2 bytes if M=0).

[SECTION:cpu_65816_instruction_set_arithmetic]
desc=arithmetic_and_increment_decrement
ADC=add_with_carry|flags=N_V_Z_C|BCD_if_D=1
SBC=subtract_with_carry|flags=N_V_Z_C|BCD_if_D=1
INC=increment_memory|flags=N_Z|width_per_M
INX=increment_X|flags=N_Z|width_per_X
INY=increment_Y|flags=N_Z|width_per_X
DEC=decrement_memory|flags=N_Z|width_per_M
DEX=decrement_X|flags=N_Z|width_per_X
DEY=decrement_Y|flags=N_Z|width_per_X
INC_A=increment_accumulator|65816_addition|"INC A" or simply "INC"
DEC_A=decrement_accumulator|65816_addition
> Note ADC has the SUBTLE behavior that if you forget to clear carry
> before the first add of a multi-byte sequence, your sum is off by one.
> Always "CLC : ADC" for the first add and let subsequent ADCs propagate
> the carry. SBC works the opposite way: SET carry first ("SEC : SBC").

[SECTION:cpu_65816_instruction_set_logic_shift]
desc=logical_and_shift_rotate_instructions
AND=logical_AND_into_A|flags=N_Z
ORA=logical_OR_into_A|flags=N_Z
EOR=exclusive_OR_into_A|flags=N_Z
BIT=test_bits|sets_N_V_Z_from_memory_AND_A_without_storing
ASL=arithmetic_shift_left|flags=N_Z_C|operates_on_A_or_memory
LSR=logical_shift_right|flags=N_Z_C
ROL=rotate_left_through_carry|flags=N_Z_C
ROR=rotate_right_through_carry|flags=N_Z_C
TRB=test_and_reset_bits|65816_addition|clears_bits_in_memory_that_are_set_in_A
TSB=test_and_set_bits|65816_addition|sets_bits_in_memory_that_are_set_in_A
> BIT is special: BIT addressing-mode A-effect is to AND the operand with
> A and set Z based on the result, but ALSO copy bits 6 and 7 of the
> operand directly into V and N flags. So you can test high bits of memory
> without disturbing A. BIT immediate (BIT #$xx) only sets Z and does NOT
> touch N/V — useful for compact branches.

[SECTION:cpu_65816_instruction_set_branch_jump]
desc=branch_jump_call_return
BCC=branch_if_carry_clear|signed_8bit_offset
BCS=branch_if_carry_set
BEQ=branch_if_equal|Z=1
BNE=branch_if_not_equal|Z=0
BPL=branch_if_plus|N=0
BMI=branch_if_minus|N=1
BVC=branch_if_overflow_clear
BVS=branch_if_overflow_set
BRA=branch_always|65816_addition|signed_8bit
BRL=branch_long|65816_addition|signed_16bit
JMP=jump_within_bank|3_byte_instruction
JML=jump_long|4_byte|sets_PB
JSR=jump_subroutine_within_bank|pushes_PC_minus_1
JSL=jump_subroutine_long|pushes_PB_then_PC_minus_1|65816_addition
RTS=return_from_JSR|pulls_PC_adds_1
RTL=return_from_JSL|pulls_PC_then_PB
RTI=return_from_interrupt|pulls_P_then_PC|in_native_also_pulls_PB
> The 65816 added BRL (branch long with 16-bit relative offset) which can
> reach anywhere in the current bank without going through JMP. JSL and
> RTL are the long-call long-return pair that span banks. Critical: RTI
> in native mode pulls 4 bytes (P, PCL, PCH, PB) but in emulation mode
> only 3 (P, PCL, PCH). Mismatched RTI will corrupt the stack.

[SECTION:cpu_65816_instruction_set_compare]
desc=comparison_sets_flags_no_store
CMP=compare_A_to_memory|flags=N_Z_C
CPX=compare_X_to_memory
CPY=compare_Y_to_memory
> CMP performs A - memory but does not store the result, only sets flags.
> Carry is set if A >= memory (no borrow). Use BCS for "greater than or
> equal", BCC for "less than", BEQ for "equal".

[SECTION:cpu_65816_instruction_set_stack]
desc=stack_operations|all_push_pull
PHA=push_A|width_per_M
PHX=push_X|width_per_X
PHY=push_Y|width_per_X
PHP=push_P|always_1_byte
PHB=push_data_bank|1_byte
PHD=push_direct_page|2_bytes
PHK=push_program_bank|1_byte|65816_addition
PLA=pull_A
PLX=pull_X
PLY=pull_Y
PLP=pull_P
PLB=pull_data_bank
PLD=pull_direct_page
PEA=push_effective_absolute|pushes_16bit_immediate
PEI=push_effective_indirect|pushes_word_at_DP_offset
PER=push_effective_PC_relative
> PEA is commonly used to push a return address onto the stack so that
> a subsequent RTS jumps to a computed location. The trick is "PEA
> target-1; JMP elsewhere" — when elsewhere does RTS, it returns to
> target. PEI reads a 16-bit value from direct page and pushes it.

[SECTION:cpu_65816_instruction_set_block_move]
desc=block_move_instructions|MVN_and_MVP|65816_addition
MVN=move_negative|copies_from_low_to_high|increments_X_and_Y
MVP=move_positive|copies_from_high_to_low|decrements_X_and_Y
A=length_minus_1|byte_count_to_move
X=source_address|16_bit
Y=destination_address|16_bit
operand_byte1=destination_bank
operand_byte2=source_bank
> Block move is the 65816's killer feature for memory-to-memory copies.
> Each MVN/MVP instruction moves A+1 bytes from source bank:X to
> destination bank:Y, advancing X and Y until A wraps around. The
> instruction REPEATS internally — it does not execute once, it loops.
> Note the operand byte order: destination bank first, source bank second.
> Many assemblers print them backwards (source, dest) which is the order
> a human would write but the BYTES emitted are dest, src. MVN takes
> 7 cycles per byte; MVP takes 7 cycles per byte. To copy 16 KiB you
> need ~115,000 cycles which is more than 2 frames at 2.68 MHz, so big
> copies should use DMA instead.

[SECTION:cpu_65816_instruction_set_transfer]
desc=register_transfer_operations
TAX=transfer_A_to_X|widths_per_X
TAY=transfer_A_to_Y
TXA=transfer_X_to_A
TYA=transfer_Y_to_A
TXY=transfer_X_to_Y|65816_addition
TYX=transfer_Y_to_X
TXS=transfer_X_to_S|sets_stack_pointer
TSX=transfer_S_to_X
TCD=transfer_C_(16bit_A)_to_DP|always_16bit
TDC=transfer_DP_to_A
TCS=transfer_C_to_S|always_16bit
TSC=transfer_S_to_A
XBA=exchange_B_and_A|swaps_high_and_low_bytes_of_16bit_A
XCE=exchange_carry_with_emulation_flag
> TCD/TDC are how you set the direct page register from a computed
> value: load A with desired DP, then TCD. Always 16-bit regardless of
> M flag because DP is always 16-bit. Same for TCS/TSC and the stack
> pointer in native mode.

[SECTION:cpu_65816_instruction_set_flag_misc]
desc=flag_manipulation_and_misc
CLC=clear_carry
SEC=set_carry
CLI=clear_interrupt_disable|enables_IRQ
SEI=set_interrupt_disable|masks_IRQ
CLD=clear_decimal_mode
SED=set_decimal_mode
CLV=clear_overflow
REP=reset_(clear)_P_bits|operand_is_immediate_mask
SEP=set_P_bits|operand_is_immediate_mask
NOP=no_operation|2_cycles_no_effect
WAI=wait_for_interrupt|halts_CPU_until_NMI_or_IRQ
STP=stop_clock|halts_until_reset|RARELY_USED
COP=coprocessor_trap|jumps_to_COP_vector
BRK=software_break|jumps_to_BRK_vector
> WAI is the proper way to wait for vblank without polling. The CPU halts,
> draws no power, and resumes on the next interrupt with the I flag still
> respected. Many games use "STZ $4200; LDA #$81; STA $4200; CLI; WAI"
> to wait for the next NMI cleanly. STP is almost never used because
> recovering requires a hardware reset.

[SECTION:cpu_65816_cycle_timing_rules]
desc=how_to_compute_actual_instruction_cycle_counts
> 65816 instruction cycles depend on several factors that you must add
> up correctly to get a true count. Start with the base count for the
> opcode (these are tabulated in WDC's official W65C816S datasheet).
> Then apply the modifiers below.

base_cycles=look_up_in_official_table_per_opcode
+1_if_M_clear=for_each_memory_access_in_16bit_M_mode|load_or_store_of_2_bytes_takes_extra_cycle
+1_if_X_clear_index_crosses_page=in_emulation_mode_only_(x,X)_or_(x),Y_indexing
+1_if_DP_low_byte_nonzero=any_DP_addressing_when_DP&$FF != 0
+1_if_branch_taken=branches_not_taken_are_2_cycles
+1_if_branch_crosses_page_boundary=in_emulation_mode_only
+1_if_decimal_mode_in_native=BCD_arithmetic_takes_extra_cycle_in_native
+2_if_native_mode_for_BRK_COP=push_extra_PB_byte
master_cycle_per_cpu_cycle=6_8_or_12_depending_on_address_speed_region
> The "+1 if DP low nonzero" rule catches a lot of people: any direct
> page instruction takes an extra cycle if the low byte of the DP
> register is not zero. So setting DP to $0100 vs $0000 vs $0001 has
> different timing. Tight cycle-accurate code keeps DP aligned to a
> page boundary.

[SECTION:cpu_65816_direct_page_explained]
desc=direct_page_register_DP_purpose_and_movement
size=16_bit
location_in_emulation=fixed_at_$0000|just_like_6502_zero_page
location_in_native=anywhere_in_bank_$00|set_via_TCD_or_PLD
typical_use=$0000_default|or_$0100_for_separate_workspace
performance_advantage=DP_addressing_is_2_bytes_vs_3_bytes_for_absolute|saves_ROM_and_one_cycle
constraint=must_stay_in_bank_$00|cannot_cross_into_$01_bank
> Direct page is the 6502's "zero page" reimagined as a movable 256-byte
> window into bank $00. Setting DP to $0000 makes addresses $00..$FF the
> direct page (the classic 6502 zero page). Setting DP to $0100 makes
> $0100..$01FF the direct page, which is useful for code that wants its
> own scratch area without disturbing the global zero page. The hardware
> ensures DP arithmetic stays in bank $00, so DP=$FF80 wraps around for
> high direct-page addresses.

[SECTION:cpu_65816_data_bank_explained]
desc=data_bank_register_DB_purpose
size=8_bit
purpose=upper_byte_of_24bit_address_for_most_data_loads_and_stores
set_via=PLB_LDA+PHA+PLB_or_LONG_addressing
default_at_reset=$00
typical_use=set_to_bank_where_main_data_table_lives|then_use_short_absolute_addresses
> When you write LDA $1234, the actual address read is DB:$1234. The
> 65816 prepends the data bank register to form a 24-bit address. So
> if your data table is at $7E:0000 you might "LDA #$7E; PHA; PLB" once
> and then use "LDA $0123" to access $7E:0123 cheaply. Without doing
> this you would need long-absolute "LDA $7E0123" everywhere, which
> costs an extra byte and an extra cycle per access.

[SECTION:cpu_65816_gotchas]
desc=common_traps_for_new_65816_programmers
> 1) Forgetting to switch from emulation to native at boot. Without
>    "CLC; XCE" you are running a fancy 6502.
> 2) Mixing M=0 and M=1 code without tracking which mode you are in.
>    "LDA #$00" is one byte different from "LDA #$0000" and the
>    assembler must know your current mode. Most assemblers (including
>    Psy-Q's ASM658) have an MX directive or similar to tell it.
> 3) Forgetting to set DB. After reset DB=$00 so absolute loads read
>    from bank $00. If your data is in $7E (WRAM) and you forget to
>    set DB, you'll read garbage.
> 4) Forgetting to update DP after switching contexts. If you JSL into
>    a routine that uses direct page and forget to set DP first, the
>    routine reads from whatever DP was last set to.
> 5) RTI vs RTL vs RTS confusion. RTS pulls 2 bytes (PCL, PCH). RTL
>    pulls 3 (PCL, PCH, PB). RTI pulls 3 in emulation (P, PCL, PCH)
>    and 4 in native (P, PCL, PCH, PB). Mismatched returns crash.
> 6) The X-flag-set-clears-XH gotcha. SEP #$10 immediately zeros the
>    high bytes of X and Y, losing data.
> 7) Block moves with the operand bytes in the wrong order. The
>    instruction is "MVN dest_bank, src_bank" — destination first.
> 8) Doing tight WRAM loops while expecting FastROM speedup. WRAM is
>    always 2.68 MHz regardless of $420D.
> 9) Reading a write-only register and getting open bus, not zero.
> 10) Forgetting that the stack in emulation mode is locked to $01xx,
>    so you cannot grow it past 256 bytes. Native mode allows the full
>    bank $00 stack.

# =============================================================================
# === INTERRUPTS: NMI, IRQ, BRK, COP, RESET ===================================
# =============================================================================

[SECTION:interrupt_overview]
desc=interrupt_handling_on_the_5A22
> The SNES has five types of CPU control transfer that aren't normal jumps:
> RESET (power-on or external reset pin), NMI (non-maskable interrupt,
> generated by V-blank), IRQ (interrupt request, generated by H/V counter
> match), BRK (software break instruction), and COP (coprocessor trap
> instruction). Each has its own vector pair (one for emulation mode, one
> for native mode) at the top of bank $00. When an interrupt fires, the
> CPU pushes return state onto the stack, sets the I flag (mask further
> IRQs), clears the D flag (binary mode for the handler), loads the vector,
> and starts executing the handler.

[SECTION:nmi_detailed]
desc=Non_Maskable_Interrupt|generated_by_PPU_at_vblank_start
acronym=NMI=Non_Maskable_Interrupt
trigger=PPU_finishing_visible_lines_and_entering_vblank|specifically_at_dot_0_of_scanline_225_NTSC_or_241_PAL
controlling_register=$4200_NMITIMEN_bit_7
$4200.D7=NMI_enable|0=disabled|1=fires_on_each_vblank
flag_register=$4210_RDNMI_bit_7
read_clears_flag=reading_$4210_clears_D7_to_0
vector_native=$00FFEA
vector_emulation=$00FFFA
cycles_to_enter_native=8_cycles
cycles_to_enter_emulation=7_cycles
stack_pushed_native=PB|PC_high|PC_low|P|(4_bytes_total)
stack_pushed_emulation=PC_high|PC_low|P|(3_bytes_total)
state_changes_on_entry=I_flag_set|D_flag_cleared|in_native_PB_set_to_$00
return_instruction=RTI
> NMI is the heartbeat of every SNES game. It fires once per frame when
> the PPU finishes the visible region and enters vertical blank. At that
> moment $4210 bit 7 latches and, if $4200 bit 7 is set, the CPU is
> interrupted. The handler reads $4210 (which clears the latch) and then
> performs all VRAM/OAM/CGRAM uploads while the PPU is idle.
>
> CRITICAL TIMING: NMI fires at the START of vblank but you only have
> ~2730 microseconds (NTSC) or ~4600 microseconds (PAL) before vblank
> ends and the PPU resumes drawing. If your NMI handler runs longer than
> that, you will see partial uploads and screen corruption. To budget:
> at 2.68 MHz CPU, vblank is roughly 7300 CPU cycles NTSC, 12300 cycles
> PAL. A DMA byte costs ~8 master cycles = ~1.5 CPU cycles, so 6 KiB of
> DMA upload eats roughly 9000 master cycles = ~1500 CPU cycles, leaving
> ~5800 cycles for everything else.
>
> CRITICAL ORDERING: enable NMI BEFORE reading $4210 the first time. If
> the NMI flag is already pending when you set $4200.D7, the NMI will
> fire immediately. To avoid this, write $4200 with NMI disabled, read
> $4210 once to clear, then write $4200 with NMI enabled. Most games do
> this in their reset handler.
>
> NMI IS NON-MASKABLE in the sense that the I flag does not block it,
> only $4200.D7 does. SEI does not stop NMI. The only way to disable NMI
> is to clear $4200.D7. This is why disabling/enabling NMI temporarily
> requires careful sequencing — you cannot just SEI/CLI around it.

nmi_handler_template=|
  <handler entry>
  PHP            ; save flags
  REP #$30       ; A, X, Y to 16-bit
  PHA : PHX : PHY : PHB : PHD       ; save all working state
  PHK : PLB      ; set DB to current code bank
  
  LDA $4210      ; clear NMI flag (also returns CPU version in low bits)
  
  ; perform VRAM/OAM/CGRAM uploads here via DMA
  
  PLD : PLB : PLY : PLX : PLA       ; restore
  PLP            ; restore flags
  RTI            ; return (pulls P, PC, PB)

nmi_pitfalls=|
  - Forgetting to clear $4210 leaves the flag pending; next vblank will
    fire NMI again immediately (race-able).
  - Doing too much work in NMI corrupts the visible frame.
  - Not preserving B (data bank) before setting it can break code that
    runs after RTI.
  - Forgetting that DMA cycles also count against vblank time.

[SECTION:irq_detailed]
desc=Interrupt_Request|generated_by_H_V_counter_match
acronym=IRQ=Interrupt_Request
trigger=H_counter_match_OR_V_counter_match_OR_both|set_by_$4200.D4_D5
controlling_register=$4200_NMITIMEN_bits_4_5
$4200.D4=H_count_irq_enable
$4200.D5=V_count_irq_enable
$4207_$4208=H_target_value_0..339
$4209_$420A=V_target_value_0..261_NTSC_or_311_PAL
flag_register=$4211_TIMEUP_bit_7
read_clears_flag=reading_$4211_clears_D7
vector_native=$00FFEE
vector_emulation=$00FFFE_(SHARED_with_BRK)
cycles_to_enter=7_cycles_emulation|8_cycles_native
stack_pushed=same_as_NMI
state_changes=I_flag_set|D_flag_cleared
maskable=YES_via_I_flag|SEI_blocks|CLI_unblocks
return=RTI
mode_table.D5=0_D4=0=disabled
mode_table.D5=0_D4=1=h_only|fires_at_h_match_on_EVERY_scanline
mode_table.D5=1_D4=0=v_only|fires_at_v_match_at_h=0_dot
mode_table.D5=1_D4=1=both|fires_only_when_h_AND_v_both_match|once_per_frame
> IRQ is the way games do mid-frame effects. The PPU continuously counts
> horizontal dots (0-339) and vertical lines (0-261 NTSC); when both
> counters match the values you wrote to $4207-$420A, an IRQ is generated.
> The most common configuration is V-only (V_EN=1, H_EN=0): "fire IRQ
> when scanline reaches line N". This lets you change palette, scroll,
> or any other PPU register at a known horizontal line during the visible
> region.
>
> The H-only mode is especially powerful: it fires on EVERY scanline at
> the same H position. So you get one IRQ per scanline, perfect for raster
> effects. This is computationally expensive though — at 60 Hz NTSC you
> get ~13,440 IRQs per second, each costing the entry cycles plus your
> handler logic.
>
> SHARED VECTOR WARNING: in emulation mode the IRQ vector at $00FFFE is
> shared with BRK. You must check the B flag in P (bit 4 in emulation)
> to distinguish them. In native mode IRQ has its own vector ($00FFEE)
> and BRK is at $00FFE6 — much cleaner.
>
> IRQs ARE BLOCKED BY THE I FLAG. SEI prevents IRQ from firing; CLI
> reenables. They are also blocked while DMA is running, because the
> CPU is halted during DMA. So if your IRQ should fire on scanline 50
> but a DMA started at scanline 49 and runs through scanline 51, your
> IRQ fires LATE (right after DMA ends). This is a real source of
> raster glitches.
>
> Reading $4211 clears the IRQ flag. You must do this in your handler
> or the IRQ will refire immediately on RTI.

irq_handler_template=|
  <handler entry>
  PHA : PHX : PHY
  PHB : PHK : PLB
  
  LDA $4211      ; clear IRQ flag
  
  ; perform raster effect: change PPU register here
  ; e.g., LDA new_scroll : STA $210D : STA $210D
  
  ; if doing per-scanline IRQ, set up next H/V target here
  
  PLB : PLY : PLX : PLA
  RTI

irq_timing_jitter=|
  IRQ entry has 7-8 cycles of latency from the trigger. If the CPU is
  in the middle of a long instruction (like MVN block move), that
  instruction completes first, adding more latency. So the actual scanline
  on which your handler code starts can vary by ±2-3 scanlines worst case.
  Cycle-precise raster effects use the WAI instruction: just before the
  target line, "STZ $4200" / "WAI" puts the CPU to sleep so it wakes up
  with predictable latency on IRQ.

[SECTION:irq_vs_nmi]
desc=key_differences_between_IRQ_and_NMI
| property         | NMI                              | IRQ                              |
| trigger          | vblank start                     | H/V counter match                |
| maskable_by_I    | NO (I flag does not block)       | YES                              |
| flag_to_disable  | $4200.D7=0                       | $4200.D4 and D5 both 0           |
| vector_native    | $00FFEA                          | $00FFEE                          |
| vector_emulation | $00FFFA                          | $00FFFE (shared with BRK)        |
| ack_register     | $4210 (read)                     | $4211 (read)                     |
| use_case         | once-per-frame VRAM uploads      | mid-frame raster effects         |

[SECTION:reset]
desc=power_on_or_external_reset
trigger=power_on|reset_button_pressed|RES_pin_low
state=e=1|m=1|x=1|D=0|I=1|DP=$0000|DB=$00|PB=$00|S=$01FF
vector=$00FFFC
behavior=fetches_16_bit_PC_from_$00FFFC_and_starts_executing
note=DBR_PBR_DP_S_are_NOT_explicitly_initialized|software_must_set_them
> Reset always starts in emulation mode with the I flag set. The very
> first instructions any SNES game runs are dedicated to setting up the
> CPU state: switch to native, REP #$30, set up native stack at $1FFF,
> set DP to $0000, set DB to $00, then start initializing PPU registers.

[SECTION:brk_cop_traps]
desc=software_trap_instructions
BRK=software_break|2_byte_instruction|signature_byte_after_BRK_is_ignored_by_CPU_but_handler_can_read_it
COP=coprocessor_trap|2_byte_instruction|same_pattern_as_BRK
brk_vector_native=$00FFE6
brk_vector_emulation=$00FFFE_(shared_with_IRQ)
cop_vector_native=$00FFE4
cop_vector_emulation=$00FFF4
> BRK and COP push the same return state as IRQ/NMI but to their own
> vectors. They are 2-byte instructions: the first byte is the opcode,
> the second is a "signature" byte that the handler can inspect by
> reading the byte just before the return PC. This is how you implement
> software interrupts and system calls (e.g., BRK $80 = "syscall 0x80").
> COP is intended for floating-point coprocessors that never existed for
> the 65816, so games rarely use it.
>
> CRITICAL: in emulation mode BRK pushes PC+2 (skipping the signature
> byte), but the IRQ vector is shared. Your handler must check the B
> flag in the pushed P (bit 4) to know if it was BRK or IRQ.

[SECTION:wai_stp_instructions]
desc=CPU_halt_instructions
WAI=Wait_for_Interrupt|halts_CPU_until_NMI_or_IRQ_(or_RESET)
STP=Stop_Clock|halts_CPU_until_RESET
WAI_resume=on_NMI_or_unmasked_IRQ|CPU_resumes_at_instruction_after_WAI|then_branches_to_handler
WAI_with_I_set=CPU_still_resumes|but_does_not_branch_to_handler|just_continues_execution
> WAI is a low-power wait that resumes when an interrupt arrives. The
> common pattern "SEI; LDA #$81; STA $4200; CLI; WAI" enables NMI and
> waits for it. It is also used for cycle-accurate raster timing: WAI
> wakes up at a known point relative to the next IRQ, removing CPU
> instruction-completion jitter.
>
> A subtle WAI behavior: even with I=1 (IRQ masked), WAI still resumes
> when an IRQ pin asserts — but it does NOT branch to the handler.
> Execution simply continues at the next instruction. This is sometimes
> used to wait for a specific event without taking the IRQ.

[SECTION:interrupt_vectors_full]
desc=complete_vector_table_at_top_of_bank_$00
$00FFE4_$00FFE5=COP_native
$00FFE6_$00FFE7=BRK_native
$00FFE8_$00FFE9=ABORT_native_(unused_on_SNES)
$00FFEA_$00FFEB=NMI_native
$00FFEC_$00FFED=reserved
$00FFEE_$00FFEF=IRQ_native
$00FFF0_$00FFF3=reserved
$00FFF4_$00FFF5=COP_emulation
$00FFF6_$00FFF7=reserved
$00FFF8_$00FFF9=ABORT_emulation
$00FFFA_$00FFFB=NMI_emulation
$00FFFC_$00FFFD=RESET_emulation_(used_at_power_on)
$00FFFE_$00FFFF=IRQ_BRK_emulation_(shared)
> All vectors live in bank $00 in the highest 32 bytes ($FFE0-$FFFF).
> They are 16-bit (within bank $00). On reset the CPU is in emulation
> mode so it uses the emulation vectors; after switching to native, the
> native vectors apply for subsequent interrupts.

# =============================================================================
# === DMA — DIRECT MEMORY ACCESS — DETAILED ====================================
# =============================================================================

[SECTION:dma_overview_detailed]
desc=Direct_Memory_Access_subsystem|8_channels|GPDMA_and_HDMA_modes
acronym=DMA=Direct_Memory_Access
channels=8|numbered_0..7
priority=channel_0_highest_channel_7_lowest
mode=each_channel_independently_GPDMA_or_HDMA|cannot_be_both_simultaneously
controlling_regs_per_channel=$43x0..$43xA_where_x_is_channel_number
gpdma_trigger=write_to_$420B_with_bit_n_set_for_channel_n
gpdma_completion=automatic|$420B_bit_clears_when_channel_done
hdma_enable=write_to_$420C_with_bit_n_set
hdma_trigger=AUTOMATIC_each_h_blank|continues_until_$420C_bit_cleared
cpu_halted_during_dma=YES|all_CPU_cycles_consumed_until_DMA_completes
hdma_preempts_gpdma=YES|GPDMA_pauses_when_HDMA_needs_to_run|resumes_after
> DMA is the SNES's bulk-transfer engine. The 65816 is too slow to push
> 6 KiB of tile data into VRAM during the ~7000-cycle vblank window
> using normal LDA/STA loops, so the system has 8 dedicated DMA channels
> that move data with their own state machines while the CPU is halted.
>
> Each channel has 16 bytes of register space ($43n0-$43nA where n is
> the channel number 0-7) configuring source address, destination
> register, transfer pattern, byte count, and direction. Two completely
> different operating modes use the same channels: General Purpose DMA
> (GPDMA) does a one-shot bulk transfer triggered by the CPU, while
> Horizontal DMA (HDMA) does scheduled per-scanline transfers triggered
> automatically by the PPU.

[SECTION:dma_per_channel_register_map]
desc=detailed_layout_of_$43x0_through_$43xA_for_channel_x
$43x0=DMAPx_DMA_parameter
$43x0.D7=transfer_direction|0=A_to_B|1=B_to_A
$43x0.D6=HDMA_addressing_mode|0=absolute|1=indirect|GPDMA_ignores
$43x0.D5=unused
$43x0.D4=A_bus_address_decrement|0=increment|1=decrement|only_if_D3=0
$43x0.D3=A_bus_address_fixed|0=increment_or_decrement|1=hold
$43x0.D2_D1_D0=transfer_pattern|see_dma_transfer_modes
$43x1=BBADx_B_bus_address|holds_$xx_for_target_$21xx
$43x2=A1Tx_L_A_bus_address_low_byte
$43x3=A1Tx_M_A_bus_address_middle_byte
$43x4=A1Tx_B_A_bus_address_bank
$43x5=DASx_L|GPDMA=byte_count_low|HDMA=indirect_data_addr_low
$43x6=DASx_H|GPDMA=byte_count_high|HDMA=indirect_data_addr_high
$43x7=DASBx|HDMA_indirect_data_address_bank|GPDMA_unused
$43x8=A2Ax_L|HDMA_scratch_table_pointer_low
$43x9=A2Ax_H|HDMA_scratch_table_pointer_high
$43xA=NTRLx|HDMA_line_counter|D7=continue_mode_flag|D6_D0=lines_remaining
> The 16 bytes per channel are reused differently for GPDMA vs HDMA. In
> GPDMA mode, DASx is the byte count (0 means 65536). In HDMA mode, DASx
> is the indirect data address pointer and DASBx is its bank, while NTRLx
> tracks the per-line counter as HDMA chews through the table.

[SECTION:dma_transfer_modes]
desc=$43x0_D2_D1_D0_transfer_pattern_table
mode_0=write_once_to_BBAD_(1_register)_|example_$2122_palette
mode_1=write_low_then_high_to_BBAD_BBAD+1_(2_registers)_|example_VRAM_$2118_$2119
mode_2=write_twice_to_same_BBAD_(1_register_double)_|example_OAM_$2104
mode_3=write_low_low_high_high_to_BBAD_BBAD_BBAD+1_BBAD+1_(2_registers)_|example_BG_scroll
mode_4=write_to_BBAD_BBAD+1_BBAD+2_BBAD+3_(4_registers)_|example_M7A_M7B_M7C_M7D
mode_5=write_low_high_low_high_to_BBAD_BBAD+1_(2_registers)_|alternate_pattern
mode_6=alias_of_mode_2
mode_7=alias_of_mode_3
> The pattern determines how the source byte stream is fed to the
> destination register(s). The B-bus is the PPU register port, so all
> destinations are $21xx (the BBADx low byte specifies which $21xx).
> For VRAM uploads you typically use mode 1 (writes alternate to $2118
> and $2119), so each pair of source bytes becomes one VRAM word. For
> palette uploads use mode 0 (single register $2122 writing both halves
> via the auto-increment in $2121).

[SECTION:dma_general_purpose_procedure]
desc=how_to_actually_perform_a_GPDMA_step_by_step
example_vram_upload_to_$0000=|
  ; Upload 0x1000 bytes from $7E:8000 to VRAM word $0000
  
  ; 1. Set VRAM address
  STZ $2116          ; VMADDL = 0
  STZ $2117          ; VMADDH = 0
  LDA #$80           ; increment after high byte, +1 word per write
  STA $2115          ; VMAIN
  
  ; 2. Configure DMA channel 0
  LDA #$01           ; mode 1 (low/high to 2 regs), A->B, A inc
  STA $4300          ; DMAP0
  LDA #$18           ; B-bus addr = $2118 (VMDATAL)
  STA $4301          ; BBAD0
  LDA #$00           ; A-bus low
  STA $4302          ; A1T0L
  LDA #$80           ; A-bus mid
  STA $4303          ; A1T0M
  LDA #$7E           ; A-bus bank
  STA $4304          ; A1T0B
  LDA #$00           ; byte count low
  STA $4305          ; DAS0L
  LDA #$10           ; byte count high
  STA $4306          ; DAS0H
  
  ; 3. Trigger
  LDA #$01           ; bit 0 = enable channel 0
  STA $420B          ; MDMAEN — DMA starts immediately and runs to completion
  ; CPU is halted here until DMA finishes
> Steps 1 and 2 set up the destination register (VMADD), increment mode,
> and the DMA channel parameters. Step 3 triggers. Once you write to
> $420B, the CPU stops executing instructions and the DMA engine moves
> bytes from the source bank to the B-bus destination at full speed
> (~8 master cycles per byte). When done, the corresponding bit in $420B
> clears and CPU execution resumes at the instruction after the STA $420B.

[SECTION:dma_timing_costs]
desc=cycle_cost_of_DMA_operations
overhead_per_dma=8_master_cycles_init_+_8_per_byte
gpdma_cost=8_master_cycles_per_byte_+_8_master_cycles_initial
gpdma_alignment=DMA_must_synchronize_to_an_8_master_cycle_boundary|adds_0_to_7_master_cycles
example_4kb_dma=4096_bytes*8_master=32768_master_cycles=approx_19_scanlines
example_full_vblank_ntsc_budget=approx_50000_master_cycles=approx_6250_bytes
hdma_per_channel_per_line=approx_18_master_cycles_overhead_+_byte_costs
hdma_setup_at_start_of_frame=approx_18_master_cycles_per_active_channel
> DMA is fast but not instant. A byte takes about 8 master cycles to
> move (i.e., one byte every ~373 nanoseconds). In one NTSC vblank
> (~50000 master cycles after subtracting the IRQ entry overhead and
> other housekeeping), you can move at most ~6 KiB. PAL gives you
> ~12 KiB. If you need more, split the upload across multiple frames.

[SECTION:dma_restrictions_and_quirks]
desc=things_that_will_break_DMA_or_cause_subtle_bugs
> 1) DMA cannot read from B-bus addresses ($21xx) — those are the PPU
>    side. The A-bus is the source/dest with the 24-bit address; the
>    B-bus is the single-byte port at $21xx. So to copy from VRAM to
>    WRAM you set direction $43x0.D7=1 (B->A), B-bus to $2139, and the
>    A-bus to your WRAM destination.
>
> 2) DMA cannot transfer between WRAM and itself via the WMDATA port
>    ($2180) because the source and destination would both be on the
>    A-bus. Use MVN/MVP block move instead.
>
> 3) DMA channels share state with HDMA channels. If you're using
>    channels 0-3 for HDMA per-frame, only channels 4-7 are free for
>    GPDMA. The bit you write to $420B for GPDMA must NOT overlap with
>    the bits you wrote to $420C for HDMA.
>
> 4) During DMA the CPU is HALTED. NMI and IRQ are not serviced; they
>    queue up and fire after DMA completes. So if you trigger a 5KB DMA
>    that lasts 5000 cycles and an IRQ was supposed to fire 100 cycles
>    in, the IRQ fires 4900 cycles late.
>
> 5) GPDMA byte count of 0 means 65536, not 0. So $4305=$00 $4306=$00
>    transfers a full 64KB.
>
> 6) The A-bus address is 24-bit but the bank stays fixed during the
>    transfer — the address increments within a bank and wraps at
>    $FFFF back to $0000 of the same bank, NOT to the next bank. So
>    transferring more than 64KB through a single channel is impossible
>    in one shot; you need multiple DMA calls or chained channels.
>
> 7) HDMA preempts GPDMA. If GPDMA is in progress and an H-blank starts
>    on a line where HDMA is active, GPDMA pauses, HDMA runs to
>    completion, then GPDMA resumes. The total wall-clock time of the
>    GPDMA therefore includes any HDMA overhead.

# =============================================================================
# === HDMA — HORIZONTAL BLANK DMA — DETAILED ===================================
# =============================================================================

[SECTION:hdma_overview_detailed]
desc=H_blank_DMA|automatic_per_scanline_transfers_for_raster_effects
acronym=HDMA=Horizontal_Direct_Memory_Access
how_it_works=at_start_of_each_h_blank_PPU_signals_DMA_engine_to_run_active_HDMA_channels
init_on_each_frame=at_start_of_frame_(scanline_0)_HDMA_engine_reloads_table_pointers
control_register=$420C_HDMAEN
$420C.Dn=enable_HDMA_on_channel_n|persistent
addressing_modes=absolute_(simple)_or_indirect_(table_of_pointers)
addressing_mode_select=$43x0_D6
> HDMA is one of the SNES's signature features and the source of most of
> its visual effects. Instead of running once and stopping like GPDMA,
> HDMA runs automatically every scanline, transferring a small amount of
> data to a PPU register. By changing the destination register's value
> on each scanline, you create per-line effects: gradient skies (palette
> color), parallax (scroll values), perspective (Mode 7 matrix), iris
> wipes (window position), translucent overlays (color math).
>
> The configuration is similar to GPDMA but the meaning of some registers
> changes. The "table" in HDMA is a list of (line_count, data) records
> that the HDMA engine consumes one record at a time. Each record says
> "for the next N scanlines, transfer this data". When N reaches zero,
> the engine moves to the next record. A record with line_count=0
> terminates the table.

[SECTION:hdma_table_format_absolute]
desc=HDMA_absolute_addressing_mode_table_layout
record_byte_0=line_count_byte|D7=continue_flag|D6_D0=line_count_minus_1
record_following_bytes=data_bytes_to_transfer_(transfer_size_per_mode)
table_terminator=line_count_byte=0
example_absolute_table=|
  ; Channel set to mode 0 (1 byte transfer, write once)
  ; Per scanline transfer 1 byte to BBAD destination
  
  hdma_brightness_table:
    .byte 30, $0F     ; for 30 lines, brightness = 15
    .byte 60, $07     ; next 60 lines, brightness = 7  
    .byte 100, $03    ; next 100 lines, brightness = 3
    .byte 0           ; terminate
> In absolute mode, the data is inline in the table — each record has a
> line count followed by N bytes of data depending on the transfer mode.
> Mode 0 = 1 byte per record, mode 1 = 2 bytes, mode 2 = 2 bytes (write
> twice), mode 3 = 4 bytes, etc. The line count's high bit is the
> "continue" mode flag (see below).

[SECTION:hdma_table_format_indirect]
desc=HDMA_indirect_addressing_mode_table_layout
record_byte_0=line_count_(same_as_absolute)
record_bytes_1_2=16bit_pointer_to_actual_data_in_DASBx_bank
data_at_pointer=transfer_size_per_mode|same_as_absolute
table_terminator=line_count_byte=0
> In indirect mode, the table contains POINTERS to data instead of the
> data itself. Each record is 3 bytes: line count, then a 16-bit pointer
> to where the actual data lives (in the bank specified by $43x7 DASBx).
> Indirect lets one HDMA table reference data scattered across memory,
> useful when the data needs to be modified independently of the table
> structure.

[SECTION:hdma_line_counter_behavior]
desc=NTRLx_$43xA_during_HDMA_execution
NTRLx_D7=continue_flag|when_set_engine_keeps_using_SAME_DATA_for_each_line_in_the_count
NTRLx_D6_D0=lines_remaining_in_current_record
> The line counter is the heart of HDMA's table format. Each record's
> first byte is loaded into NTRLx and decremented every scanline. When
> it reaches zero, the engine fetches the next record. The high bit
> (continue mode) controls whether the data bytes are reloaded each
> line or kept the same:
>
> - Continue=0 (line count without high bit set): the data is read
>   ONCE at the start of the record and applied for ALL lines in the
>   count. Use for "stay at this value for N lines, then change".
>
> - Continue=1 (line count with high bit set): the data is read
>   AFRESH on each line (consuming more bytes from the table). Use for
>   "change this register on every scanline for N lines".
>
> Mixing both: a typical gradient sky table might use continue=1 for
> the visible region (scrolling palette per line) and continue=0 for
> the bottom (hold one color).

[SECTION:hdma_use_cases]
desc=common_visual_effects_implemented_via_HDMA
gradient_sky=transfer_to_$2122_CGDATA|change_backdrop_color_per_line
parallax_scroll=transfer_to_$210D_$210E_BG1HOFS_BG1VOFS|different_scroll_per_line
mode7_perspective=transfer_to_$211B_$211E_M7A_M7B_M7C_M7D|change_matrix_per_line_for_floor_perspective
window_position=transfer_to_$2126_$2129_W1L_W1R_W2L_W2R|moving_window_for_iris_or_spotlight
color_math=transfer_to_$2131_CGADSUB|enable_disable_translucency_per_region
brightness_fade=transfer_to_$2100_INIDISP|brightness_per_line_for_fade
bg_mode_change=transfer_to_$2105_BGMODE|RARE_change_BG_mode_mid_frame|enables_split_screen_modes
sample_application_f_zero=Mode_7_floor_with_horizon|HDMA_M7A_M7B_M7C_M7D_per_line_creates_3D_perspective
> HDMA enables effects that would be impossible to do with CPU writes:
> writing to $2100 (master brightness) every line at the right H-blank
> moment to fade the screen with a gradient. The CPU could not keep up
> with 224 writes per frame at the right cycle counts; HDMA does it for
> free.

[SECTION:hdma_timing_costs]
desc=cycle_cost_of_HDMA_per_frame
init_per_frame_per_active_channel=approx_18_master_cycles
per_scanline_per_active_channel=approx_8_master_cycles_overhead_+_byte_transfer_cost
per_byte_transferred=8_master_cycles
example_8_channels_active_2_bytes_each=8_channels*224_lines*(8+16)=43008_master_cycles_per_frame
budget_impact=approx_3_scanlines_of_total_CPU_time_lost_to_HDMA_per_frame
> HDMA is cheap but not free. Each active channel costs ~18 master
> cycles initialization at the start of the frame, then ~8 cycles
> overhead per scanline plus the cost of the bytes themselves. With
> all 8 channels active doing minimal transfers you lose roughly 3
> scanlines of CPU time per frame, leaving the other ~259 lines for
> game logic.

[SECTION:hdma_gotchas]
desc=common_HDMA_pitfalls
> 1) HDMA tables are read from a fixed bank ($43x4 for absolute, $43x7
>    for indirect). The bank does NOT auto-increment. So your table
>    must fit entirely within one bank.
>
> 2) HDMA channels are the SAME 8 as GPDMA. If you're using channel 0
>    for HDMA, channel 0 is unavailable for GPDMA. Pick GPDMA channels
>    not in $420C.
>
> 3) The init at start-of-frame happens at scanline 0 dot ~6. If you
>    set up HDMA registers AFTER scanline 0 starts, you may miss the
>    init for that frame; safest is to configure HDMA during NMI
>    (vblank) so it's ready before the next frame.
>
> 4) HDMA preempts GPDMA, so a long GPDMA that crosses a scanline
>    boundary will be paused for HDMA's run. This is fine but unexpected
>    timing variation can cascade.
>
> 5) Disabling HDMA mid-frame (clearing $420C bit) does NOT take effect
>    until the next scanline boundary, and the engine may have already
>    advanced its table pointer for the current line.
>
> 6) HDMA SCROLL gotcha: writing scroll registers $210D-$2114 via HDMA
>    requires careful sequencing because of the write-twice latch. Use
>    transfer mode that writes the right number of bytes for the
>    register pair you target.
>
> 7) HDMA mid-screen mode change ($2105 BGMODE) is possible but the new
>    mode does not fully take effect until the next scanline; some
>    registers (like BG scroll) lag.

# =============================================================================
# === PPU SUBSYSTEM — VIDEO REFERENCE =========================================
# =============================================================================

[SECTION:ppu_overview]
desc=Picture_Processing_Unit|two_chips_PPU1_5C77_and_PPU2_5C78
chips=PPU1=5C77_(background_generation_and_VRAM_access)|PPU2=5C78_(window_color_math_main_sub_compositing)
output=composite_video_to_TV
clock=master/4_one_dot_per_4_master_cycles
visible=256x224_default|256x239_with_$2133.D2|512x224_in_modes_5_6
backgrounds_simultaneously=up_to_4_(in_mode_0)
sprites=up_to_128_via_OAM
modes=8_BG_modes_(0..7)_with_different_layer_counts_and_color_depths
features=mosaic|color_math_add_subtract|window_clipping|scrolling|priority|hires|interlace|mode7_affine|EXTBG
> The PPU is actually two chips that talk to a shared VRAM and CGRAM.
> PPU1 (5C77) is responsible for fetching tile data, computing background
> pixels with rotation/scaling for Mode 7, and producing the layer pixels.
> PPU2 (5C78) handles the window masks, the color math (add/subtract for
> translucency), and the final composition of main and sub screens. From
> a programmer's perspective they appear as one register file at $2100-$213F.

[SECTION:ppu_bg_modes_detailed]
desc=8_background_modes_with_color_depth_and_layer_count
mode_0=4_layers|2bpp_2bpp_2bpp_2bpp|4_colors_per_layer|8_palettes_each
mode_0_use=rare|tetris_attack_simple_overlays
mode_1=3_layers|4bpp_4bpp_2bpp|16_16_4_colors|MOST_COMMON_MODE
mode_1_use=most_action_RPG_platformer_games|BG3_often_HUD
mode_1_priority_quirk=$2105.D3=1_makes_BG3_appear_above_BG1_BG2_priority_layers
mode_2=2_layers|4bpp_4bpp|offset_per_tile|BG3_provides_offsets
mode_2_use=Star_Ocean_water_distortion|some_visual_effects
mode_3=2_layers|8bpp_4bpp|256_color_BG1|direct_color_supported
mode_3_use=detailed_backgrounds|Final_Fantasy_VI_train_scene
mode_4=2_layers|8bpp_2bpp|offset_per_tile
mode_4_use=mostly_used_with_offset_per_tile_for_unique_effects
mode_5=2_layers|4bpp_2bpp|512_pixels_horizontal_HIRES
mode_5_use=Seiken_Densetsu_3_menus|RPG_dialogues|HIRES_text
mode_6=1_layer|4bpp|512_horizontal|offset_per_tile
mode_6_use=very_rare
mode_7=1_layer|8bpp|AFFINE_TRANSFORM|matrix_M7A_M7B_M7C_M7D
mode_7_use=F-Zero|Pilotwings|Mario_Kart|Super_Castlevania_IV_rotating_room
mode_7_extbg=$2133.D6=1_enables_EXTBG_high_bit_of_pixel_used_as_priority_for_pseudo_2nd_layer
> The mode determines the trade-off between number of layers and colors
> per layer. Mode 1 is the workhorse: three backgrounds with 16 colors
> on the main two and 4 colors on BG3 (typically used for HUD/text). The
> total color budget across all layers is 256 colors in CGRAM regardless
> of mode, but how those colors are partitioned across layers and palettes
> changes per mode. In 4bpp mode each layer can use 16 of the 256 colors
> in any of 16 palettes; in 8bpp mode the layer can use all 256 colors
> directly.

[SECTION:ppu_bg_tile_data_format]
desc=how_tile_pixel_data_is_stored_in_VRAM
2bpp_planar=8x8_tile_=_16_bytes
2bpp_layout=row0_plane0|row0_plane1|row1_plane0|row1_plane1|...|row7_plane0|row7_plane1
2bpp_pixel_assembly=for_each_pixel_in_row_combine_bit_from_plane_0_(LSB)_with_bit_from_plane_1_(bit_1)_to_get_2bit_color_index
4bpp_planar=8x8_tile_=_32_bytes
4bpp_layout=first_16_bytes_=_planes_0_1_in_2bpp_format|then_16_bytes_=_planes_2_3_in_2bpp_format
4bpp_pixel_assembly=combine_4_bits_from_4_planes_per_pixel
8bpp_planar=8x8_tile_=_64_bytes
8bpp_layout=four_2bpp_blocks_in_sequence|planes_0_1_then_2_3_then_4_5_then_6_7
mode_7_format=8x8_tile_=_64_bytes_LINEAR
mode_7_layout=byte_pairs_(map_byte_data_byte)_interleaved_in_VRAM|odd_bytes_=_tile_data|even_bytes_=_tilemap_index
> The planar format is the SNES's clever way to make 4bpp/8bpp tiles
> easy to address per-pixel. Each "row" within a tile is split into
> bitplanes; pixel N in that row gets one bit from each plane. To
> assemble pixel 0 (leftmost) of row 0 in a 4bpp tile: take bit 7 of
> byte 0 (plane 0), bit 7 of byte 1 (plane 1), bit 7 of byte 16 (plane 2),
> bit 7 of byte 17 (plane 3). Combine those four bits into a 4-bit
> palette index. Sounds complex but the planes are word-interleaved so
> hardware can fetch a row of pixels with two consecutive word reads.
> Mode 7 uses an entirely different layout where each tile is 64 bytes
> linear (one byte per pixel) and the tilemap is interleaved with the
> tile data in VRAM.

[SECTION:ppu_bg_tilemap_format]
desc=16_bit_tilemap_entry_layout
entry_size=2_bytes_(16_bits)
D9_D0=character_index|0..1023_selects_tile_within_chr_data
D12_D10=palette_index|0..7
D13=priority_bit|see_priority_section
D14=horizontal_flip
D15=vertical_flip
> Each tile slot in a background's tilemap is a single 16-bit word
> containing the tile index, palette, priority, and H/V flip flags. The
> 10 bits of tile index limit each background to 1024 distinct tiles —
> if you need more, you switch tilemaps mid-frame via HDMA or use the
> larger 64x64 tilemap layout.

[SECTION:ppu_bg_tilemap_size_layout]
desc=tilemap_arrangement_in_VRAM_for_different_$2107_$210A_sizes
size_$00=32x32_(2KB)_(1024_entries_=_2048_bytes)
size_$01=64x32_(4KB)
size_$02=32x64_(4KB)
size_$03=64x64_(8KB)
quadrant_layout_64x64=4_quadrants_of_32x32_tilemaps_in_sequence|TL_TR_BL_BR
> A 32x32 tilemap is the basic unit (256x256 pixels). Larger maps are
> arranged as multiple 32x32 quadrants in sequence. For 64x64, the four
> quadrants in VRAM order are top-left, top-right, bottom-left,
> bottom-right. Software that scrolls a 64x64 map must handle the
> quadrant boundary explicitly because the layout is not a simple linear
> array.

[SECTION:ppu_bg_tile_chr_base_explained]
desc=where_tile_pixel_data_lives|set_via_$210B_$210C
$210B.D3_D0=BG1_chr_base|in_4K_word_(8_KiB)_units
$210B.D7_D4=BG2_chr_base
$210C.D3_D0=BG3_chr_base
$210C.D7_D4=BG4_chr_base
nibble_meaning=value*$1000_=_VRAM_word_offset|so_value_$2_means_word_$2000_=_byte_$4000
> Each BG layer's pixel data starts at a configurable VRAM offset
> specified in 8 KiB units. So you can pack BG1 tiles starting at VRAM
> word $0000, BG2 at word $1000, BG3 at word $2000, etc. Tilemaps live
> separately and are pointed to by $2107-$210A in 1 KiB units (2048 byte
> units). Plan your VRAM layout so chr data and tilemap don't overlap.

[SECTION:ppu_bg_priority]
desc=which_pixel_wins_when_multiple_layers_overlap
> The PPU resolves overlapping pixels using a per-mode priority order.
> Each tilemap entry has a priority bit (D13) that puts the tile in
> "high priority" or "low priority" within the layer. Then within each
> mode there is a fixed ordering between BG1 high, BG1 low, BG2 high,
> BG2 low, BG3 high, BG3 low, OBJ priority 0, OBJ priority 1, etc.

mode_1_priority_default_high_to_low=|
  BG3 priority 1 (if $2105.D3=1)
  OBJ priority 3
  BG1 priority 1
  BG2 priority 1
  OBJ priority 2
  BG1 priority 0
  BG2 priority 0
  OBJ priority 1
  BG3 priority 1 (if $2105.D3=0)
  OBJ priority 0
  BG3 priority 0
  backdrop

[SECTION:ppu_bg_scroll]
desc=BG_scroll_register_writes
$210D=BG1HOFS|write_twice_low_high|13_bit_only_low_8_+_high_3
$210E=BG1VOFS|write_twice_low_high
$210F=BG2HOFS|same_pattern
$2110=BG2VOFS
$2111=BG3HOFS
$2112=BG3VOFS
$2113=BG4HOFS
$2114=BG4VOFS
write_twice_quirk=writes_share_an_internal_latch|sequence_must_be_low_then_high
mode7_share=$210D_writes_BOTH_BG1HOFS_AND_M7HOFS|$210E_BOTH_BG1VOFS_AND_M7VOFS
> Scroll registers are 13-bit values written as two consecutive bytes.
> The internal write latch toggles between expecting low and high. After
> a warm reset the latch state is undefined; cold reset code should write
> low byte twice to be safe (the high byte will then be a no-op until
> the latch resets). Mode 7 uses $210D and $210E for both BG1 and Mode 7
> scroll, so writing to those registers in Mode 7 affects both — usually
> not what you want, so Mode 7 software writes them once at scene setup
> and lets HDMA handle the per-line matrix updates instead.

[SECTION:ppu_oam_layout]
desc=Object_Attribute_Memory|sprite_storage|544_bytes_total
total_bytes=544
low_table_bytes=512|holds_4_byte_records_for_128_sprites
high_table_bytes=32|holds_2_bits_per_sprite_for_high_position_bit_and_size_select
sprite_count=128
> OAM is a tiny 544-byte RAM dedicated to sprite metadata. It is split
> into two tables: a 512-byte "low" table holding the bulk of each
> sprite's record (X, Y, tile, attributes), and a 32-byte "high" table
> packing two extra bits per sprite (the X position high bit and the
> size selector). The high table being 2 bits per sprite means it's
> tightly packed: each high-table byte contains the bits for 4 sprites.

oam_low_record_4_bytes=|
  byte 0: X position low byte (0-255)
  byte 1: Y position (0-255, but visible region is 0-223 or 0-238)
  byte 2: tile number low byte (0-255)
  byte 3: attributes:
    bit 0: tile number high bit (combined with byte 2 = 9 bits = 0-511 tiles)
    bits 3-1: palette select (0-7) -- sprite palettes are CGRAM 128-255
    bits 5-4: priority (0-3)
    bit 6: horizontal flip
    bit 7: vertical flip

oam_high_record_2_bits=|
  bit 0: X position high bit (combined with low byte X = 9 bits = -256..255 signed)
  bit 1: size select (0=small, 1=large; small/large dimensions per OBJSEL $2101)

oam_sprite_palettes_in_cgram=palettes_8..15|or_in_256_color_terms_CGRAM_indices_128..255
oam_priority_layers=4_priorities_0_to_3|see_priority_section_for_layering_with_BG

[SECTION:ppu_oam_access_rules]
desc=when_OAM_can_be_safely_written
$2102_$2103=OAMADDL_OAMADDH|set_OAM_word_address_(0..255_for_low_table_+_higher_for_high_table)
$2104=OAMDATA|write_twice_low_high|writes_to_low_table_or_high_table_based_on_address
write_window=forced_blank_($2100.D7=1)_or_vblank_only|writes_during_active_display_corrupt_OAM
auto_reload_at_vblank=OAM_address_reloads_to_value_set_in_$2102_$2103_at_start_of_each_vblank
typical_pattern=DMA_full_OAM_during_NMI|use_GPDMA_with_BBAD_$2104_mode_2
oam_dma_size=544_bytes
> The OAM access rules trip up new programmers. The PPU is constantly
> reading OAM during the visible display to draw sprites; if you write
> at the wrong time you corrupt active sprite data. The safe windows are
> forced blank (when you've set $2100 bit 7 to halt the PPU) and vblank.
> The standard pattern is to maintain a "shadow OAM" in WRAM during the
> frame and DMA it to OAM in NMI. The DMA is one channel, mode 2 (write
> twice to $2104), 544 bytes, ~70 microseconds.

[SECTION:ppu_oam_per_line_limits]
desc=hardware_limits_on_visible_sprites_per_scanline
range_over_max=32_OBJs_per_line|33rd_or_beyond_NOT_displayed
range_over_flag=$213E.D6_set_for_a_frame_when_exceeded
time_over_max=34_8x8_quanta_per_line_(approximately_272_pixels_of_sprite_width)
time_over_flag=$213E.D7_set_for_a_frame_when_exceeded
priority_rotation_to_avoid_starvation=$2103.D7_enables_OBJ_priority_rotation_through_OAM_address
workaround_flickering=alternate_visible_sprites_each_frame_to_create_perceptual_increase
> The 32-sprite-per-line limit is one of the SNES's most famous
> constraints. If your game has more than 32 sprites overlapping a single
> scanline, only the first 32 (in priority order) draw; the rest disappear
> for that line. The 34-quanta limit is a separate constraint based on
> total horizontal sprite width: each 8x8 pixel block counts as one
> "quantum", so a single 64x64 sprite uses 8 quanta per line. Together
> these limits cap visible sprite content at roughly 256 8x8 quanta per
> line.
>
> Games work around the limit using priority rotation: by rotating which
> sprite has the highest priority every frame, no single sprite gets
> permanently dropped — they all flicker instead, which is more visually
> tolerable than missing sprites. Set $2103.D7=1 and write the desired
> rotation seed to $2102 D1-D7 each frame.

[SECTION:ppu_cgram_layout]
desc=Color_Generator_RAM|256_colors_total|15_bit_BGR
size_bytes=512
size_colors=256
color_format=15_bit_BGR
color_layout_low_byte=GGGRRRRR
color_layout_high_byte=0BBBBBGG
combined_word=0BBBBBGGGGGRRRRR
red_range=0..31
green_range=0..31
blue_range=0..31
bit_15=unused|writes_ignored
> CGRAM holds the actual color values that pixels reference. Each color
> is 15 bits packed into 16: 5 bits red, 5 green, 5 blue, with bit 15
> ignored. The packing across two bytes is little-endian word style:
> the low byte contains red and the low 3 bits of green, the high byte
> contains the high 2 bits of green and all 5 bits of blue. So writing
> $E0 then $7F gives R=0, G=$1F (full), B=$1F (full) = full cyan.
>
> 256 colors total is the global palette. Background tiles in 4bpp mode
> can pick any 16-color subset (one of 16 palettes); 8bpp tiles use the
> full 256. Sprite tiles use the upper half of CGRAM (palettes 8-15 in
> 4bpp, indices 128-255). Color 0 of any palette is treated as
> transparent for tiles, except for the BG color 0 which is the
> backdrop.

[SECTION:ppu_cgram_access]
desc=how_to_read_write_CGRAM
$2121=CGADD|set_CGRAM_word_address_0..255
$2122=CGDATA|write_twice_low_then_high|each_word_is_one_color
$213B=CGDATAREAD|read_twice_low_then_high
write_window=forced_blank_or_vblank
auto_increment=after_each_write_pair_address_advances_by_1
typical_pattern=set_$2121_to_palette_start|GPDMA_to_$2122_mode_0|transfers_2_bytes_per_color_in_sequence
palette_dma=for_a_full_256_color_palette_use_512_byte_dma_via_channel
> CGRAM access is similar to VRAM but smaller and simpler: set the
> address with $2121, then write color words to $2122 (twice each, low
> then high). The address auto-increments. Most games keep a "shadow
> palette" in WRAM, modify it during gameplay (for fade effects, day/night
> cycles, hit flashes), and DMA it to CGRAM in NMI.

[SECTION:ppu_color_math]
desc=add_subtract_translucency_using_main_and_sub_screens
> Color math is the SNES's translucency mechanism. The PPU composes the
> final image in two passes: a "main" screen (the visible image) and a
> "sub" screen (the secondary image). Then for each pixel where color
> math is enabled, the main pixel value is combined with either the sub
> pixel value or a fixed background color via add or subtract. This
> creates effects like waterfalls (main = water tile, sub = scenery
> behind, math = add giving lightening effect), ghosts (main = ghost,
> sub = floor, math = subtract giving darkening), and HUD overlays
> (translucent menu boxes).

main_screen_layers=$212C_TM|D0_BG1|D1_BG2|D2_BG3|D3_BG4|D4_OBJ
sub_screen_layers=$212D_TS|same_bit_layout
math_enable=$2131_CGADSUB
$2131.D0_D5=enable_for_BG1_BG2_BG3_BG4_OBJ_4to7_BACKDROP
$2131.D6=half_result|0=full|1=halved_result_to_avoid_overflow
$2131.D7=mode|0=add|1=subtract
fixed_color_source=$2132_COLDATA|writes_R_G_B_components_separately
math_window_main=$2130_CGSWSEL_D5_D4
math_window_sub=$2130_CGSWSEL_D7_D6
direct_color_mode=$2130.D0|in_modes_3_4_7_tile_data_directly_indexes_color
> Setting up color math: enable layers in TM/TS, then in $2131 enable
> per-layer math participation, set add or subtract, set half or full,
> and configure the windows. Most basic translucency uses subtract+half
> on the main screen with the sub screen showing the background. The
> half flag is critical: without it, addition can overflow ($1F+$10=$2F
> which truncates wrong) and subtraction can underflow.
>
> OBJ math limitation: only sprite palettes 4-7 participate in color
> math (set via $2131.D4 enabling OBJ4to7). Palettes 0-3 always render
> opaque. This is the famous "use specific sprite palettes for ghosts"
> rule.

[SECTION:ppu_window_logic]
desc=window_clipping_for_layers
> Windows are rectangular regions defined by a left and right pixel
> position. The SNES has 2 independent window definitions (W1 and W2),
> each with a left bound (WH0/WH2) and right bound (WH1/WH3). Each
> background and OBJ layer can be enabled to participate in either or
> both windows, with per-window inversion (mask is INSIDE or OUTSIDE
> the window) and per-layer logic combining W1 and W2 (OR, AND, XOR,
> XNOR).
>
> Use cases: spotlight (one circular window via HDMA changing W1L/W1R
> per scanline), iris wipes (window growing each frame), masking off
> the HUD region from color math, restricting an effect to a specific
> screen area.

window_definitions=$2126_WH0_W1_left|$2127_WH1_W1_right|$2128_WH2_W2_left|$2129_WH3_W2_right
layer_window_select=$2123_W12SEL_BG1_BG2|$2124_W34SEL_BG3_BG4|$2125_WOBJSEL_OBJ_MATH
selection_byte_layout=2_nibbles_one_per_layer|each_nibble_D0_w1_invert|D1_w1_enable|D2_w2_invert|D3_w2_enable
combination_logic=$212A_WBGLOG_BG1_BG4|$212B_WOBJLOG_OBJ_MATH
combination_codes=00=OR|01=AND|10=XOR|11=XNOR
main_window_mask=$212E_TMW|disables_layer_in_main_screen_INSIDE_window
sub_window_mask=$212F_TSW|same_for_sub_screen
> A common iris wipe HDMA: set up channel for $2126 (W1L) and $2127 (W1R)
> with mode 1 (write low, write high to consecutive registers). Build a
> table where each scanline's W1L and W1R values describe a circle's
> intersection with that line. Result: animated circular iris.

[SECTION:ppu_mode7_math]
desc=Mode_7_affine_transform_equations
matrix=2x2_signed_fixed_point|M7A_M7B_M7C_M7D|each_8.8_signed_format
center=M7X_M7Y|13_bit_signed
scroll=M7HOFS_M7VOFS|via_$210D_$210E_shared_with_BG1
formula_x_prime=M7A*(X+M7HOFS-M7X)+M7B*(Y+M7VOFS-M7Y)+M7X*256
formula_y_prime=M7C*(X+M7HOFS-M7X)+M7D*(Y+M7VOFS-M7Y)+M7Y*256
note=screen_(X,Y)_is_input_pixel_position|(X',Y')_is_index_into_128x128_tilemap
matrix_layout=|
  | M7A  M7B |   | X - M7X + M7HOFS |   | M7X*256 |
  |          | * |                  | + |         |
  | M7C  M7D |   | Y - M7Y + M7VOFS |   | M7Y*256 |
> The Mode 7 affine transform takes each visible pixel's screen position,
> translates by the matrix center (M7X, M7Y) and scroll offset, applies
> the 2x2 matrix, and translates back. The result is a pair of texture
> coordinates X' and Y' that index into the 128x128-tile Mode 7 background.
> M7A controls the X-axis horizontal scaling (along with rotation), M7B
> controls the Y-axis horizontal contribution (skew/rotation), M7C
> controls X-axis vertical contribution, M7D controls Y-axis vertical
> scaling.
>
> For a simple rotation by angle θ: M7A = cos(θ), M7B = -sin(θ),
> M7C = sin(θ), M7D = cos(θ), all in 8.8 fixed point (so cos(0) = $0100,
> sin(45°) ≈ $00B5). For zoom by 2x: M7A = M7D = $0080, M7B = M7C = 0.
>
> The famous "racing game floor" effect uses HDMA to change M7A-M7D every
> scanline so the matrix's effective scale grows with screen Y, creating
> the illusion of perspective. The math is roughly: at line N, scale =
> $0100 * (horizon_distance / (N - horizon_y)). Pre-compute a per-line
> table at scene setup and HDMA it.

[SECTION:ppu_mode7_extbg]
desc=EXTBG_pseudo_second_layer_in_Mode_7
control=$2133.D6=1_enables_EXTBG
operation=Mode_7_pixel_high_bit_(D7)_used_as_priority_for_a_second_layer
result=appears_to_split_the_8bpp_palette_into_two_7bpp_layers
use=Tales_of_Phantasia|Pilotwings|some_RPGs_for_overlay_on_Mode_7_background
> EXTBG is a clever hack that gets a second pseudo-layer out of Mode 7
> by reinterpreting the high bit of each pixel. Pixels with bit 7 set
> appear in front of normal layers; pixels with bit 7 clear appear
> behind. So you effectively get a 7-bit-color background and a 7-bit-
> color foreground sharing the same Mode 7 layer. The palette is
> halved (128 colors per layer instead of 256), and the trick is
> usually used to put a HUD or character sprite on top of a rotating
> Mode 7 floor.

[SECTION:ppu_vram_access_rules]
desc=safe_windows_and_quirks_for_VRAM_writes
write_window=forced_blank_($2100.D7=1)_or_vblank_only
read_window=same
write_during_display=garbage_or_corruption|PPU_is_actively_fetching_so_writes_collide
auto_increment=via_$2115_VMAIN
$2115.D1_D0=increment_amount|00=+1|01=+32|10=+128|11=+128
$2115.D3_D2=address_remap|see_address_remap_section
$2115.D7=increment_after_high_byte|0=after_$2118|1=after_$2119
typical_value=$80_(+1_word_increment_after_high_byte)
> VRAM writes are word-oriented: each $2118/$2119 pair forms one 16-bit
> word at the current VMADD address. The auto-increment is critical for
> bulk DMA: after writing the high byte (or low, per $2115.D7), the
> address advances by 1, 32, or 128 words. The "+32" mode is used for
> uploading column-major tile data into a row-major tilemap area; the
> "+128" mode is used for some Mode 7 tile data layouts.

[SECTION:ppu_vram_address_remap]
desc=$2115_D3_D2_address_remap_modes_for_chr_data
$2115.D3_D2=00=no_remap|address_used_as_is
$2115.D3_D2=01=remap_for_2bpp_tile_format|swizzles_address_to_match_tile_planar_layout
$2115.D3_D2=10=remap_for_4bpp_tile_format
$2115.D3_D2=11=remap_for_8bpp_tile_format
> The remap modes let you write SEQUENTIAL bytes from a source and have
> the hardware reorganize them into the planar tile format described
> earlier. Without remap, you would have to manually reshuffle bytes to
> get plane 0 row 0, plane 1 row 0, plane 0 row 1, etc. With remap, the
> hardware does it. Useful for streaming compressed tile data that
> decompresses into linear order.

[SECTION:ppu_vram_read_prefetch_quirk]
desc=VRAM_read_prefetch_latch_behavior_first_read_returns_garbage
mechanism=$2139_$213A_have_a_prefetch_latch
sequence=after_setting_VMADD_first_read_returns_value_from_PREVIOUS_address|second_read_returns_actual_value
fix=ALWAYS_dummy_read_after_setting_VMADD_then_real_reads_after
> If you set VMADD to $1234 and then read $2139, you get whatever was
> at the previously-latched address, NOT $1234. The hardware prefetches
> the next word, so you must dummy-read once to "prime" the latch. This
> is the most common VRAM-reading bug — code that copies VRAM data to
> WRAM gets all results shifted by one position.

# =============================================================================
# === PPU REGISTERS — DETAILED, EVERY REGISTER, EVERY BIT =====================
# =============================================================================

[SECTION:ppu_register_$2100]
name=INIDISP|access=W|init_at_reset=$8F
D7=force_blank|1=display_off,VRAM_OAM_CGRAM_freely_accessible_anytime
D3..D0=master_brightness|0=black|F=full|each_step=approximately_1/15_intensity
> $2100 is THE register you write at the start of every NMI to enter forced
> blank if you need to do bulk VRAM/OAM/CGRAM uploads outside of vblank.
> Write $80 to enter forced blank with brightness 0 (black). Write $0F at
> the end of vblank to leave forced blank with full brightness. The brightness
> field is applied as a global multiplier on the final pixel output, which is
> how fade-in/fade-out effects are done — just ramp $2100 from $00 to $0F or
> back over a series of frames.
gotcha=writing_$2100_does_NOT_clear_high_bit_of_$213F_until_OAM_address_reset_runs

[SECTION:ppu_register_$2101]
name=OBSEL|access=W|purpose=object_size_and_VRAM_base_select
D7..D5=size_select_index_into_table_below
D4..D3=name_select|adds_offset_to_secondary_4K_word_block
D2..D0=name_base_select|upper_3_bits_of_8K_word_aligned_VRAM_base_for_OBJ_tiles
size_table.0=8x8_and_16x16
size_table.1=8x8_and_32x32
size_table.2=8x8_and_64x64
size_table.3=16x16_and_32x32
size_table.4=16x16_and_64x64
size_table.5=32x32_and_64x64
size_table.6=16x32_and_32x64_undocumented
size_table.7=16x32_and_32x32_undocumented
> Sprites can be one of two sizes per frame, selected per-sprite via OAM
> table bit. The size_table picks BOTH sizes available. The "name base" is
> in 8K-word units (16 KiB), and "name select" provides an additional 4K-word
> offset for the OBJ "second page" used to support multiple sprite tile sets
> without re-uploading. VRAM is 64 KiB total, organized as 32K words.

[SECTION:ppu_register_$2102_$2103]
name=OAMADDL_OAMADDH|access=W|sequence=write_$2102_then_$2103
$2102=OAM_address_low_8_bits|word_addressable
$2103.D7=OBJ_priority_rotation_enable|when_set_OAM_iteration_starts_at_word_address
$2103.D0=OAM_address_high_bit_(a8)
> The address space is 0..255 in word units (so 0..511 bytes for the 512-byte
> OAM low area). High OAM (32 bytes of attribute) is auto-addressed via the
> upper bits. Writing $2103 also resets the byte-write toggle for $2104.
> "Priority rotation" makes whichever OBJ index you set the start of OAM
> iteration take rendering priority — used to defeat the per-line 32-sprite
> limit by rotating which sprites get evaluated first each frame.
oam_address_reset=at_start_of_vblank_when_$2100_force_blank_is_clear|address_is_reloaded_from_$2102_$2103_latch_at_H=10_V=225

[SECTION:ppu_register_$2104]
name=OAMDATA|access=W|sequence=write_twice_low_then_high_for_low_OAM|once_for_high_OAM
> OAM has a write-twice quirk: the byte-write toggle starts at "low" after
> writing $2102 or $2103. Each pair of bytes writes one OAM word at the
> current address, then auto-increments. Writes to high OAM ($100..$10F
> word range, i.e. address 256..271) take a single byte not a pair, because
> high OAM is byte-organized. Writing during active rendering corrupts OAM —
> only safe in forced blank or vblank.

[SECTION:ppu_register_$2105]
name=BGMODE|access=W
D2..D0=BG_mode_0..7
D3=BG3_priority_high_in_mode_1|0=normal|1=BG3_high_priority_tiles_become_top_layer
D4=BG1_tile_size|0=8x8|1=16x16
D5=BG2_tile_size|0=8x8|1=16x16
D6=BG3_tile_size|0=8x8|1=16x16
D7=BG4_tile_size|0=8x8|1=16x16
> BG mode determines color depth, layer count, and special features. See
> ppu_bg_modes_detailed. Tile size of 16x16 means each tilemap entry covers
> 16x16 pixels — internally the PPU still fetches four 8x8 character tiles
> in a 2x2 arrangement, with the tile number derived from the base tile +
> [+0,+1,+16,+17]. The "BG3 priority high" bit ($2105.D3) is what makes the
> Mario World/Zelda HUD render in front of everything; BG3 tiles with their
> priority bit set become the absolute frontmost layer.

[SECTION:ppu_register_$2106]
name=MOSAIC|access=W
D7..D4=mosaic_size|0=1x1(off)|F=16x16
D3..D0=mosaic_enable_per_BG|D0=BG1|D1=BG2|D2=BG3|D3=BG4
> Mosaic replicates the upper-left pixel of each NxN block across the
> block, creating a chunky pixelated effect. Used for transitions (Final
> Fantasy battle scene fade-in), explosions, and damage flash effects.
> The size field is "size minus 1" so $0 = 1x1 (effectively off), $F = 16x16.

[SECTION:ppu_register_$2107_$210A]
name=BG1SC..BG4SC|access=W|purpose=tilemap_base_address_and_size_per_BG
D7..D2=tilemap_base_in_VRAM|units_of_1K_word=2KiB|so_value*$0400_in_word_addresses
D1..D0=tilemap_size|00=32x32(1_screen)|01=64x32(2H)|10=32x64(2V)|11=64x64(4_screens)
$2107=BG1SC|$2108=BG2SC|$2109=BG3SC|$210A=BG4SC
> Each tilemap is 32x32 entries minimum (=2 KiB at 2 bytes per entry). For
> 64x32 the second screen sits IMMEDIATELY after the first in VRAM (so the
> next 2 KiB block). For 32x64, same. For 64x64, four 2 KiB blocks
> consecutively. The tilemap "base" is a 1K-word stride (= 2 KiB), so writing
> $00 puts the tilemap at VRAM word $0000, $04 at $0400 (= byte $0800), etc.
> Common pattern: BG1 tilemap at $0000 (uses $0000..$07FF if 32x32), BG2 at
> $0800, BG3 at $1000, BG4 at $1800, leaving $2000..$FFFF for character data.

[SECTION:ppu_register_$210B_$210C]
name=BG12NBA_BG34NBA|access=W|purpose=tile_character_data_base_per_BG
$210B.D3..D0=BG1_chr_base|units_of_4K_word=8KiB
$210B.D7..D4=BG2_chr_base
$210C.D3..D0=BG3_chr_base
$210C.D7..D4=BG4_chr_base
> Each BG has its own 4K-word stride for the start of its tile graphics.
> Value $0 means tiles start at VRAM word $0000, $1 at $1000, etc. Note
> the conflict potential — if BG1 chr base is at $0000 but BG1 tilemap is
> ALSO at $0000, the first tilemap entries will be interpreted as garbage
> tile graphics. Always plan VRAM layout carefully. A common 4 KiB layout
> for Mode 1: BG3 chr at $0000 (2 KiB for ASCII font), BG1 chr at $1000
> (8 KiB), BG2 chr at $1800 (8 KiB), tilemaps at $3000+, OBJ tiles at $4000+.

[SECTION:ppu_register_$210D_$2114]
name=BGnHOFS_BGnVOFS|access=W|sequence=write_low_then_high_each_call_(double_write)
$210D=BG1HOFS|shared_with_M7HOFS_in_mode_7
$210E=BG1VOFS|shared_with_M7VOFS
$210F=BG2HOFS|$2110=BG2VOFS
$2111=BG3HOFS|$2112=BG3VOFS
$2113=BG4HOFS|$2114=BG4VOFS
range=10_bits_(0..1023)|in_mode_7_signed_13_bits_(-4096..4095)
double_write_quirk=hardware_uses_a_shared_high_byte_buffer_per_register
old_value_buffer=$210D_writes_low_byte_then_$210D_writes_high_byte
> Scroll registers are write-twice. Each write to $210D (and similar) goes
> to a 16-bit register where the FIRST write goes to the LOW byte and the
> SECOND write goes to the HIGH byte. The actual hardware behavior is: low
> byte = (current_value & 0xFF00) | new_byte; high byte = ((new_byte & 0x03)
> << 8) | (prev_low & 0xF8) | ((current_value >> 8) & 0x07). This is the
> "PPU offset register quirk" — there's a single shared latch BG1HOFS uses
> that other registers also touch, leading to subtle bugs. ALWAYS write
> scroll values in pairs and never assume a known starting state.
mode7_quirk=writing_$210D_or_$210E_writes_BOTH_BG1_scroll_AND_M7_scroll_simultaneously

[SECTION:ppu_register_$2115]
name=VMAIN|access=W|purpose=VRAM_address_increment_and_remap_control
D7=increment_after_high_byte|0=increment_after_$2118_or_$2139_low_read|1=after_$2119_or_$213A_high_read
D3..D2=full_graphic_remap_mode|00=none|01=2bpp|10=4bpp|11=8bpp
D1..D0=increment_amount|00=+1|01=+32|10=+128|11=+128
typical_value=$80|increment_after_high_byte_word_writes_+1_per_step
> $2115 is set ONCE per VRAM upload session and controls how the VRAM
> address advances. Value $80 (the most common) means: after each word write
> to $2118/$2119, advance the address by 1 word. This is for normal tile and
> tilemap writes where you stream sequential words. Value $00 (less common)
> means advance by 1 BYTE after each low-byte write — useful for Mode 7
> tilemap which is interleaved.
vram_remap_modes=address_remapping_for_streaming_compressed_tiles_into_planar_format
remap_quirk=remap_only_affects_address_TRANSLATION_for_each_access|underlying_VMADD_value_unchanged

[SECTION:ppu_register_$2116_$2117]
name=VMADDL_VMADDH|access=W|word_aligned_VRAM_address|max_$7FFF
> Set the VRAM word address before any read or write. The address is 15-bit
> word-addressable (so addresses 32K words = 64 KiB). Writes to $2116 and
> $2117 do NOT trigger any read prefetch — that only happens after a real
> $2139/$213A read. So you can set VMADD freely.
read_setup_pattern=set_VMADD|dummy_read_$2139_or_$213A_to_prime_prefetch|then_real_reads

[SECTION:ppu_register_$2118_$2119]
name=VMDATAL_VMDATAH|access=W|the_actual_VRAM_data_port
> $2118 writes the LOW byte at the current word address. $2119 writes the
> HIGH byte. Auto-increment occurs based on $2115.D7. Most code does word
> writes via STA $2118 with 16-bit accumulator (writes both bytes), then
> the increment fires after the high byte goes through.
DMA_pattern=set_VMADD|set_$2115=$80|GPDMA_mode_1_to_$2118_with_word_data_source

[SECTION:ppu_register_$211A]
name=M7SEL|access=W|mode_7_screen_setup
D0=mode7_horizontal_flip
D1=mode7_vertical_flip
D7..D6=screen_overflow_behavior|00=wrap|10=transparent|11=fill_with_tile_0
> When the Mode 7 transformation maps a screen pixel to a position outside
> the 1024x1024 Mode 7 plane, this register decides what happens. Wrap means
> the plane tiles infinitely. Transparent means the pixel becomes the
> backdrop color (lets you put other layers behind a small Mode 7 region).
> Fill with tile 0 means out-of-bounds pixels show character $00.

[SECTION:ppu_register_$211B_$2120]
name=M7A_M7B_M7C_M7D_M7X_M7Y|access=W|sequence=write_low_then_high
$211B=M7A_signed_16|$211C=M7B_signed_16|$211D=M7C_signed_16|$211E=M7D_signed_16
$211F=M7X_signed_13|$2120=M7Y_signed_13
> The M7A..M7D form a 2x2 affine transformation matrix applied to Mode 7.
> Standard interpretation: M7A=cos(angle)*scale, M7B=-sin(angle)*scale,
> M7C=sin(angle)*scale, M7D=cos(angle)*scale. M7X and M7Y are signed 13-bit
> center-of-rotation offsets. The transform formula is:
>   [VRAM_X]   [M7A M7B] [SCREEN_X + BG1_HOFS - M7X]   [M7X]
>   [VRAM_Y] = [M7C M7D] [SCREEN_Y + BG1_VOFS - M7Y] + [M7Y]
> Each M-register uses an 8.8 fixed-point format internally. The SNES
> performs a SIGNED multiply automatically when M7B is written: result
> appears at $2134..$2136 as M7A * (M7B>>8). This is exploited by some
> games as a free 16x8=24 multiply unit.
hardware_multiply_side_effect=writing_$211C_(M7B)_triggers_signed_8x16_multiply|result_at_$2134_$2135_$2136

[SECTION:ppu_register_$2121]
name=CGADD|access=W|CGRAM_color_index_0..255
> Sets the CGRAM byte address. Each color is 2 bytes, so writing N here
> means "write to color N" — the byte toggle for $2122 starts at "low".
> Writing $2121 always resets the byte toggle.

[SECTION:ppu_register_$2122]
name=CGDATA|access=W|sequence=write_twice_low_then_high
color_format=0BBBBBGGGGGRRRRR_15bit_BGR|D15_unused
> Each color is 15-bit BGR with 5 bits per channel. The byte order on the
> bus is little-endian (low byte first). Writing two bytes increments the
> CGRAM byte address by 2 (one full color). CGRAM access is restricted to
> vblank or forced blank just like VRAM and OAM.
conversion_24bit_to_15bit=R5=R8>>3|G5=G8>>3|B5=B8>>3|word=(B5<<10)|(G5<<5)|R5
conversion_15bit_to_24bit=R8=(word&31)<<3|G8=((word>>5)&31)<<3|B8=((word>>10)&31)<<3

[SECTION:ppu_register_$2123_$2125]
name=W12SEL_W34SEL_WOBJSEL|access=W|window_mask_settings_per_layer
$2123=BG1_BG2_window_mask_setup
$2124=BG3_BG4_window_mask_setup
$2125=OBJ_color_window_mask_setup
each_byte_layout=BG1/BG3/OBJ_in_low_nibble|BG2/BG4/COLOR_in_high_nibble
each_nibble.D0=window_1_inside_or_outside_invert
each_nibble.D1=window_1_enable_for_this_layer
each_nibble.D2=window_2_invert
each_nibble.D3=window_2_enable_for_this_layer
> The SNES has TWO independent window regions, W1 and W2, each defined by a
> left and right column position. Each layer (BG1, BG2, BG3, BG4, OBJ, color
> math) can independently enable W1 and/or W2, and either window can be
> "inverted" so that "inside the window" becomes "outside". The two windows
> are then combined per layer via OR/AND/XOR/XNOR (set in $212A/$212B). The
> result tells the PPU which screen X coordinates have the window "active"
> for that layer.

[SECTION:ppu_register_$2126_$2129]
name=WH0_WH1_WH2_WH3|access=W|window_position_left_right
$2126=W1_left_position|$2127=W1_right
$2128=W2_left_position|$2129=W2_right
range=0..255
> Window region X coordinates. The window is "active" between left and
> right inclusive. To make a window cover the whole screen set L=0 R=255.
> To disable, set L > R (window will never be active).
> HDMA these registers per scanline to make non-rectangular windows: e.g.,
> a circular fade transition by writing successively narrower (left,right)
> pairs each scanline.

[SECTION:ppu_register_$212A_$212B]
name=WBGLOG_WOBJLOG|access=W|window_mask_combination_logic
$212A.D1_D0=BG1|D3_D2=BG2|D5_D4=BG3|D7_D6=BG4
$212B.D1_D0=OBJ|D3_D2=COLOR_math
logic_codes=00=OR|01=AND|10=XOR|11=XNOR
> When both W1 and W2 are enabled for a layer, this combines them. OR is
> "inside either window", AND is "inside both windows", XOR is "inside one
> but not both", XNOR is "outside both or inside both". Most games just use
> OR with one window.

[SECTION:ppu_register_$212C]
name=TM|access=W|main_screen_layer_enable
D0=BG1|D1=BG2|D2=BG3|D3=BG4|D4=OBJ
> Each bit enables that layer on the MAIN screen (the front layer the
> player normally sees). Layers not enabled here will not draw at all on
> the main screen.

[SECTION:ppu_register_$212D]
name=TS|access=W|sub_screen_layer_enable
D0=BG1|D1=BG2|D2=BG3|D3=BG4|D4=OBJ
> Same layer bits but for the SUB screen (behind the main, used as the
> backdrop for color math). A layer can be on BOTH main and sub screens
> simultaneously — that's how Secret of Mana puts the same trees both in
> front of and behind the water.

[SECTION:ppu_register_$212E_$212F]
name=TMW_TSW|access=W|window_mask_main_sub_screen_disable
D0..D4=disable_per_layer_inside_window
> When a window is active for a layer, this register decides whether to
> DISABLE drawing of that layer in the windowed area. So with TMW.D0=1 and
> BG1's window enabled, BG1 will not draw inside its window region. This
> lets you cut a hole in a layer using the windows.

[SECTION:ppu_register_$2130]
name=CGWSEL|access=W|color_math_mode_select
D0=direct_color_mode_enable|forces_8bpp_BG_pixel_to_be_BBBGGGRR_directly_instead_of_CGRAM_index
D1=add_subtract_screen|0=fixed_color_only|1=use_subscreen_for_color_math
D5..D4=color_math_main_screen_window_region|00=never_clip|01=clip_inside|10=clip_outside|11=always_clip
D7..D6=color_math_subscreen_disable|00=never_disable|01..11=disable_inside/outside/always
> Direct color mode is the trick that gives Mode 3/4/7 access to a wider
> palette: instead of looking up an 8bpp tile pixel in CGRAM (256 colors),
> the pixel value IS the color, packed as BBGGGRRR in 8 bits, giving you
> 8 reds * 8 greens * 4 blues = 256 colors but freely chosen. Used by
> sky gradients in racing games.
> The color math mode selects whether to use a fixed RGB color (set via
> $2132 COLDATA) or the subscreen pixel as the second operand of the
> add/subtract operation.

[SECTION:ppu_register_$2131]
name=CGADSUB|access=W|color_math_enables
D0=BG1_color_math_enable
D1=BG2_color_math_enable
D2=BG3_color_math_enable
D3=BG4_color_math_enable
D4=OBJ_color_math_enable_only_palettes_4_to_7
D5=backdrop_color_math_enable
D6=half_color_math_(divide_result_by_2)
D7=add_or_subtract|0=add|1=subtract
> Color math performs main_pixel + sub_pixel (or - sub_pixel), optionally
> halved. Halving is what produces "translucency" — translucent at 50%.
> Each layer must be individually enabled. OBJ color math only works on
> palette 4-7 sprites (giving you "sprites with translucency" via palette
> selection — the way Final Fantasy VI shadows ghost characters work).

[SECTION:ppu_register_$2132]
name=COLDATA|access=W|fixed_color_for_color_math
D7=B_select|D6=G_select|D5=R_select|D4..D0=intensity
> Sets the fixed RGB value used by color math when subscreen is disabled.
> Each write affects the channels selected by D5/D6/D7. To set R=10 G=20
> B=30 you would do three writes: write $25 (B select 1, value 5), wait,
> then write $4A (G select, value 10 — wrong, this isn't right). Actually,
> the format is: D5=set_R_channel, D6=set_G, D7=set_B, D4..D0=value.
> Multiple channels can be set in one write by setting multiple bits.
> Common: STZ $2132 to clear all channels (intensity 0 for everything).

[SECTION:ppu_register_$2133]
name=SETINI|access=W|screen_init_misc
D0=screen_interlace_enable
D1=OBJ_v_double|sprites_appear_2x_tall_in_interlace
D2=overscan_enable|0=224_visible_lines|1=239_visible_lines
D3=pseudo_hires_enable|512_horizontal_resolution_via_main_sub_alternation
D6=external_BG_input_enable|enables_Mode_7_EXTBG_pseudo_layer
D7=external_sync|NEVER_SET_ON_RETAIL|halts_video_signal
> $2133 holds the most "scary" bit ($2133.D7) — setting it on a real SNES
> stops video output. $2133.D2 enables overscan mode, giving 239 visible
> lines instead of 224 (used by some PAL games and a few NTSC ones like
> SimCity Japanese). $2133.D6 is the EXTBG bit that enables the Mode 7
> second pseudo-layer trick.

[SECTION:ppu_register_$2134_$2136]
name=read_signed_multiply_result|access=R|24bit_product
> Reads the result of the M7A * M7B signed multiply that was triggered the
> last time M7B ($211C) was written. The result is 16x8 = 24-bit signed.
> $2134 = bits 0..7, $2135 = bits 8..15, $2136 = bits 16..23. The multiply
> takes some unknown number of master cycles to complete (datasheet says
> 8 cycles after the write); reading too early gives stale data.

[SECTION:ppu_register_$2137]
name=SLHV|access=R|software_latch_h_v_counter
side_effect=any_read_latches_current_h_and_v_counters_into_$213C_$213D
> Reading $2137 has no return data of interest, but the side effect is
> critical: it captures the current PPU H and V coordinates into the
> latched counter registers. Used by raster effects to know exactly where
> the beam is. Note: writing $4201.D7 = 0 (clearing controller-2 IOBit)
> ALSO latches the counters and is the more common way.

[SECTION:ppu_register_$2138]
name=read_OAMDATA|access=R|sequence=read_twice_low_then_high
> Reads from OAM at the current OAM address (set via $2102/$2103). Auto-
> increments after each pair. Like writes, only safe in vblank or forced
> blank.

[SECTION:ppu_register_$2139_$213A]
name=read_VMDATAL_VMDATAH|access=R|VRAM_data_port_with_PREFETCH_quirk
> Reads from VRAM at the current address. CRITICAL: there's a 16-bit
> prefetch latch. The first read after setting VMADD returns the data
> from the PREVIOUS address (or stale latched data). You MUST do a dummy
> read to prime the latch, then real reads will return current data.
> Whether the prefetch advances on $2139 or $213A read depends on $2115.D7.
correct_read_pattern=set_VMADD|read_$2139_(or_$213A)_once_dummy|read_real_data_in_loop

[SECTION:ppu_register_$213B]
name=read_CGDATA|access=R|sequence=read_twice_low_then_high
> Reads from CGRAM at the current address. Set $2121 first.

[SECTION:ppu_register_$213C]
name=OPHCT|access=R|H_counter_latched_value|sequence=read_low_then_high
> Returns the H position (0..339) where the counter was last latched.
> Read low byte first, then high (only D0 of high byte is meaningful).
> The byte-toggle is reset by reading $213F.

[SECTION:ppu_register_$213D]
name=OPVCT|access=R|V_counter_latched_value|sequence=read_low_then_high
> V position (0..261 NTSC, 0..311 PAL) of the last latch event.

[SECTION:ppu_register_$213E]
name=STAT77|access=R|PPU1_status
D0..D3=PPU1_chip_version|usually_$01
D4=master_slave_mode_unused
D5=PPU1_open_bus
D6=range_over_flag|set_when_a_scanline_has_more_than_34_8x8_sprite_quanta
D7=time_over_flag|set_when_a_scanline_has_more_than_32_sprites
> The range_over and time_over flags can be polled to detect sprite limit
> violations during the previous frame. They are cleared at the start of
> vblank.

[SECTION:ppu_register_$213F]
name=STAT78|access=R|PPU2_status
D0..D3=PPU2_chip_version|usually_$01,$02,or_$03
D4=PPU2_open_bus
D5=NTSC_PAL_mode|0=NTSC|1=PAL
D6=external_latch_flag|set_when_HVcounters_were_latched|cleared_on_read_of_$213F
D7=field_flag|toggles_each_frame_at_V=0_H=1_in_interlace
side_effect=reading_$213F_resets_the_byte_toggle_for_$213C_and_$213D_and_clears_external_latch_flag
> $213F is critical for raster timing. Read it to detect a latch event,
> then read $213C and $213D to get the H/V coordinates. The read also
> resets the toggle so the next $213C read returns the LOW byte. The PAL
> bit lets games auto-detect region for proper timing.


# =============================================================================
# === CPU INTERNAL REGISTERS $4200-$421F — DETAILED ===========================
# =============================================================================

[SECTION:cpu_register_$4200]
name=NMITIMEN|access=W|init=$00
D7=NMI_enable_at_vblank
D5=V_count_IRQ_enable
D4=H_count_IRQ_enable
D0=auto_joypad_read_enable
yx_codes_for_irq.[D5=0,D4=0]=no_IRQ
yx_codes_for_irq.[D5=0,D4=1]=H_IRQ_every_scanline_when_H=$4207_$4208
yx_codes_for_irq.[D5=1,D4=0]=V_IRQ_when_V=$4209_$420A_with_H=0
yx_codes_for_irq.[D5=1,D4=1]=HV_IRQ_when_V=VTIME_AND_H=HTIME
> $4200 is THE register that controls when the CPU is interrupted. Setting
> D7 enables the per-frame NMI at vblank. The yx field selects the IRQ
> mode (none, H-only every line, V-only once per frame, or HV combined).
> D0 enables the auto-joypad-read DMA-like operation that runs at the
> start of vblank. The most common value during gameplay is $81: NMI on,
> auto-joypad on, no IRQ. For raster effects you would set $A1 (NMI on,
> H-IRQ on, auto-joypad on) or $C1 (NMI on, V-IRQ on, auto-joypad on).
init_warning=clearing_$4200_disables_IRQ_AND_clears_pending_IRQ_flag_in_one_step
init_pattern=at_reset_value_is_$00|set_to_$81_after_PPU_init_to_start_NMI_loop

[SECTION:cpu_register_$4201]
name=WRIO|access=W|init=$FF
D7=output_to_controller_2_IOBit|drives_PPU_external_latch_pin
D6=output_to_controller_1_IOBit|generally_unused
> Writing 0 to $4201.D7 LATCHES the PPU H/V counters into $213C/$213D —
> this is the most common way to read the current beam position from
> software. Pattern: STZ $4201 to latch, read $213F to confirm latch
> occurred (D6 set), then read $213C/$213D for H/V. After reading restore
> $4201 to $FF to release the line.

[SECTION:cpu_register_$4202_$4203]
name=WRMPYA_WRMPYB|access=W|hardware_unsigned_8x8_multiply
$4202=multiplicand_A_8bit
$4203=multiplier_B_8bit|writing_this_TRIGGERS_multiply
result_at=$4216_$4217|16_bit_unsigned_product
timing=8_master_cycles_after_$4203_write
> The 8x8 unsigned multiplier is the simplest CPU peripheral. Write the
> two operands, then 8 cycles later read the 16-bit result from $4216.
> Faster than software multiply by ~10x, used everywhere — sprite
> coordinate scaling, sound mixing, etc. The result lingers in $4216
> until the next write. The "8 cycles" refers to master cycles, so on a
> standard CPU instruction the result is available immediately on the
> next instruction (since each opcode takes at least 6 master cycles).
quirk=if_you_initiate_a_new_multiply_before_8_cycles_pass_the_old_result_is_corrupted

[SECTION:cpu_register_$4204_$4206]
name=WRDIVL_WRDIVH_WRDIVB|access=W|hardware_unsigned_16/8_divide
$4204_$4205=dividend_C_16bit
$4206=divisor_B_8bit|writing_this_TRIGGERS_divide
quotient_at=$4214_$4215|16_bit_unsigned
remainder_at=$4216_$4217|16_bit_unsigned|shares_register_with_multiply
timing=16_master_cycles_after_$4206_write
divide_by_zero_result=$FFFF_quotient,$00_remainder
> The unsigned divider takes a 16-bit dividend and 8-bit divisor, returns
> a 16-bit quotient and 16-bit remainder. The remainder shares its
> physical register with the multiplier result, so DON'T mix multiplies
> and divides without saving results in between. Used for screen-space
> coordinate division (1/Z perspective math), AI tick scheduling, etc.
gotcha=hardware_unit_is_unsigned_only|signed_division_must_be_done_in_software_around_the_unsigned_op

[SECTION:cpu_register_$4207_$4208]
name=HTIMEL_HTIMEH|access=W|H_IRQ_trigger_position
range=0..339
trigger_dot=approximately_H=value+3.5_master_cycles_offset
> When H-IRQ is enabled and the PPU H counter reaches this value, the IRQ
> line goes low. Use this for raster effects: split-screen, per-scanline
> palette changes, parallax scrolling. Combined with VTIMEN you can have
> the IRQ fire on a SPECIFIC scanline at a specific X position.

[SECTION:cpu_register_$4209_$420A]
name=VTIMEL_VTIMEH|access=W|V_IRQ_trigger_position
range=0..261(NTSC)|0..311(PAL)
> The line on which V-IRQ fires (or HV-IRQ qualifies). Combined with HTIME
> for HV-IRQ mode.

[SECTION:cpu_register_$420B]
name=MDMAEN|access=W|GPDMA_channel_enable_and_trigger
each_bit=enables_and_immediately_starts_GPDMA_on_that_channel
D0=channel_0|D1=channel_1|...|D7=channel_7
> The instant you write to $420B, all the channels with their bit set
> begin GPDMA. The CPU is HALTED for the duration. Channels are processed
> in order from low to high. After all transfers complete, control returns
> to the instruction following the STA $420B. Bits in $420B don't stay
> set; they're "trigger" bits.
typical_use=LDA_#$01_then_STA_$420B_for_single_channel_DMA

[SECTION:cpu_register_$420C]
name=HDMAEN|access=W|HDMA_channel_enable
each_bit=enables_HDMA_on_that_channel
> Unlike $420B, bits in $420C STAY set until you clear them. The PPU
> performs HDMA transfers automatically at H=278 of every visible scanline
> for each enabled channel. Setting a bit mid-frame may not "catch" the
> next H=278 if the H counter is past 278; safest to set $420C in NMI.
> All HDMA channels are auto-deactivated at the start of vblank, BUT the
> $420C bits are NOT cleared — they take effect again at H=6 of V=0 next
> frame.

[SECTION:cpu_register_$420D]
name=MEMSEL|access=W|init=$00
D0=FastROM_enable|0=2.68MHz_in_$80+_banks|1=3.58MHz_in_$80+_banks
> Setting D0 enables FastROM access in banks $80..$BF and $80..$FF. Only
> useful for FastROM (Mode 30/31/35) cartridges where the ROM chip can
> sustain 3.58 MHz access. The reason banks $80+ are aliases of $00+ on
> LoROM/HiROM is precisely so games can choose to run from either based
> on whether they want speed (FastROM in $80+) or compatibility/SlowROM.
must_set_in=FastROM_games_typically_set_$420D=$01_at_reset_then_JML_to_a_$80+_bank

[SECTION:cpu_register_$4210]
name=RDNMI|access=R|init=$02_partial
D7=NMI_pending|set_when_NMI_was_triggered|CLEARED_BY_READ
D3..D0=CPU_5A22_chip_version|usually_$02
D4..D6=open_bus_(reflect_data_bus)
> Read $4210 inside the NMI handler to "acknowledge" the NMI. The act of
> reading clears D7 so subsequent NMI hardware can re-fire. If you don't
> read $4210, the next vblank's NMI may not trigger correctly.
canonical_nmi_handler_first_op=LDA_$4210

[SECTION:cpu_register_$4211]
name=TIMEUP|access=R|init=$00
D7=IRQ_pending|set_when_H_or_V_IRQ_fired|CLEARED_BY_READ
D0..D6=open_bus
> Same idea as $4210 but for IRQs. Read inside IRQ handler to ack.
canonical_irq_handler_first_op=LDA_$4211

[SECTION:cpu_register_$4212]
name=HVBJOY|access=R
D7=vblank_active|set_at_H=0_of_first_vblank_line|cleared_at_H=0_V=0
D6=hblank_active|set_at_H=274|cleared_at_H=1
D0=auto_joypad_read_busy|set_during_~4224_master_cycle_joypad_read_at_start_of_vblank
> Used for polling vblank from main loop (alternative to NMI), and for
> waiting until auto-joypad-read completes before reading $4218..$421F.
wait_for_joypad_pattern=:wait_LDA_$4212|AND_#$01|BNE_:wait

[SECTION:cpu_register_$4213]
name=RDIO|access=R
D7=read_back_value_of_external_latch_pin_(controller_2_IOBit)
D6=read_back_controller_1_IOBit
> Lets you read the current state of the I/O pins. Used by some peripherals
> like the Super Scope which drive these lines as a control signal.

[SECTION:cpu_register_$4214_$4215]
name=RDDIVL_RDDIVH|access=R|divide_quotient_low_high_OR_remainder_after_multiply
> After write to $4206, this is the 16-bit quotient. After write to $4203,
> this is unused (the multiply result lives in $4216).

[SECTION:cpu_register_$4216_$4217]
name=RDMPYL_RDMPYH|access=R|multiply_product_OR_divide_remainder
> After multiply: 16-bit unsigned product. After divide: 16-bit unsigned
> remainder. Reading these doesn't trigger anything new.

[SECTION:cpu_register_$4218_$421F]
name=JOY1L_JOY1H_JOY2L_JOY2H_JOY3L_JOY3H_JOY4L_JOY4H|access=R|auto_joypad_data
$4218_$4219=controller_1_16bit
$421A_$421B=controller_2_16bit_(or_super_scope_data_or_mouse_low_word)
$421C_$421D=controller_3_16bit_(via_multitap_in_port_2)
$421E_$421F=controller_4_16bit_(via_multitap_in_port_2)
bit_layout_high_byte=B|Y|SELECT|START|UP|DOWN|LEFT|RIGHT
bit_layout_low_byte=A|X|L|R|0|0|0|0
> The auto-joypad-read circuit reads each controller port serially over
> 16 clock pulses, putting the result here. Read these AFTER $4212.D0 = 0.
> The high byte has the "directional + start/select + B/Y" buttons (the
> 8 NES-style bits) and the low byte has the SNES-additional buttons
> A/X/L/R in the top nibble.
mouse_in_port=if_a_mouse_is_in_port_2_then_$421A_$421B_holds_the_mouse_signature_byte_$0001_only|the_actual_X/Y_must_be_read_via_manual_$4017_bit_banging
multitap_in_port_2=joypad_2_data_at_$421A_$421B|controllers_3_4_at_$421C_$421F|controller_5_data_NOT_in_auto_read_must_be_read_manually


# =============================================================================
# === DMA CHANNEL REGISTERS $43x0-$43xA — DETAILED ============================
# =============================================================================

[SECTION:dma_channel_register_layout]
total_channels=8|x_in_$43xA=channel_number_0..7
each_channel_uses_16_bytes=$4300..$430F_for_ch0|$4310..$431F_for_ch1|...
> Each of the 8 DMA channels has its own 16-byte register window. The
> channels are completely independent and share NO state. Both GPDMA and
> HDMA share the same registers — the trigger ($420B vs $420C) decides
> which mode to use. If a channel is enabled for both GPDMA and HDMA at
> the same time, undefined behavior results (don't do this).

[SECTION:dma_channel_$43x0]
name=DMAPx|access=W|DMA_parameters
D7=transfer_direction|0=A_bus_to_B_bus_(CPU_to_PPU)|1=B_to_A_(PPU_to_CPU)
D6=HDMA_addressing_mode|0=absolute_table_inline|1=indirect_table_holds_pointer
D5=unused
D4=A_bus_address_step|0=increment|1=decrement
D3=A_bus_address_fixed|0=auto_step|1=hold_address
D2..D0=transfer_pattern_(see_dma_transfer_modes)
> The single most important channel register. D7 selects direction; almost
> always 0 (CPU→PPU). D6 picks HDMA mode (absolute or indirect). D4/D3
> control whether the source address advances after each byte (0 = inc,
> 1 = dec, or held fixed if D3=1). D2..D0 picks the byte pattern, which
> determines how the source bytes are distributed across consecutive
> $21xx ports.

[SECTION:dma_channel_$43x1]
name=BBADx|access=W|B_bus_address_(PPU_register_low_byte)
> The low 8 bits of the destination port. The full destination is always
> $2100 ORed with this byte, so the destination is in $2100..$21FF range.
> Common values: $18=$2118 (VRAM low), $19=$2119, $22=$2122 (CGRAM data),
> $04=$2104 (OAM data), $40=$2140 (APU port 0), $80=$2180 (WRAM data port).

[SECTION:dma_channel_$43x2_$43x3_$43x4]
name=A1Tx_low_high_bank|access=W|A_bus_24bit_source_or_dest
$43x2=offset_low|$43x3=offset_high|$43x4=bank
> The 24-bit source address (when D7=0) or destination (when D7=1) for
> the GPDMA. For HDMA, this is the address of the HDMA TABLE in CPU
> memory space. The source can be in ROM, WRAM, or anywhere — the only
> restriction is don't try to read from $4000..$41FF (XSlow region with
> undefined DMA behavior).

[SECTION:dma_channel_$43x5_$43x6]
name=DASx|access=W|GPDMA_byte_count_OR_HDMA_indirect_data_address
GPDMA_use=16bit_byte_count|0=means_$10000_(64KiB_max_per_transfer)
HDMA_use=16bit_indirect_data_address_loaded_from_table_into_this_register
> For GPDMA: how many bytes to transfer. Note that 0 means MAXIMUM (65536),
> not zero. For HDMA-indirect: this register is automatically loaded each
> time a new HDMA cell with indirect format is processed.
gotcha=for_DMA_modes_with_word_pattern_make_sure_byte_count_is_divisible_by_2_or_the_last_word_is_clipped

[SECTION:dma_channel_$43x7]
name=DASBx|access=W|HDMA_indirect_data_BANK
> The bank byte for the HDMA indirect data pointer. Combined with $43x5/6
> to form the full 24-bit address of where the actual transfer data lives
> when in indirect mode. UNUSED in absolute HDMA mode and in GPDMA.

[SECTION:dma_channel_$43x8_$43x9]
name=A2Ax|access=W|HDMA_table_current_address_(scratch)
> Working register for HDMA. At the start of each frame this is loaded
> with $43x2/$43x3 (the HDMA table base in low/high — bank stays from
> $43x4). After each cell is processed, A2Ax advances to the next cell.
> Don't write to this directly unless you're doing very advanced HDMA
> tricks like multi-frame tables.

[SECTION:dma_channel_$43xA]
name=NTRLx|access=W|HDMA_line_counter
D7=continue_mode|0=write_value_once_then_skip_(N-1)_lines|1=write_value_every_line_for_N_lines
D6..D0=remaining_line_count_for_current_cell
> Working register for HDMA. Loaded from the first byte of each HDMA
> cell. The PPU decrements the count each scanline; when count hits 0
> it loads the next cell from the table. A line count of 0 in the table
> TERMINATES the HDMA channel for the rest of the frame.

[SECTION:dma_channel_$43xB_$43xF]
name=unused_or_reserved
> Some references mention $43xB or $43xF as scratch but they have no
> documented effect on real hardware. Don't use them.

# =============================================================================
# === WRAM PORT AND ADDRESS BUS DETAILS =======================================
# =============================================================================

[SECTION:wram_overview]
total_size=128KiB
banks=$7E_and_$7F|each_64KiB
mirror=$7E:$0000..$1FFF_appears_at_$00..$3F:$0000..$1FFF_and_$80..$BF:$0000..$1FFF
> WRAM is the work RAM, the SNES's main scratch memory. The first 8 KiB
> ($7E:0000..$7E:1FFF) is mirrored into the bottom of every "low" bank,
> which is convenient because the 65C816 direct page (zero page equivalent)
> lives in this region. So you can use the LOW bank addresses ($00:00xx)
> as fast direct-page-relative scratch even when DBR is set elsewhere.
typical_layout=$7E:0000..$7E:00FF=zero_page_used_as_direct_page|$7E:0100..$7E:01FF=stack|$7E:0200..$7E:1FFF=game_state_low|$7E:2000..$7F:FFFF=tilemap_buffers_sprite_buffers_etc

[SECTION:wram_data_port_$2180_$2183]
$2180=WMDATA|RW|reads_or_writes_byte_at_current_WRAM_address|auto_increments
$2181=WMADDL|W|low_byte_of_WRAM_address
$2182=WMADDM|W|middle_byte_of_WRAM_address
$2183=WMADDH|W|high_bit_of_WRAM_address|only_D0_used_(WRAM_is_128KiB)
> The WRAM data port lets you access ALL of WRAM through a single I/O
> register. This is useful for two reasons: (1) you can DMA into WRAM
> using $2180 as the destination, which is faster than ldX/stX loops,
> and (2) you can DMA WRAM-to-WRAM by setting both source and destination
> to use the WRAM port simultaneously (well, source via A bus reading
> $7E:xxxx and destination via $2180 — there are subtle restrictions).
DMA_from_ROM_to_WRAM_pattern=set_$4302_$4304_to_ROM_source|set_$2181_$2182_$2183_to_WRAM_dest|$4301=$80|$4300=$00_(mode_0_inc)|byte_count_in_$4305_$4306|STA_$420B_to_trigger
DMA_clear_pattern=set_source_to_zero_byte_in_ROM|$4300=$08_(mode_0_fixed_source)|$4301=$80|set_WRAM_addr|byte_count|STA_$420B
> The "fixed source" mode ($43x0.D3=1) is used to flood-fill memory: point
> the source at a single $00 byte in ROM, set fixed mode, and DMA $10000
> bytes. The whole bank gets cleared in one transfer.

[SECTION:wram_dma_to_wram_restrictions]
restriction_1=cannot_DMA_from_$2180_TO_$2180_(self_loop)
restriction_2=cannot_DMA_from_WRAM_to_WRAM_using_A_bus_to_A_bus_(both_use_same_bus)
restriction_3=must_use_$2180_as_one_endpoint_for_WRAM_to_WRAM_via_B_bus
> The DMA hardware has one A bus and one B bus. To copy from one part of
> WRAM to another via DMA, you have to set the destination as $2180 (B bus
> port) and have the source A bus address point at the source WRAM bank
> (e.g., $7E:xxxx). This works because the WRAM data port and the direct
> WRAM address are different "views" of the same memory.

# =============================================================================
# === SRAM (SAVE RAM / BATTERY-BACKED) DETAILED ===============================
# =============================================================================

[SECTION:sram_overview]
purpose=save_data_persistence_via_battery_backed_SRAM_in_cartridge
size_codes_$FFD8=$00=none|$01=2KB|$02=4KB|$03=8KB|$04=16KB|$05=32KB|$06=64KB|$07=128KB|$08=256KB|$09=512KB
size_for_sa1_$FFD8=BWRAM_size_codes_different
> SRAM is just slow static RAM in the cartridge with a coin-cell battery
> attached so it survives power-off. The battery typically lasts ~10
> years; many SNES games from 1990s now have dead batteries causing save
> loss. SRAM is mapped into the CPU address space differently for LoROM
> vs HiROM vs special chip carts.

[SECTION:sram_lorom_layout]
mapping=banks_$70..$7D:$0000..$7FFF
also_seen=$F0..$FD:$0000..$7FFF_in_some_carts
size_max_lorom=256KiB_in_theory_(14_banks_x_32KiB)
typical=2_8_or_32_KiB
quirks=banks_$7E_and_$7F_are_WRAM_so_SRAM_must_stop_at_$7D
> LoROM uses the lower half of banks $70+ for SRAM. The same banks $70+
> upper half ($8000..$FFFF) are sometimes used for ROM data, sometimes
> reserved.

[SECTION:sram_hirom_layout]
mapping=banks_$20..$3F:$6000..$7FFF|and|$A0..$BF:$6000..$7FFF
size_max_hirom=64KiB_in_theory_(32_banks_x_8KiB_window)|but_practical=32KiB_typical
typical=2_8_or_32_KiB
> HiROM puts SRAM in the $6000..$7FFF region of low banks (and their $80+
> mirrors). The window is only 8 KiB per bank but spans 32 banks, so the
> total possible is 256 KiB; in practice games rarely use more than 32 KiB.

[SECTION:sram_quirks]
quirk_1=always_initialize_SRAM_on_first_boot|games_typically_compute_a_checksum_of_save_slot_and_invalidate_if_mismatch
quirk_2=if_battery_dies_SRAM_returns_random_garbage_on_reads|never_$FF_filled
quirk_3=write_pattern_byte_to_a_known_location_at_init_to_detect_fresh_carts
quirk_4=in_emulators_SRAM_is_stored_in_a_separate_.srm_file_alongside_the_ROM
quirk_5=auto_sized_by_emulators_from_$FFD8_value
quirk_6=some_carts_use_64KiB_FRAM_or_EEPROM_instead_of_battery_SRAM_(less_common)
quirk_7=Yoshi's_Island_uses_RTC_(real_time_clock)_chip_AND_SRAM_in_separate_address_space
quirk_8=writing_during_$2100_force_blank_or_vblank_is_NOT_required_for_SRAM_(unlike_VRAM/OAM/CGRAM)|SRAM_is_just_normal_memory

# =============================================================================
# === CONTROLLER DETAILED — JOYPAD, MOUSE, SCOPE, MULTITAP ====================
# =============================================================================

[SECTION:controller_port_pinout]
pin_1=+5V_power
pin_2=clock_(strobe)|connected_to_$4016_(port_1)_or_$4017_(port_2)_read_signal
pin_3=latch|connected_to_$4016_write_bit_0
pin_4=data1|connected_to_$4016/$4017_bit_0_read
pin_5=data2|connected_to_$4016/$4017_bit_1_read|used_by_multitap_for_paired_controllers
pin_6=IOBit|connected_to_$4201_$4213_bit_6_(port_1)_or_bit_7_(port_2)|controller_2_IOBit_can_LATCH_the_PPU_H_V_counters
pin_7=ground

[SECTION:controller_$4016]
name=JOYWR_(write)_JOYA_(read)|access=RW
write.D0=latch_signal|write_1_then_0_to_pulse_latch_pin_on_both_ports
read.D0=data1_of_port_1
read.D1=data2_of_port_1
> $4016 is the LEGACY NES-style joypad register. Writing 1 then 0 to D0
> latches both controller ports. Subsequent reads of $4016 read one bit
> from data1 and one bit from data2 of port 1, advancing the controller's
> shift register. Used for manual reads of mouse, multitap, scope, etc.

[SECTION:controller_$4017]
name=JOYB_(read)|access=R
read.D0=data1_of_port_2
read.D1=data2_of_port_2
read.D5_D6=usually_0
read.D7=usually_0
> Same as $4016 but for port 2. Reading $4017 advances port 2's shift
> register and returns the next data1/data2 bit pair.

[SECTION:controller_auto_joypad_read]
trigger=automatic_at_start_of_vblank_when_$4200.D0=1
duration=4224_master_cycles
status=$4212.D0_(busy_during)
output=$4218..$421F
mechanism=hardware_pulses_latch|then_clocks_16_times|each_clock_reads_data1+data2_of_each_port
> The auto-read circuit does the equivalent of: STZ $4016 (latch start),
> STA $4016 (latch end), then 16 reads of $4016 and $4017 to clock the
> shift registers. The result populates $4218..$421F: each is a 16-bit
> word with the standard SNES button layout. This happens at the START
> of vblank, BEFORE the NMI handler typically runs, so by the time the
> NMI handler is reading $4218 the data is fresh.
gotcha=DO_NOT_read_$4218..$421F_or_$4016_$4017_during_the_4224_cycle_window|wait_for_$4212.D0=0_first
disable_for_special_devices=for_mouse_or_super_scope_disable_auto_read_via_$4200.D0=0_and_do_manual_$4016_$4017_reads

[SECTION:controller_button_layout]
auto_read_word=high_byte_first_then_low_byte_when_read_as_16bit
high_byte_D7=B
high_byte_D6=Y
high_byte_D5=SELECT
high_byte_D4=START
high_byte_D3=UP
high_byte_D2=DOWN
high_byte_D1=LEFT
high_byte_D0=RIGHT
low_byte_D7=A
low_byte_D6=X
low_byte_D5=L_shoulder
low_byte_D4=R_shoulder
low_byte_D3..D0=always_0_for_standard_pad
controller_id_low_nibble=device_signature|$0=standard_pad|$1=mouse|$2=super_scope|$E=multitap|$F=none
> When read as a 16-bit value (LDA $4218 with 16-bit accumulator), the
> high byte has the directional + start/select + B/Y bits, and the low
> byte has A/X/L/R + device ID. To check "B is pressed" you AND with
> $8000 and test for nonzero. The low nibble of the low byte tells you
> what KIND of device is plugged in.

[SECTION:controller_manual_read]
when_used=for_devices_with_>16_bits_data_(mouse_32bit,_super_scope_24bit,_multitap_extra_pads)
sequence=
  1=disable_auto_read_via_$4200.D0=0
  2=write_$01_to_$4016_to_latch
  3=write_$00_to_$4016_to_release
  4=loop_N_times|read_$4016_or_$4017|extract_bit
  5=re-enable_auto_read_if_desired
> Manual read pattern in pseudo-code:
>   STZ $4200 ; disable auto
>   LDA #$01 : STA $4016 ; latch begin
>   LDA #$00 : STA $4016 ; latch end
>   LDX #16 ; or whatever bit count
>   - LDA $4016 : ROR : ROL pad_value : DEX : BNE -
>   LDA #$81 : STA $4200 ; re-enable

[SECTION:controller_snes_mouse]
device=SNES_Mouse|works_in_either_port|signature_$0001_in_low_nibble
data_format=32_bits_serial_via_$4016_or_$4017
bits_0_to_7=signature_low
bit_8=R_button
bit_9=L_button
bits_10_11=current_speed_mode
bits_12_15=signature_high
bit_16=Y_direction|0=down|1=up
bits_17_23=Y_displacement_7_bit|0..127
bit_24=X_direction|0=right|1=left
bits_25_31=X_displacement_7_bit
displacement_per_frame_max=127_units
counts_per_inch=200
speed_modes=00=slow|01=normal|10=fast
speed_change=disable_auto_read|write_a_$01_then_$00_to_$4016_(or_$4017)_repeatedly_to_pulse_speed_change
> The mouse is a serial-clocked device that returns 32 bits per read cycle.
> The first 16 bits are signature + buttons (compatible with how the auto-
> read sees a $0001 device ID), the next 16 bits are the X/Y delta. The
> deltas are RELATIVE — accumulated since the last read. The hardware
> resets the counter after the read latch.

[SECTION:controller_super_scope]
device=Super_Scope|aka=Bazooka_in_Japan|connector=port_2_ONLY
buttons=trigger,cursor,pause,turbo
operating_principle=infrared_lightgun|when_aimed_at_TV_the_internal_photodetector_sees_the_PPU_beam_pass_under_the_aim_point|signal_back_through_IOBit_latches_PPU_H_V_counters
read_data=24_bits_via_manual_$4017_reads
data_layout=
  bits_0_3=$00xx_signature
  bit_4=cursor
  bit_5=pause
  bit_6=turbo_mode
  bit_7=trigger
  bits_8_15=padding
hit_position=read_$213C_$213D_after_$213F.D6=1_to_get_pixel_X_Y
$4213.D6=read_back_state_of_IOBit
> The Super Scope works by latching the PPU H/V counters when the photo-
> detector "sees" the beam pass through the aim point. The procedure:
> the game enables the latch by clearing $4201.D7 (raises IOBit), the
> Scope's optics see the CRT beam, internal logic in the Scope pulls the
> latch line, the PPU latches H/V into $213C/$213D, the game polls
> $213F.D6 to detect the latch, then reads $213C/$213D to get the
> aim coordinates.
caveat=does_not_work_on_LCD_TVs_or_modern_displays_(no_CRT_beam_to_track)

[SECTION:controller_multitap]
device=Super_Multitap_aka_MultiPlayer_5|connector=port_2_ONLY
function=expands_port_2_into_4_additional_ports_(controllers_2_3_4_5)
detection=write_$01_then_$00_to_$4016|then_read_$4017.D1_8_times|all_$FF_means_multitap
modes=2_player_pass_through|5_player_active
mode_switch=write_$0_or_$1_to_$4017_to_select_pair
operation=in_5P_mode_$4017.D0_returns_one_pair_of_pads_(2_and_3)_and_$4017.D1_returns_other_pair_(4_and_5)|switch_via_pin_PP7_($4201.D7)
auto_read_with_multitap=$421A_$421B=pad_2|$421C_$421D=pad_3|$421E_$421F=pad_4|pad_5_NOT_in_auto_read|requires_manual
> The multitap is a Y-splitter for port 2 with internal logic. When
> detected and 5P mode enabled, the auto-read circuit gets pads 2-4 in
> the normal slots and pad 5 must be polled manually. Detection is by
> the pattern that without a multitap, $4017.D1 always reads 0; with a
> multitap and the latch sequence, $4017.D1 returns $FF.
incompatible_devices=mouse|super_scope|other_multitaps_chained|any_device_drawing_>17mA


# =============================================================================
# === APU / SPC700 / DSP — DETAILED ===========================================
# =============================================================================

[SECTION:apu_overview]
chip=SPC700_8bit_CPU|aka=Sony_SPC|sometimes_called_S_SMP
clock=2.048_MHz_nominal|24.576_MHz_oscillator_divided_by_12|actual_~1.024_or_~2.048_depending_on_silicon_lot
ram=64_KiB_SPC_RAM|completely_separate_from_main_5A22_address_space
internal_dsp=Sony_S_DSP|generates_the_audio
ipl_rom=64_bytes_at_$FFC0..$FFFF|hardcoded_boot_loader|cannot_be_changed
io_ports=4_bytes_($2140..$2143_from_main|$F4..$F7_from_SPC)
audio_output=stereo_16bit_at_32000Hz_sample_rate
> The APU is essentially a complete second computer with its own CPU,
> RAM, and audio synthesizer. The main CPU and APU communicate ONLY
> through 4 mailbox bytes that are visible to both sides at different
> addresses. There is no shared memory, no DMA between them, no direct
> sample upload — every byte of music data and every BRR sample must be
> hand-uploaded byte by byte through the IPL handshake protocol or a
> custom protocol implemented by the loaded SPC driver.

[SECTION:apu_mailbox_protocol]
main_side_$2140=APU_IO_port_0|read_or_write
main_side_$2141=APU_IO_port_1
main_side_$2142=APU_IO_port_2
main_side_$2143=APU_IO_port_3
spc_side_$F4=same_as_main_$2140|same_byte_visible_at_both_addresses
spc_side_$F5=same_as_main_$2141
spc_side_$F6=same_as_main_$2142
spc_side_$F7=same_as_main_$2143
> Each mailbox byte is dual-ported: a read on the SPC side returns
> whatever the main side last wrote (and vice versa). There is NO
> handshake bit, NO interrupt, NO automatic notification — both sides
> must POLL. By convention, mailbox 0 ($2140/$F4) carries a "command"
> byte that the SPC driver polls; the other 3 carry parameters.
race_condition=if_main_writes_$2140_at_the_exact_master_cycle_SPC_is_reading_it,_SPC_reads_OR_of_old_and_new_value|design_protocols_with_acks_to_avoid

[SECTION:apu_ipl_boot_protocol]
purpose=upload_initial_program_from_main_to_SPC_RAM_at_powerup
spc_at_reset=writes_$AA_to_$F4|writes_$BB_to_$F5|then_loops_reading_$F4_for_nonzero
main_step1=poll_$2140_until_value=$AA_AND_$2141_until_value=$BB
main_step2=write_target_load_address_low_to_$2142_and_high_to_$2143
main_step3=write_$CC_to_$2141_(start_signal)
main_step4=wait_until_$2140=$CC_(SPC_acknowledged)
main_step5=write_first_data_byte_to_$2141|write_$00_to_$2140|wait_for_$2140=$00
main_step6=write_next_data_byte_to_$2141|write_$01_to_$2140|wait_for_$2140=$01
main_step7=continue_with_increasing_$2140_count_byte_(wraps_at_$FF)
end_of_block=write_new_target_address|write_$00_to_$2143_(stop_continuation)|write_value_=_(prev_count+2)_or_higher_to_$2140_to_signal_new_address
final_block=set_target_=_program_entry_point|write_$00_to_$2141|write_(prev_count+2)_to_$2140
> The IPL boot is the chicken-and-egg solution: how do you load a sound
> driver into a CPU that has no firmware? Answer: 64 bytes of hardcoded
> firmware in the SPC. This 64-byte IPL implements a primitive byte-by-
> byte upload protocol via the mailbox. The main CPU sequence is verbose
> and slow but rock-solid reliable. After the IPL hands control to the
> uploaded driver (Step 7's "final block"), the driver is in charge and
> can implement any custom protocol it wants — usually a much faster one
> for streaming song data and sample data during gameplay.

[SECTION:spc700_register_file]
A=accumulator_8bit
X=index_8bit
Y=index_8bit
SP=stack_pointer_8bit|stack_in_$0100..$01FF
PSW=processor_status_word_8bit
PC=program_counter_16bit
> The SPC700 is similar to a 6502/65C02 but not identical. It has A/X/Y
> registers, a hardware stack at $0100..$01FF, and a status word with
> N/V/P/B/H/I/Z/C flags. The "P" flag is direct page select (like
> 65C02's relocatable zero page).
psw.D7=N_negative
psw.D6=V_overflow
psw.D5=P_direct_page_select|0=$00xx|1=$01xx
psw.D4=B_break
psw.D3=H_half_carry
psw.D2=I_interrupt_disable
psw.D1=Z_zero
psw.D0=C_carry

[SECTION:spc700_io_registers]
$00F0=TEST|test_register_DO_NOT_WRITE
$00F1=CONTROL|D7=ROMEN_(map_IPL_ROM_at_$FFC0)|D5=clear_ports_$F6_$F7|D4=clear_ports_$F4_$F5|D2_D1=timer_2_1_0_enables
$00F2=DSPADDR|next_DSP_register_to_access_via_$F3
$00F3=DSPDATA|read_or_write_DSP_register_at_$F2_index
$00F4..$00F7=APUIO0..APUIO3|mailbox_to/from_main_CPU
$00F8=AUX0|general_purpose_byte_(survives_reset_in_some_revisions)
$00F9=AUX1|same
$00FA=T0DIV|timer_0_period|0=$100,_else_value
$00FB=T1DIV|timer_1_period
$00FC=T2DIV|timer_2_period
$00FD=T0OUT|timer_0_output_(read_clears)
$00FE=T1OUT|timer_1_output
$00FF=T2OUT|timer_2_output
> All SPC700 I/O lives at $00F0..$00FF in zero page. The DSP is accessed
> through an indirect window at $F2/$F3: write the DSP register index to
> $F2, then read or write $F3 to access that register. Timers 0 and 1
> tick at 8 kHz (every 128 cycles), Timer 2 ticks at 64 kHz (every 16
> cycles). When a timer reaches its DIV value it sets the corresponding
> OUT register's low nibble bit, which is cleared by reading.

[SECTION:spc700_addressing_modes]
immediate=#imm
direct_page=$dp_(uses_PSW.P_to_select_$00xx_or_$01xx)
direct_page_indexed_x=$dp+X
direct_page_indexed_y=$dp+Y
absolute=$abs_16bit
absolute_indexed_x=$abs+X
absolute_indexed_y=$abs+Y
absolute_indirect_indexed_y=[$abs]+Y
indirect_X=(X)
indirect_X_post_inc=(X)+
relative=PC_relative_8bit_signed
bit=$dp.bit_or_$abs.bit
> Most instructions are 1 or 2 bytes. The most common addressing mode is
> direct page, which is 8-bit address resolved through PSW.P. Bit
> manipulation instructions can address any single bit in any direct page
> or absolute byte, useful for register flag work.

[SECTION:spc700_instruction_categories]
data_transfer=MOV|MOVW(16bit)|PUSH|POP|XCN(nibble_swap)
arithmetic=ADC|SBC|CMP|INC|DEC|MUL_YA(8x8=16)|DIV_YA_X(16/8)|ADDW(16bit)|SUBW(16bit)
logical=AND|OR|EOR|NOT1
shift_rotate=ASL|LSR|ROL|ROR
bit_ops=SET1|CLR1|TSET1|TCLR1|AND1|OR1|EOR1|MOV1
branch=BPL|BMI|BVC|BVS|BCC|BCS|BNE|BEQ|BBS|BBC|CBNE|DBNZ
jump_call=JMP|CALL|TCALL|PCALL|RET|RET1|RETI
flag=CLRC|SETC|CLRP|SETP|CLRV|EI|DI|NOTC
control=NOP|SLEEP|STOP|BRK
> The SPC700 has dedicated instructions for compare-and-branch (CBNE) and
> decrement-and-branch (DBNZ) which make tight loops faster. The MUL_YA
> and DIV_YA_X instructions provide hardware multiply/divide on the YA
> register pair (Y as high byte, A as low byte). PCALL is a "page call"
> for jumping to one of 16 fixed entry points in page $FFC0..$FFFF.

[SECTION:spc700_timing]
master_clock=24.576_MHz
spc_cycle=1_master_cycle_/_24|so_each_SPC_cycle_is_~40.7_ns
typical_instructions=2_to_8_SPC_cycles
> Instruction timings are in SPC cycles. Most simple ops (MOV register,
> branches) are 2-4 cycles. Memory access ops are 3-5 cycles. Multiply
> and divide are slow (9-12 cycles). Total budget per audio frame
> (1/60 sec) is around 17000 SPC cycles, which is enough for a basic
> tracker-style sound driver to mix 8 voices and update note state.

[SECTION:dsp_overview]
chip=Sony_S_DSP|inside_the_APU
voices=8
output_rate=32000_Hz_stereo
sample_format=BRR_(Bit_Rate_Reduction)_4bit_ADPCM_in_9_byte_blocks
features=adsr_envelopes|gain_envelopes|pitch_modulation|noise|echo_FIR|key_on_off
> The DSP is a fixed-function audio synthesizer with 8 polyphonic voices.
> Each voice plays a sample from APU RAM (BRR-encoded), with its own
> pitch, volume, panning, envelope, and effects routing. The DSP mixes
> all 8 voices into a stereo output at 32 kHz. There's a global echo
> processor (8-tap FIR + delay) for reverb effects.
register_access=via_SPC700_$F2_$F3_window
register_count=128_total|each_8_bits

[SECTION:dsp_voice_block_layout]
each_voice_uses=16_consecutive_DSP_register_bytes
voice_n_base=$n0_where_n=0..7
+$00=VOL_L|signed_8bit|left_channel_volume_for_voice
+$01=VOL_R|signed_8bit|right_channel_volume
+$02=PITCH_L|14bit_pitch_low_byte
+$03=PITCH_H|14bit_pitch_high_(D5..D0)
+$04=SRCN|sample_source_number_index_into_DIR_table
+$05=ADSR1|D7=ADSR_enable|D6..D4=A_attack_rate|D3..D0=D_decay_rate
+$06=ADSR2|D7..D5=S_sustain_level|D4..D0=R_release_rate
+$07=GAIN|when_ADSR_disabled,_envelope_is_GAIN_mode|see_gain_modes
+$08=ENVX|current_envelope_value|read_only|0..127
+$09=OUTX|current_output_sample_after_envelope|read_only|signed_8bit
> Each voice's 16-byte block contains volume, pitch, sample selection,
> envelope settings, and read-back of current envelope/output. To play
> a sample on voice 0: set SRCN ($04), set PITCH ($02/$03), set ADSR
> ($05/$06), set volumes ($00/$01), then trigger via global KON register.

[SECTION:dsp_global_registers]
$0C=MVOL_L|main_volume_left|signed
$1C=MVOL_R|main_volume_right
$2C=EVOL_L|echo_volume_left|signed
$3C=EVOL_R|echo_volume_right
$4C=KON|key_on|writing_1_to_a_bit_starts_that_voice|each_bit=voice_0..7
$5C=KOF|key_off|writing_1_to_a_bit_starts_that_voice's_release_phase
$6C=FLG|D7=soft_reset|D6=mute_all|D5=echo_disable|D4..D0=noise_clock_rate_(0=lowest)
$7C=ENDX|each_bit_set_when_voice_n's_BRR_block_with_END_flag_was_decoded|read_only
$0D=EFB|echo_feedback|signed
$2D=PMON|D1..D7=enable_pitch_modulation_for_voices_1..7|voice_0_modulates_voice_1
$3D=NON|D0..D7=enable_noise_for_voice_n_instead_of_BRR_sample
$4D=EON|D0..D7=enable_voice_n_to_be_routed_into_echo_input
$5D=DIR|directory_table_offset_in_$100_units|page_in_APU_RAM_where_BRR_sample_pointers_live
$6D=ESA|echo_buffer_start_address_high_byte|in_$100_units
$7D=EDL|echo_delay|D3..D0=delay_in_units_of_16ms|0..15
$0F_$1F_$2F_$3F_$4F_$5F_$6F_$7F=FIR_C0..C7|signed_8bit_FIR_filter_coefficients_for_echo
> The global registers control overall mix, echo, noise, and voice
> triggering. The DIR register points at a "sample directory" — a table
> of (start_address, loop_address) word pairs in APU RAM that the SRCN
> field of each voice indexes into. So to play sample N: set SRCN=N, and
> the DSP looks up DIR_page*256 + N*4 to find the sample's start address.

[SECTION:dsp_brr_format]
block_bytes=9
samples_per_block=16
header_byte_layout=
  D7..D4=range_shift|0..12|determines_decode_amplitude
  D3..D2=filter_select|0..3|predictive_filter_for_decode
  D1=loop_flag|when_END_is_set,_continue_at_loop_address
  D0=end_flag|when_set,_this_is_the_last_block_of_the_sample
data_bytes_after_header=8|each_holds_2_signed_4bit_nibbles
filter_0=output=raw_<<_shift|no_prediction
filter_1=output=raw_<<_shift+(prev*15/16)
filter_2=output=raw_<<_shift+(prev*61/32)-(prev_prev*15/16)
filter_3=output=raw_<<_shift+(prev*115/64)-(prev_prev*13/16)
> BRR is a simple ADPCM format: 16 samples per 9-byte block. Each sample
> is a 4-bit signed nibble that's left-shifted by the range and added to
> a predictor value computed from the last 1 or 2 output samples (filter
> 0 = no prediction, filters 1-3 use a one- or two-tap IIR predictor).
> When the END flag is set on a block, decoding stops; if LOOP is also
> set, decoding restarts at the sample's loop point. The loop point is
> stored in the directory table, NOT in the sample data itself.
loop_pattern=set_END_and_LOOP_in_last_block|directory_loop_address_points_to_block_to_continue_from
no_loop_pattern=set_END_only_in_last_block|sample_stops_after_block_decoded
sample_size_calculation=blocks*9_bytes|samples_per_block=16|so_for_N_samples_blocks=ceil(N/16)

[SECTION:dsp_adsr_envelope]
A_attack=0..15|0=infinite_(no_attack)|larger=faster_attack
D_decay=0..7|larger=faster_decay_to_sustain_level
S_sustain_level=0..7|sustain_amplitude=(s+1)/8
R_release_rate=0..31|larger=faster_release
trigger=writing_to_KON
attack_curve=linear_+0.125_per_step_at_attack_rate
decay_curve=exponential_-50%_per_step_at_decay_rate_until_sustain_reached
sustain_curve=exponential_-50%_per_step_at_release_rate_(slow)
release_curve=on_KOF_write,_exponential_-50%_per_step_at_release_rate
> Standard four-stage envelope. Attack is linear, decay/sustain/release
> are exponential. The "rate" values are not seconds — they're indices
> into a hardware rate table where higher values = faster. Rate 0 means
> "infinite" — the envelope stage takes forever, useful for preventing
> attack/decay from happening when you want.

[SECTION:dsp_gain_envelope]
when_used=when_ADSR_enable_($05.D7)=0
gain_modes=4|selected_by_$07.D7_D6_D5
direct_mode=$07.D7=0|$07.D6..D0=fixed_envelope_level_0..127
linear_inc_mode=$07.D7_D6_D5=110|$07.D4..D0=rate
linear_dec_mode=$07.D7_D6_D5=100|$07.D4..D0=rate
exponential_dec_mode=$07.D7_D6_D5=101|$07.D4..D0=rate
bent_inc_mode=$07.D7_D6_D5=111|$07.D4..D0=rate|increases_to_$80_then_increases_more_slowly_to_$7F
> GAIN mode lets you bypass ADSR and directly drive the envelope. Useful
> for tremolo, custom envelope shapes, or just holding a constant volume.

[SECTION:dsp_echo_buffer]
location_in_apu_ram=ESA*$100|grows_for_(EDL*$800)_bytes
size_per_delay_step=$800_bytes|=2KiB
max_size=$8000_bytes_(32KiB)_at_EDL=15
sample_storage=interleaved_LR_words|2_bytes_per_sample_per_channel
fir_filter=8_taps|coefficients_at_FIR_C0..C7|sum_of_coefficients_must_be_<=$80_to_avoid_clipping
feedback_loop=output_of_FIR_is_added_back_to_input_via_EFB|0_disables_feedback
> The echo unit reads samples from a circular buffer in APU RAM, runs
> them through the 8-tap FIR filter, and outputs the result with
> configurable feedback. This produces reverb, chorus, and similar
> effects. CRITICAL: the echo buffer LIVES IN APU RAM, so it eats into
> your sample memory budget! 2-8 KiB is typical for game music. The
> buffer is also CONTINUOUSLY WRITTEN BY DSP — never store sample data
> in the echo region or it gets clobbered.
buffer_setup_caveat=must_set_ESA_BEFORE_enabling_echo_or_DSP_writes_garbage_to_arbitrary_RAM
disable_during_setup=set_FLG.D5=1_to_disable_echo_writes_while_changing_ESA_or_EDL

[SECTION:dsp_pitch_calculation]
formula=output_sample_rate=32000_*_(pitch_value/$1000)
pitch_value_for_unity=$1000_(plays_back_at_native_recorded_rate)
pitch_value_for_octave_up=$2000
pitch_value_for_octave_down=$0800
pitch_value_for_specific_note=$1000_*_(target_freq/source_freq)*(32000/source_sample_rate)
14bit_max=$3FFF_(maximum_pitch_=_8x_speedup)
> Pitch is a 14-bit value. $1000 = play at recorded rate. Each octave is
> a 2x change. The DSP interpolates between samples using Gaussian
> interpolation (a 4-tap filter), giving better quality than naive
> nearest-neighbor or linear interpolation.

[SECTION:dsp_pitch_modulation]
$2D_PMON=enables_per_voice|D1=voice_1_modulated_by_voice_0_output|D2=voice_2_by_voice_1|...
> Pitch modulation lets one voice's output sample modulate the next
> voice's pitch. Used for vibrato, FM-synthesis-style sounds, and
> certain distinctive SNES sound effects. Voice 0 cannot be modulated
> (there's no "voice -1").

[SECTION:dsp_noise]
$3D_NON=per_voice_enable_for_noise_replacement
noise_rate_clock=$6C_FLG.D4..D0|0=lowest_~16Hz|31=highest_~32kHz
> When a voice has its NON bit set, instead of playing a BRR sample it
> plays the global noise generator at the rate set by FLG. Used for
> drums, percussive effects, and white noise.


# =============================================================================
# === CYCLE ACCURACY REFERENCE — HARD NUMBERS FOR EVERYTHING ==================
# =============================================================================

[SECTION:cycle_accuracy_master_clock]
master_clock_ntsc_hz=21477272|theoretical=1.89e9/88|approx=21.477_MHz
master_clock_pal_hz=21281370|approx=21.281_MHz
> All SNES timing is derived from the master clock. CPU, PPU, DMA — all
> count their work in master cycles. There's no separate "CPU clock"
> with its own crystal; the CPU just runs N master cycles per memory
> access depending on what region of memory it's hitting.

[SECTION:cycle_accuracy_memory_access_speeds]
fast_6_master_cycles=banks_$80..$BF_$8000..$FFFF_AND_$420D.D0=1|banks_$C0..$FF_AND_$420D.D0=1|register_area_$2000..$2FFF|register_area_$4200..$5FFF|cart_$4400..$5FFF
slow_8_master_cycles=banks_$00..$3F_$8000..$FFFF|banks_$00..$3F_$0000..$1FFF_(WRAM_mirror)|banks_$00..$3F_$6000..$7FFF|banks_$40..$7D_$0000..$FFFF|banks_$7E_$7F|banks_$80..$BF_$8000..$FFFF_when_$420D.D0=0|banks_$C0..$FF_when_$420D.D0=0
xslow_12_master_cycles=$4000..$41FF_(controller_legacy_registers_only)
internal_op_6_master_cycles=any_CPU_internal_cycle_(no_memory_access)|always_6_regardless_of_$420D
> Three speed regions: 6 (fast), 8 (slow), 12 (xslow). Internal operation
> cycles (the CPU "thinking" without touching memory) are always 6 master
> cycles. Memory access cycles are 6, 8, or 12 depending on what address
> is being touched. The same instruction can take different total cycle
> counts when running from FastROM vs SlowROM, vs hitting WRAM vs ROM.
> XSlow only applies to $4000..$41FF — basically the legacy controller
> registers $4016/$4017. Avoid these for tight loops.
example_lda_$1234_in_slow_bank=opcode_fetch(8)+addr_low(8)+addr_high(8)+data_read(8)=32_master_cycles
example_lda_$1234_in_fast_bank=6+6+6+6=24_master_cycles
example_clc=opcode_fetch+1_internal=14_or_12_depending_on_speed

[SECTION:cycle_accuracy_scanline]
scanline_master_cycles=1364
scanlines_per_frame_ntsc=262_(non_interlace)|263_(interlace_alternating)
scanlines_per_frame_pal=312_(non_interlace)|313_(interlace_alternating)
visible_lines=224_(default)|239_(if_$2133.D2=1_overscan)
vblank_starts_at=line_$E1_(225)_or_line_$F0_(240)_if_overscan
vblank_ends_at=line_0
short_scanline=in_non_interlace_mode_line_$F0_(240)_of_every_other_frame_is_only_1360_master_cycles_(loses_4_master_cycles_for_color_subcarrier_phase)
> Each scanline is 1364 master cycles, which corresponds to 340 PPU "dots"
> at 4 master cycles per dot. NTSC has 262 lines per frame normally, with
> the rare exception of one short scanline every other frame to keep the
> color subcarrier in phase with the line rate. Vblank begins on line $E1
> (or $F0 with overscan) and ends at the start of line 0.
frame_master_cycles_ntsc=1364*262=357368|or_357364_on_short_frames
frame_microseconds_ntsc=~16639
frames_per_second=60.0988_NTSC|50.0070_PAL

[SECTION:cycle_accuracy_wram_refresh]
when=once_per_scanline
duration=40_master_cycles
start_offset_in_scanline=approximately_538_master_cycles_after_scanline_start
quantum=multiple_of_8_master_cycles_after_previous_refresh
> The DRAM refresh cycle steals 40 master cycles from CPU execution every
> scanline. The CPU is paused. This means even an unbroken sequence of
> CPU operations cannot exceed (1364 - 40) = 1324 cycles per scanline of
> useful work. Most cycle-accurate emulators model this; some games have
> code that's tuned to it.

[SECTION:cycle_accuracy_irq_response]
nmi_irq_check_when=just_before_the_FINAL_CPU_cycle_of_each_instruction
nmi_irq_response_overhead=~14_master_cycles_(IRQ/NMI_pseudo_op_fetch+vector_load+jsr_setup)
delay_after_dma=if_NMI_fires_during_DMA,_handler_runs_24..30_master_cycles_after_DMA_completes
plp_cli_sei_quirk=these_instructions_update_I_flag_in_their_FINAL_cycle_so_IRQ_check_uses_OLD_value_of_I
rti_brk_cop_no_quirk=these_DO_update_I_in_time_for_their_own_check
> The CPU checks for pending interrupts just before completing each
> instruction. If an interrupt is pending and not masked, the next
> "instruction" executed is actually the IRQ/NMI pseudo-opcode that
> pushes return state and jumps via vector. Total response latency is
> ~14 master cycles plus whatever time was left in the instruction at
> the moment of interrupt.
> Important quirk: PLP/CLI/SEI/SEP #$04/REP #$04 update the I flag in
> their last cycle, AFTER the IRQ check has already happened. So a
> "CLI" followed by an enabled IRQ does NOT immediately fire — the IRQ
> fires after the NEXT instruction. RTI, BRK, and COP do not have this
> quirk and update flags in time.

[SECTION:cycle_accuracy_dma_timing]
dma_per_byte=8_master_cycles
dma_channel_overhead=8_master_cycles_per_active_channel
dma_total_overhead=8_master_cycles_per_DMA_transfer_(beyond_per_channel)
dma_alignment=DMA_starts_at_next_8_master_cycle_boundary_after_$420B_write|then_resyncs_to_CPU_clock_after
dma_resync_overhead=2_to_8_master_cycles_at_start|2_to_8_at_end
dma_during_xslow=$4000..$41FF_DMA_behavior_undefined|don't
> DMA is incredibly fast: 8 cycles per byte regardless of the speed of
> the source or destination memory. Compare to a software loop which
> takes ~24-32 cycles per byte. The overhead is small: 8 cycles for the
> first channel, 8 cycles per additional channel, plus 8-16 cycles of
> alignment slop on each end.
example_8KiB_DMA=8_(overhead)+_8_(channel_init)+_8*8192_(bytes)+~6_(end_align)=65566_master_cycles_(~3_ms)
worst_case_full_64KiB_DMA=~525000_master_cycles_(~24.5_ms)|exceeds_one_NTSC_frame
practical_per_vblank_DMA=~98000_master_cycles_(~4.6_ms)|allows_~12KiB_per_vblank_at_224_lines

[SECTION:cycle_accuracy_hdma_timing]
hdma_init_at=V=0_H=6|all_active_channels_have_their_$43x8_$43x9_loaded_from_$43x2_$43x3
hdma_init_overhead=18_master_cycles
hdma_transfer_at=H=278_of_every_visible_scanline
hdma_per_scanline_setup_overhead=~18_master_cycles_when_any_channel_is_active
hdma_per_active_channel_per_scanline=8_master_cycles_(direct)_or_24_master_cycles_(indirect_when_loading_new_pointer)
hdma_per_byte=8_master_cycles
hdma_active_lines=224_(or_239_if_overscan)
> HDMA's per-scanline cost adds up. With 4 direct channels active and 1
> indirect channel, that's 18 + 4*8 + 24 = 74 cycles per scanline. Over
> 224 scanlines that's 16576 cycles per frame "stolen" from CPU. Heavy
> HDMA users (8 channels all active) can lose up to ~30000 cycles per
> frame, which is ~16% of total frame budget.
gotcha=HDMA_is_AUTO_DEACTIVATED_at_start_of_vblank|but_$420C_bits_are_NOT_cleared|will_re-activate_next_frame_unless_you_clear_$420C
gotcha_2=if_an_HDMA_table_cell_has_line_count=0,_that_channel_is_terminated_for_REST_OF_FRAME

[SECTION:cycle_accuracy_auto_joypad_read]
trigger=automatic_at_start_of_vblank_when_$4200.D0=1
start_dot=between_dots_32.5_and_95.5_of_first_vblank_scanline
duration=4224_master_cycles
status_flag=$4212.D0_set_during_read
> Auto-joypad reads steal ~4224 cycles from each frame. They start a few
> dots into vblank, so by the time the NMI handler is busy doing other
> things the read is in progress. You MUST poll $4212.D0 = 0 before
> reading $4218..$421F or you get garbage. The simplest pattern is to
> do other vblank work first (palette uploads, sound updates), then
> read joypads near the end.

[SECTION:cycle_accuracy_multiply_divide]
multiply_$4202_$4203=8_master_cycles_after_write_to_$4203
divide_$4204_$4206=16_master_cycles_after_write_to_$4206
> Both are non-blocking — write the operands, do unrelated work, then
> read the result. The 8 / 16 cycle delays are short enough that almost
> any subsequent instruction has the result ready.

[SECTION:cycle_accuracy_ppu_rendering]
pixel_output_starts=H=22_of_each_visible_scanline
pixel_output_ends=H=277
dots_per_scanline=340
master_cycles_per_dot=4_(usually)_or_6_(dots_323_and_327_only)
ppu_memory_access_per_dot=4_master_cycles
ppu_lookahead=2_to_3_tiles_(=16..24_pixels)
> The PPU is a beast: it has its own VRAM access bus running at 4 master
> cycles per pixel for rendering. While the CPU is paused for refresh,
> the PPU is happily fetching tile data and outputting pixels. The PPU
> looks ahead 2-3 tiles, which is why writes to scroll registers in mid-
> scanline often produce a "shifted" effect — the change applies a few
> tiles after where you expected.
hblank_window=H=274_to_H=1_of_next_line|=66_dots_=_about_264_master_cycles
forced_blank_lockout_window=technically_VRAM_OAM_CGRAM_writable_but_PPU_will_show_garbage_briefly

[SECTION:cycle_accuracy_irq_trigger_formulas]
v_irq_only=trigger_when_PPU_reaches_V=$4209_$420A_AND_H=0|H_offset_~2.5_dots
h_irq_only=trigger_when_PPU_reaches_H=$4207_$4208_on_EVERY_scanline|H_offset_~3.5_dots
hv_irq=trigger_when_V=$4209_$420A_AND_H=$4207_$4208|combined
no_irq_dot_153_short_scanline=H=153_does_not_trigger_IRQ_on_short_scanline_in_non_interlace
no_irq_dot_153_last_scanline=H=153_does_not_trigger_IRQ_on_last_scanline_of_any_frame
> The IRQ trigger formulas have hidden quirks. The "approximately" cycle
> offsets reflect the fact that the IRQ line goes low slightly after the
> stated H position, so handler entry begins ~14-20 cycles later. Two
> dots are excluded from H-IRQ entirely (dot 153 on certain scanlines)
> due to the short-scanline color subcarrier alignment.


# =============================================================================
# === OPEN BUS, MEMORY DATA REGISTER, AND INSTRUCTION WRAPPING QUIRKS =========
# =============================================================================

[SECTION:open_bus_mdr]
mdr_definition=Memory_Data_Register|stores_value_of_last_read_or_write_on_data_bus
behavior=reading_unmapped_address_returns_MDR_(stale_value)
io_cycles_dont_update_mdr=internal_CPU_cycles_have_addresses_but_dont_drive_data_bus
ppu1_mdr=separate_register_in_PPU1_chip|set_when_$2134_$2138_or_$21x4_$21x6_$21x8_$21xA_(write-only)_are_read|fills_undefined_bits_of_PPU1_register_reads
ppu2_mdr=separate_register_in_PPU2_chip|set_when_$213B_$213D_(or_$21xB_$21xD)_are_read|fills_undefined_bits_of_PPU2_reads
> Open bus is the SNES's name for "what does an unmapped read return?"
> The answer is: whatever was last on the data bus. The CPU has its own
> MDR, and each PPU has its own MDR for register reads. When you read a
> PPU register that has some defined bits and some undefined bits, the
> defined bits are filled in by the register value and the undefined
> bits are filled by the PPU's MDR.
implication_1=do_not_rely_on_undefined_bits_of_register_reads_being_$00|they_are_open_bus
implication_2=test_for_open_bus_by_reading_$0000_or_$00_in_an_unused_bank_after_a_known_read
jsl_quirk=JSL_a_pushes_old_PB_BEFORE_reading_new_PB|so_if_target_PB_comes_from_open_bus_you_get_OLD_PB_pushed_then_new_PB_in_target

[SECTION:cpu_instruction_wrapping_pc]
pc_increment=always_wraps_within_the_program_bank_at_any_byte_of_the_opcode
> The Program Counter is 16-bit; it wraps from $FFFF to $0000 within the
> same bank. This means an instruction that crosses bank $00:FFFE..$01:0001
> actually wraps to $00:0000 partway through. CRITICAL — never put code
> that spans bank boundaries.

[SECTION:cpu_instruction_wrapping_absolute]
absolute_a=word_reads_in_native_mode_carry_into_next_bank
> "LDA $FFFE" with 16-bit accumulator reads byte from $00:FFFE and high
> byte from $00:FFFF, no problem. But "LDA $FFFF" reads from $00:FFFF
> and $01:0000 — the read CARRIES into the next bank. This is intentional
> 65816 design (different from the 6502 which wraps within $00xx).

[SECTION:cpu_instruction_wrapping_absolute_indexed]
absolute_indexed_a_x=adding_X_may_carry_into_next_bank|word_reads_carry_into_next_bank
> "LDA $FF00,X" with X=$80 reads from $00:FF80. With X=$0200 reads from
> $01:0100 — the +X computation carries past the bank boundary just fine.

[SECTION:cpu_instruction_wrapping_indirect_jump]
absolute_indirect_jmp_a=JMP_$xxFF_bug_is_FIXED_in_65816|reads_address_correctly_across_page_boundaries
absolute_indirect_uses_bank_0=address_table_is_loaded_from_$00:a_NOT_PB:a_NOT_DBR:a
absolute_indirect_jump_destination=in_current_PB|so_JMP_($1234)_loads_target_from_$00:1234_then_jumps_to_PB:target
> The famous 6502 indirect jump bug (JMP ($xxFF) reads from $xxFF and
> $xx00 instead of $xxFF and $xx00+1) is FIXED in the 65816 — it
> properly carries. But there's a different gotcha: the address table
> is loaded from BANK 0, not the current PB or DBR. The actual jump
> destination is in the current PB.

[SECTION:cpu_instruction_wrapping_absolute_indexed_indirect]
abs_indexed_indirect_jsr_ax=adding_X_wraps_within_the_current_bank
abs_indexed_indirect_table_loaded_from_PB:a+X|NOT_$00:a+X_NOT_DBR:a+X
> JSR (a,X) is a special "jump table" instruction. The (a,X) computation
> wraps within the current bank, AND the indirect address load happens
> from PB:a+X, not bank 0. So this is the only indirect addressing mode
> that uses the current Program Bank as the indirect lookup base.

[SECTION:cpu_instruction_wrapping_absolute_long]
absolute_long_l=full_24bit_addressing|word_reads_in_native_mode_carry_into_next_bank
> "LDA $7E0000" loads from bank $7E. "LDA $7EFFFF" loads from $7E:FFFF
> and $7F:0000 (carries). Long addressing IS the way to access arbitrary
> banks without changing DBR.

[SECTION:cpu_instruction_wrapping_direct]
direct_d=word_reads_in_native_mode_ALWAYS_carry_across_pages
direct_in_emulation_mode=if_DL=$00_word_reads_wrap_within_zero_page|if_DL_NOT=$00_carry
direct_indexed_d_x=in_native_mode_always_carry_across_pages|in_emulation_mode_with_DL=$00_wrap_within_page
direct_does_NOT_carry_across_banks=stays_in_bank_0_always
> Direct page (zero page) reads in native mode always carry past page
> boundaries — D=$8001, d=$80, X=$80 reads from $00:8101. Important
> nuance: even though direct page can be relocated to any 256-byte
> aligned position in bank 0 via the D register, all direct page accesses
> stay within bank $00. This is enforced by hardware.

[SECTION:cpu_instruction_wrapping_direct_indirect]
direct_indirect_d=address_load_follows_direct_d_rules|data_load_word_reads_carry_across_pages_AND_banks
direct_indirect_long_brackets=[d]_address_load_always_carries_pages|data_load_carries_pages_and_banks
direct_indirect_indexed_dy=address_load_follows_direct_d|+Y_addition_always_carries_across_banks
direct_indirect_indexed_long_brackets=[d],Y_address_load_always_carries|+Y_carries_across_banks
> The "indirect" addressing modes have separate rules for the address
> LOAD and the data LOAD. Address load follows direct page rules
> (carries pages in native mode, may wrap in emulation mode). Data load
> uses the loaded address PLUS the bank from DBR (or +Y addition), and
> can freely carry across banks.

[SECTION:cpu_instruction_wrapping_stack_relative]
stack_relative_d_s=address_always_carries_across_page_boundaries|can_exit_emulation_mode_stack_page_(!)
stack_relative_indirect_d_s_y=address_load_carries|+Y_carries_across_banks|data_load_carries_pages_and_banks
> Stack-relative addressing carries even in emulation mode. This is one
> of the rare ways to escape the $0100..$01FF stack page in emulation
> mode (along with PEA, PLD, etc.).

[SECTION:cpu_instruction_wrapping_stack_ops_emulation]
emulation_mode_sp_high=always_$01_(stack_locked_to_page_1)
emulation_mode_escape_ops=JSL|JSR_(a,X)|PEA|PEI|PER|PHD|PLD|RTL|d,S|(d,S),Y
emulation_pea_at_sp_$0100=writes_$0100_and_$00FF|sp_ends_at_$01FE|note_$01FF_unchanged
> In emulation mode, normal stack operations (PHA/PLA/JSR/RTS) keep SP
> within $01xx. But several "16-bit aware" operations don't respect this
> — PEA, PEI, PER, PHD, PLD, JSL, RTL, JSR (a,X), and indirect-stack
> addressing all "leak" out of $01xx and can write to $00xx or $02xx.
> A subtle bug source if you're trying to write 65C02-compatible code.

[SECTION:cpu_instruction_wrapping_block_move]
block_move_emulation=when_E=1,_X_and_Y_are_8bit_so_addresses_stay_in_$00xx
block_move_native=full_16bit_X_Y|can_walk_through_entire_64KiB_bank
> MVN/MVP block moves in native mode are the fastest software memory
> copy on the SNES (7 cycles per byte versus DMA's 8). Use them for
> small (<64 byte) copies where DMA setup overhead would be larger
> than the saved transfer time.

# =============================================================================
# === LAYER PRIORITY — COMPLETE TABLE =========================================
# =============================================================================

[SECTION:layer_priority_basic_concept]
main_screen=in_front|each_BG_can_be_added_to_via_$212C_TM
sub_screen=behind_main|each_BG_can_be_added_to_via_$212D_TS
backdrop=color_index_0_of_palette_0|absolute_back
translucency=main_screen_pixels_can_blend_with_subscreen_pixels_via_color_math
sprite_priority_per_sprite=4_levels|0_lowest|3_highest
bg_priority_per_tile=2_levels|0_low|1_high
> SNES layering is more complex than other consoles because each pixel
> can come from one of 4 BGs, OBJ (sprites), or backdrop, each with its
> own priority bit, AND the main screen can blend with the sub screen via
> color math. The "ray tracing" mental model: trace from front to back,
> stopping at the first opaque pixel. If you hit a translucent pixel
> (main screen layer with color math enabled), blend with the next
> opaque sub screen pixel beneath.

[SECTION:layer_priority_complete_table_mode_1]
# Mode 1 with $2105.D3=0 (BG3 priority normal). Front to back:
# Each "obj N" means sprites whose OAM priority bits are N.
order_1=obj_3
order_2=BG1_tiles_with_priority_1
order_3=BG2_tiles_with_priority_1
order_4=obj_2
order_5=BG1_tiles_with_priority_0
order_6=BG2_tiles_with_priority_0
order_7=obj_1
order_8=BG3_tiles_with_priority_1
order_9=BG4_tiles_with_priority_1
order_10=obj_0
order_11=BG3_tiles_with_priority_0
order_12=BG4_tiles_with_priority_0
order_13=backdrop
> The order interleaves BGs and OBJs by priority. The lowest-priority
> sprites (obj 0) are nearly at the back, behind BG3 priority-1 tiles
> but in front of BG3 priority-0. Higher priority sprites come forward.
> This is for MAIN screen; sub screen has the same ordering but doesn't
> include BG3 priority special handling.

[SECTION:layer_priority_mode_1_bg3_priority_high]
# When $2105.D3 = 1, BG3 priority-1 tiles jump to the absolute front.
order_1=BG3_tiles_with_priority_1_(now_in_front_of_everything)
order_2=obj_3
order_3=BG1_tiles_with_priority_1
order_4=BG2_tiles_with_priority_1
order_5=obj_2
order_6=BG1_tiles_with_priority_0
order_7=BG2_tiles_with_priority_0
order_8=obj_1
order_9=BG4_tiles_with_priority_1
order_10=obj_0
order_11=BG3_tiles_with_priority_0
order_12=BG4_tiles_with_priority_0
order_13=backdrop
> This is the "HUD trick": Mario World status bar, Zelda heart bar.
> Setting $2105.D3=1 makes any BG3 tile with the priority bit set draw
> in front of everything including all sprites. BG3 priority-0 tiles
> stay in their normal back position. So you upload the HUD as BG3
> priority-1 tiles, the playfield decoration as BG3 priority-0 tiles,
> and they coexist on the same layer.

[SECTION:layer_priority_modes_0_2_3_4_5_6]
mode_0=4_layers_2bpp_each|order_obj3,BG1.1,BG2.1,obj2,BG1.0,BG2.0,obj1,BG3.1,BG4.1,obj0,BG3.0,BG4.0
mode_2_4=2_layers_offset_per_tile|order_obj3,BG1.1,obj2,BG2.1,obj1,BG1.0,obj0,BG2.0
mode_3=2_layers_BG1_8bpp_BG2_4bpp|order_obj3,BG1.1,obj2,BG2.1,obj1,BG1.0,obj0,BG2.0
mode_5_6=hires_layers|order_obj3,BG1.1,obj2,BG2.1,obj1,BG1.0,obj0,BG2.0
> Modes other than 1 follow simpler patterns since they have fewer BGs.
> Mode 0 has 4 BGs and uses pairs (BG1+BG2 then BG3+BG4). Modes 2-4 have
> 2 BGs and the order is straightforward. Mode 7 has only BG1 (and
> possibly EXTBG pseudo-BG2).

[SECTION:layer_priority_mode_7]
mode_7_normal=order_obj3,obj2,obj1,BG1,obj0,backdrop
mode_7_extbg=order_obj3,obj2,obj1,BG1_high_(pixels_with_bit_7_set),obj0,BG1_low_(pixels_with_bit_7_clear),backdrop
> Mode 7 has only one BG by default, with sprites layered around it. The
> EXTBG hack (enabled by $2133.D6) interprets bit 7 of each Mode 7 pixel
> as a layer-priority flag, splitting Mode 7 into a front and back pseudo-
> layer. This is how Tales of Phantasia and Pilotwings put characters or
> HUDs in front of the rotating Mode 7 floor while the floor itself is
> behind the sprites.

[SECTION:layer_priority_subscreen_for_color_math]
> The subscreen ($212D layers) is what gets blended with the main screen
> when color math is enabled. The blend formula is:
>   final = main_pixel ± sub_pixel  (optionally /2 if "half" enabled)
> The subscreen's own layer ordering is the same as the main screen
> (using the same priority rules) but only sub-screen-enabled layers
> are considered. If no sub-screen layer is opaque at a given pixel,
> the COLDATA fixed color ($2132) is used instead.
common_pattern=disable_BG3_on_main_screen_via_$212C|enable_BG3_on_sub_screen_via_$212D|enable_color_math_for_BG1_via_$2131.D0|now_BG1_pixels_blend_with_BG3_subscreen_below

# =============================================================================
# === HDMA CELL FORMAT DEEP DIVE ==============================================
# =============================================================================

[SECTION:hdma_cell_format_detail]
cell_structure=N_byte_(line_count_+_repeat_flag)_followed_by_data_bytes
n_byte_layout=
  D7=continue_mode|0=write_value_ONCE_then_skip_(n-1)_lines|1=write_value_EVERY_line_for_n_lines
  D6..D0=line_count_value_(1..127)_or_special_$00_(table_terminator)
  $80=special_case|continue_mode_for_128_lines
data_bytes_per_cell=depends_on_DMA_mode_in_$43x0.D2..D0|1,_2,_or_4_bytes
table_terminator=cell_with_n_byte_=_$00|HDMA_channel_disabled_for_rest_of_frame_when_encountered
> An HDMA table is a sequence of "cells". Each cell starts with a count
> byte that says "for the next N scanlines, do this" — and then the
> data bytes that get written. The high bit of N selects whether the
> data is written every line (continue mode) or just once at the start
> of the count (skip mode).
example_cell_skip_mode=$30_$FF|writes_$FF_to_dest_then_skips_$2F_more_lines_(48_lines_total_with_only_first_changed)
example_cell_continue_mode=$A0_$AA_$BB_$CC_$DD|writes_4_bytes_(mode_4)_every_line_for_$20=32_lines
example_indirect_cell=$10_$3456|writes_pointer_$3456_into_$43x5_$43x6,_then_HDMA_dereferences_through_indirect_bank_$43x7_to_get_actual_data
table_end=$00_terminator_byte|HDMA_channel_disabled_for_rest_of_frame
> Cells can be mixed (skip mode and continue mode in the same table).
> A common HDMA table for a gradient sky:
>   $80 $20  ; 128 lines, write $20 to color register
>   $80 $30  ; next 128 lines, write $30
>   $00      ; end
> But this only writes 256 lines total which exceeds the visible area;
> the last cell is processed but the channel ends naturally at vblank.

[SECTION:hdma_indirect_explanation]
when_used=when_data_per_scanline_is_too_large_to_inline_in_table_or_when_data_lives_in_a_different_bank
indirect_bank_register=$43x7|24bit_pointer_uses_this_bank_with_offset_loaded_from_table
mechanism=N_byte_followed_by_16bit_pointer_(LE)_into_indirect_bank|HDMA_then_reads_data_from_(bank<<16)|pointer_each_line
example=for_per_scanline_color_math_color_load_a_2byte_pointer_then_read_$2132_data_from_separate_buffer
> Indirect mode lets each cell point to a separate data buffer. This
> is essential for tables that need to update large amounts of data
> per line, or for tables that live in ROM while the per-line data
> lives in WRAM (computed each frame). The indirect format costs one
> extra DMA pass per line transition (16 cycles), so it's slower per
> active scanline.

[SECTION:hdma_use_cases_concrete]
use_1=per_scanline_color_($2132)|gradient_skies|underwater_color_shifts
use_2=per_scanline_BG_scroll_($210D_$210E_etc)|wave_distortion|parallax|interlaced_scroll
use_3=per_scanline_window_position_($2126_$2127)|round_iris_transitions|spotlight_effects
use_4=per_scanline_Mode_7_matrix_(M7A_M7B_M7C_M7D)|Mode_7_perspective_(F-Zero,_Pilotwings)|axis_warp
use_5=per_scanline_color_math_settings_($2131)|select_which_layers_blend_per_line
use_6=per_scanline_BG_offset_($210D_$210E)|moving_wave_effects
use_7=per_scanline_$2105_BGMODE|mid_screen_BG_mode_change|rare,_dangerous,_used_by_Kirby's_Dreamland_3
use_8=per_scanline_brightness_($2100)|fade_per_scanline_for_dramatic_effect
> The most famous use is probably Mode 7 perspective projection, where
> M7A/B/C/D are HDMA'd with values that change per scanline to make a
> flat plane appear as a perspective-correct floor. Each scanline gets a
> different scale factor, simulating depth.


# =============================================================================
# === SA-1 (SUPER ACCELERATOR) — DETAILED =====================================
# =============================================================================

[SECTION:sa1_overview_v3]
chip_name=SA-1|aka=Super_Accelerator_1|map_mode_byte=$23
core=65C816_at_10.74_MHz_(4x_main_CPU_speed_at_default)
internal_ram_iram=2_KiB|battery_backable
bwram=up_to_2_MiB_battery_backed
arithmetic_unit=hardware_16x16_multiply_+_16/16_divide_+_40bit_cumulative_sum
char_conversion=hardware_unit_converts_bitmap_to_planar_tile_format_via_DMA
varlen_bit=ROM_treated_as_bit_stream_for_huffman_LZ_decoding
custom_dma=transfers_with_charconv_between_ROM_BWRAM_IRAM
hv_timer=programmable_position_or_linear_18bit
super_mmc=8_block_x_8_Mbit_(1_MiB)_bank_switching_=_64_Mbit_max_ROM
games_using=Kirby_Super_Star|Kirby's_Dream_Land_3|Super_Mario_RPG|Marvelous|PGA_European_Tour|Jikkyou_Oshaberi_Parodius|Mini_4WD|Power_Rangers_Zeo|Pebble_Beach_Golf|Itoi_Bass_Fishing|Shogi_Saikyo|various_strategy_RPGs
> SA-1 is a second 65C816 living inside the cartridge, running 4x faster
> than the main CPU. Both CPUs share the ROM and BWRAM, so the SA-1 can
> be doing physics or AI calculations while the main CPU handles graphics
> uploads and game logic. The two CPUs communicate through mailbox
> registers and IRQ lines. The SA-1 also has hardware accelerators for
> multiply, divide, character conversion (bitmap-to-tile), and variable-
> length bit decoding (for compression).
parallel_speedup=games_can_split_work_between_main_and_SA1_for_5x_overall_perf_when_pipelined

[SECTION:sa1_arbitration_detailed]
mode_both_idle=both_CPUs_run_at_full_speed_in_their_own_resources
mode_main_only_in_rom=main_runs_at_2.68MHz_(or_3.58MHz_if_FastROM)
mode_sa1_only_in_rom=SA-1_runs_at_10.74MHz
mode_both_in_rom=arbitrated|main=2.68MHz|SA-1=5.37MHz_(half_speed_due_to_alternation)
mode_both_in_bwram=main=2.68MHz|SA-1=5.37MHz
mode_main_in_iram=main_can_access_iram_at_main_clock_speed
mode_sa1_in_iram=SA-1_at_10.74MHz_in_iram
collision_handling=automatic_via_internal_arbiter|stalls_one_CPU_one_cycle_when_simultaneous
fastrom_disabled_for_main=in_SA-1_carts_main_CPU_is_locked_to_2.68MHz_(no_$420D_FastROM)
> Two CPUs sharing one ROM bus need arbitration. The SA-1 chip's internal
> arbiter handles this transparently — both CPUs THINK they have free
> access, but in reality the slower main CPU often "wins" priority when
> there's a conflict, so the SA-1 only effectively runs at 5.37 MHz when
> both are hammering ROM. The 4x speedup is the BEST case (SA-1 alone
> in ROM while main is in WRAM).

[SECTION:sa1_iram_detailed]
size=2_KiB
main_view=$00..$3F:$3000..$37FF|$80..$BF:$3000..$37FF|same_2KB_window
sa1_view_zero_page=$00..$3F:$0000..$07FF|$80..$BF:$0000..$07FF
sa1_view_normal=$00..$3F:$3000..$37FF|$80..$BF:$3000..$37FF
write_protect_main_side=$2229_SIWP|each_bit_protects_256_byte_page
write_protect_sa1_side=$222A_CIWP|same_layout
purpose=high_speed_scratch_for_SA-1|message_passing_buffer|stack_for_SA-1
> IRAM is the SA-1's local fast scratch RAM. It's tiny (2 KiB) but
> ultra-fast and accessible from BOTH CPUs at different addresses. The
> SA-1 sees it at $0000..$07FF (its zero page) AND $3000..$37FF (where
> the main CPU also sees it). This dual mapping is convenient: the
> SA-1 can use IRAM as direct page (0..255) for very fast scratchpad
> access, while still letting the main CPU read results at $3000..$37FF.
> Write protection is per-256-byte-page from each side, so you can
> dedicate certain pages to "main writes only" or "SA-1 writes only".

[SECTION:sa1_bwram_detailed]
size_max=2_MiB
full_window_main=$40..$4F:$0000..$FFFF|1_MiB_linearly_addressable
extended_window=$60..$6F|same_BWRAM_but_in_BITMAP_format_(2bpp_or_4bpp_pixels_addressable_per_pixel)
image_window_8K=$00..$3F:$6000..$7FFF|$80..$BF:$6000..$7FFF|sliding_window_of_8KiB
selector_main_side=$2224_BMAPS|D4..D0=block_index_0..31|each_block=8_KiB
selector_sa1_side=$2225_BMAP|D6..D0=block_index_0..127_in_extended|D7=SW46_extended_mode
write_enable_main=$2226_SBWE
write_enable_sa1=$2227_CBWE
write_protect=$2228_BWPA|D3..D0=protected_size_2K_4K_8K_16K_32K_64K_128K_256K_512K_1024K_2048K
> BWRAM is the cart's work RAM, up to 2 MiB. The MAIN CPU has two views:
> a full window in banks $40..$4F (covers 1 MiB linearly, the most common
> case) and an 8 KiB sliding window at $6000..$7FFF in low banks. The
> sliding window is selected by BMAPS — write a block index (0..31) and
> the window shows that 8 KiB block. Used to map portions of BWRAM into
> the easily-accessible $6000..$7FFF region for code that doesn't have
> long pointers.
extended_bitmap_view=at_$60..$6F|when_BBF_$223F.D0=0_pixels_are_4bpp_(half_a_byte_each)|when_BBF_=1_pixels_are_2bpp_(quarter_byte_each)
bitmap_pixel_addressing_4bpp=byte_offset=(y*row_stride+x)/2|nibble=(x&1)?low:high
bitmap_pixel_addressing_2bpp=byte_offset=(y*row_stride+x)/4|nibble_select_top_to_bottom_within_byte
> Extended bitmap view is a SA-1 trick: the same BWRAM bytes are
> reinterpreted as pixels rather than tile data. Useful for using BWRAM
> as a frame buffer for software rendering, similar to how Super FX uses
> its game-pak RAM.

[SECTION:sa1_super_mmc_bank_switching]
total_rom_max=64_Mbit_=_8_MiB
blocks=8|each_8_Mbit_(1_MiB)
windows=4_x_8_Mbit
window_C=$C0..$CF|selector=$2220_CXB|D2..D0_=_block_index|init=$00
window_D=$D0..$DF|selector=$2221_DXB|init=$01
window_E=$E0..$EF|selector=$2222_EXB|init=$02
window_F=$F0..$FF|selector=$2223_FXB|init=$03
mirror_C_lorom=$00..$1F:$8000..$FFFF|sequential_LoROM_style_access_to_window_C_block
mirror_D_lorom=$20..$3F:$8000..$FFFF
mirror_E_lorom=$80..$9F:$8000..$FFFF
mirror_F_lorom=$A0..$BF:$8000..$FFFF
cbm_flag_d7=in_each_block_register|when_=1_lorom_mirror_uses_block_data|when_=0_lorom_mirror_uses_default_image
mirror_layout_quirk=in_lorom_mirror_each_S_CPU_bank_holds_one_32K_half_of_a_real_block_bank|so_2_S_CPU_banks_=_1_block_bank
> The Super MMC is a 4-window bank switcher. The CPU can see 4 different
> 1 MiB blocks at any time at $C0..$FF. Default config maps blocks 0-3
> at the four windows, which gives access to the first 4 MiB. To reach
> blocks 4-7 the game writes to CXB/DXB/EXB/FXB at runtime to swap a
> window's contents. The lorom mirror at $00..$3F gives the main CPU
> access to the same data via 32-KiB-per-bank addressing for code that
> uses LoROM-style pointers.

