# =============================================================================
# === BITPLANE FORMAT — DETAILED PER COLOR DEPTH ==============================
# =============================================================================

[SECTION:bitplane_overview]
storage=tile_pixels_stored_in_PLANES_not_packed_pixels
plane_n=byte_holding_bit_n_of_8_horizontal_pixels
tile_size_8x8=always|fundamental_unit_of_PPU_rendering
larger_tiles=composed_from_4_8x8_tiles_in_2x2_arrangement_(16x16)_or_more
sprite_compositing=larger_sprite_sizes_use_consecutive_tile_numbers_in_2x2_or_4x4_arrangement
> The SNES (and most 80s/90s consoles) stores tile pixels in a "planar"
> format rather than packed pixels. Instead of storing the 4-bit color
> value of pixel 0 in nibble 0 of byte 0, the FIRST byte holds bit 0 of
> all 8 pixels in row 0, the SECOND byte holds bit 1 of all 8 pixels,
> etc. This is friendlier to the PPU's parallel bit-extraction hardware
> but harder to work with in software. To form pixel N's full color
> index, you take bit N from each plane byte, OR them together with
> appropriate shifts.

[SECTION:bitplane_1bpp]
size_per_tile=8_bytes
colors=2
layout=byte_0=row_0_plane_0|byte_1=row_1_plane_0|...|byte_7=row_7_plane_0
each_byte_msb=leftmost_pixel
each_byte_lsb=rightmost_pixel
> The simplest format. Used for monochrome fonts. Each row is one byte
> where bit 7 is the leftmost pixel and bit 0 is the rightmost. To get
> pixel X (0..7) of row Y: (byte[Y] >> (7-X)) & 1.

[SECTION:bitplane_2bpp]
size_per_tile=16_bytes
colors=4
layout=interleaved_pairs|byte_0=row_0_plane_0|byte_1=row_0_plane_1|byte_2=row_1_plane_0|byte_3=row_1_plane_1|...
pixel_extract=color_index=plane_0_bit|((plane_1_bit)<<1)
used_in=BG3_in_Mode_1|BG3_BG4_in_Mode_0|GameBoy_native_format
> The first SNES "real" color depth. Two interleaved planes per row,
> alternating plane 0 and plane 1 byte by byte. To get pixel X of row
> Y you need both byte (2*Y) and byte (2*Y+1).

[SECTION:bitplane_3bpp]
size_per_tile=24_bytes
colors=8
layout=2bpp_block_(16_bytes)_followed_by_1bpp_block_(8_bytes)_for_plane_2
pixel_extract=color_index=2bpp_index|((plane_2_bit)<<2)
used_in=NOT_a_native_PPU_mode|games_use_this_to_save_ROM_space_then_unpack_to_4bpp_at_runtime
common_in=Final_Fantasy_VI|some_RPGs_with_8_color_sprites
> Not directly supported by the PPU. Games store sprites as 3bpp in ROM
> to save space (3 bytes per row vs 4 for 4bpp = 25% savings), then
> upload to a temp buffer and unpack to 4bpp before DMAing to VRAM.
> The unpack just zero-extends each pixel from 3 to 4 bits (sprites
> are 4bpp native on SNES, so the high color index bits stay 0).

[SECTION:bitplane_4bpp]
size_per_tile=32_bytes
colors=16
layout=two_2bpp_blocks_back_to_back|first_2bpp_block_=_planes_0_1|second_2bpp_block_=_planes_2_3
each_2bpp_block=16_bytes_with_interleaved_planes
pixel_extract=index=plane0_bit|(plane1_bit<<1)|(plane2_bit<<2)|(plane3_bit<<3)
used_in=BG1_BG2_in_Mode_1|BG1_in_Mode_2|BG2_in_Mode_3|BG1_BG2_in_Mode_5|OBJ_(sprites)_native
> The most common SNES format. 32 bytes per tile, 16 colors per pixel,
> sprites are always this format. The two 2bpp blocks each take their
> 16 bytes consecutively, so byte 0 is row 0 plane 0, byte 1 is row 0
> plane 1, ..., byte 15 is row 7 plane 1, byte 16 is row 0 plane 2,
> byte 17 is row 0 plane 3, etc.

[SECTION:bitplane_8bpp]
size_per_tile=64_bytes
colors=256
layout=four_2bpp_blocks|planes_0_1|then_2_3|then_4_5|then_6_7
pixel_extract=index_=_OR_of_all_8_plane_bits_with_shifts
used_in=BG1_in_Mode_3|BG1_in_Mode_4|Mode_7_(but_with_different_layout)
> 8 bits per pixel = full 256-color palette access for that BG. Used
> for high-color title screens, large detailed background images. The
> direct color mode of $2130.D0 lets you bypass the palette entirely
> and use the 8 bits directly as RGB (with 3-3-2 or similar layouts).

[SECTION:bitplane_mode7]
size_per_tile=64_bytes
colors=256
layout=NOT_planar|each_byte_is_one_complete_8bit_pixel|row_0_pixel_0_to_pixel_7_in_bytes_0..7
storage_in_vram=interleaved_with_tilemap|tilemap_byte_in_low_VRAM_chip|chr_byte_in_high_VRAM_chip
> Mode 7 breaks the planar pattern entirely. Each byte is just a packed
> 8-bit pixel — much simpler. The PPU's Mode 7 hardware uses a
> different fetching scheme that takes advantage of this. The tilemap
> entries are interleaved with chr data in VRAM (because the PPU has
> two physical VRAM chips and can fetch one byte from each in parallel).

# =============================================================================
# === RNG ALGORITHM AND COMMON GAMING SUBSYSTEMS ==============================
# =============================================================================

[SECTION:rng_common_patterns]
linear_congruential_generator=most_common|formula_=_(state*A+C)_mod_M|each_call_advances_state_by_one
fibonacci_lfsr=less_common|state_is_a_shift_register|each_call_taps_specific_bits_and_shifts
table_based=precomputed_table_in_ROM|index_advances_each_call|wraps_around
hardware_assisted=use_$4214_$4215_(divide_remainder)_or_$4216_$4217_(multiply)_after_some_op_for_unpredictability
> Most SNES RNGs are simple LCGs with state in WRAM. The classic
> formula is: rng = (rng * 5 + 1) & $FF, or similar. Some games use
> a 16-bit LFSR with taps at specific bits for better quality. Some
> games stir entropy from $4216 (which can hold leftover hardware
> multiply results from earlier in the frame) for unpredictability.
example_8bit_lcg=LDA_rng|ASL|EOR_rng|ASL|EOR_rng|STA_rng|RTS|generates_sequence_with_period_255
example_with_hwm=LDA_$4216|EOR_rng|STA_rng|simple_entropy_mixing_using_leftover_multiply_result

